<1ST_LINE>r a AM-China-Missiles     03-28 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Missiles,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China-Missiles Plot Figure Sentenced; Lawyer Says He Acted Out of
Fear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese immigrant was sentenced Monday to
a year in prison for acting as the middleman in a missile-smuggling
plot involving a high-ranking member of the Chinese mission to the
United Nations.
   Shang-Yao Chi, 65, pleaded guilty Dec. 10 to conspiring to
illegally export 10 TOW II missiles to China.
   Defense attorney Alan Zegas said Chi went along with the plot
out of fear that his brother, an anti-communist like Chi, would be
harmed while in a Chinese prison.
   Chi was arrested in a Customs Service sting operation and
charged with being a middleman between a government informant and
the U.N. diplomat, who has since left the country, prosecutors said.
   U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise could have sentenced
Chi to five years in prison. But he gave a the year-and-a-day
sentence because of what the government called his ``exemplary''
cooperation in the investigation.
   The U.S. government has taken no diplomatic action against
mission officials, and the Chinese government has denied any
involvement in the plot.
   Chi was born in China and lived in nationalist Taiwan for 30
years before joining his daughter in New York City in 1979, Zegas
said. Chi's father was killed during the Cultural Revolution by
Chinese authorities, the lawyer said.
   Zegas said Chi's brother was imprisoned because of his
anti-communist sympathies. ``If (Chi) didn't go through with the
plan, he felt his brother would be murdered,'' Zegas said after
sentencing.
</TEXT>
