<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GirlsClubSuit     03-28 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Girls Club Suit,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Boys Clubs Of America Can't Add Girls to Name _ Yet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday barred the Boys Clubs of
America from adding ``and Girls'' to its name pending the outcome
of a lawsuit by the Girls Clubs of America.
   The Girls Clubs of America filed a trademark-infringement suit
last month to prevent the Boys Clubs organization from renaming
itself the Boys and Girls Clubs of America.
   The Boys Clubs has said that the organization has about 300,000
girls among it 1.3 million members, and their parents are demanding
the name change.
   U.S. District Judge Kenneth Conboy granted the Girls Clubs of
America request to block the national organization from changing
its name for now, but he refused to issue a similar order against
local Boys Club groups.
   Margaret Gates, national executive director of the Girls Clubs
of America, said the Girls Clubs' identity and fund-raising are
threatened by the Boys Clubs' name-change.
   She said Monday that she was pleased with Conboy's ruling but
that local Girls Clubs will be encouraged to sue if the local Boys
Clubs in their areas change their name.
   Ms. Gatessaid the Girls Clubs of America serves about 250,000
girls, and about 40,000 boys participate in its activities.
</TEXT>
