<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScotusNotebook     03-28 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus Notebook,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newest Justice Skipped High School To Attend Trials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One aspect of Supreme Court Justice Anthony M.
Kennedy's past that Senate investigators apparently missed was his
high school absenteeism.
   Kennedy, who joined the court Feb. 18, ``confessed'' while
discussing his childhood in Sacramento, Calif., during a recent
interview with the court's ``Docket Sheet'' publication.
   ``My dad was a lawyer, a great lawyer and I wanted to follow
him,'' the justice said. ``He was a sole practitioner and he used
to take me with him to hear him try his cases. He didn't think
school was very important; he would take me.
   ``Even in high school, he'd say, `We have to go now, we're going
for two weeks for a trial.' I would just leave school because he
would insist that I go with him. I probably saw 10 trials before I
was ever out of high school. I loved it.''
   No word in yet on Kennedy's truancy as a Stanford undergraduate
or as a Harvard law student.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Networks Forbidden to Televise Kennedy's Investiture</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Efforts by the television networks to provide live coverage of
the ceremony in which Kennedy became the 104th justice in the
court's history failed.
   Despite allowing greater access to cameras in various public
portions of the court building, and granting more on-camera
interviews from their chambers than in past years, the justices
apparently have drawn the line at the courtroom door.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kennedy Mum on Key Disqualification</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court last week cited a lack of a quorum in refusing to kill
a lawsuit stemming from an armed confrontation between Indians and
federal agents at Wounded Knee, S.D.
   Four justices, including Kennedy, disqualified themselves from
the case, and the remaining five justices automatically upheld a
lower court ruling that clears the way for a trial in which former
federal and military officials are named as defendants.
   Three members _ Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices
Antonin Scalia and Sandra Day O'Connor _ had disqualified
themselves when the case was granted review, before Kennedy joined
the court. His disqualification came as something of a surprise.
   His office informed reporters that as a rule, Kennedy will not
explain such actions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scalia Cites Joys of Being Evasive</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   During a recent question-and-answer session with George
Washington University law students, Justice Scalia proved a popular
guest despite his reluctance to give substantive replies to several
queries.
   Asked why Supreme Court justices seem more hesitant to talk
about substantive issues than lower court judges, Scalia said
justices are more likely to be quoted in the news media _ thus
causing controversy.
   ``The nice thing about this job is I'm not running for
anything,'' Scalia added. ``There's nothing anybody can give me I
don't already have.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Powell on Kennedy: ``Better Qualified Than I''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Retired Justice Lewis F. Powell, replaced by Kennedy, has high
praise for his successor.
   In a recent interview with the Cleveland Plain Dealer, Powell
noted Kennedy's long career as a federal appellate judge and added:
``I think he's better qualified than I am. I had none of that
experience. That helps you tremendously here.''
   Powell was a longtime trial lawyer in Richmond, Va., before he
joined the court in 1972.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retired Justices To Be Moved Out of Court Building?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Powell, although spending considerable time in Richmond these
days helping out the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, still
maintains an office in the Supreme Court's stately building on
Capitol Hill.
   So does retired Chief Justice Warren E. Burger.
   But a little-noticed bill introduced in December by Sen. Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., would change that.
   The proposed legislation authorizes construction of a new
judiciary building at the foot of Capitol Hill, on land currently
used as a parking lot for Senate employees.
   The building would house the Administrative Office of the U.S.
Courts, the Federal Judicial Center, the Judicial Panel on
Multi-District Litigation, the U.S. Sentencing Commission and
offices for ``retired U.S. Supreme Court justices.''
</TEXT>
