<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Simon'sStand     03-28 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Simon's Stand,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon's Lack of Victories Pushes Him Toward Reassessment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon said all he expected in
Michigan's Democratic presidential caucuses was a respectable
showing.
   He got 2 percent. But aides put the best face on even that.
   They said the results, while far from what Simon wanted, made
his strategy of expending little effort in Michigan and focusing on
the Wisconsin primary more important than ever.
   Simon was saying after Michigan what he's been saying for weeks
now _ that the Democratic race is so muddled that he's got as much
right as anyone to hang in there.
   ``We're clearly headed toward a wide-open convention,'' Simon
said.
   Jesse Jackson's victory over Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
in Michigan increased Simon's attractiveness as an alternative,
said Chris Sautter, the Illinois senator's Wisconsin campaign
coordinator.
   ``Now, we're in a position where we can be considered a serious
contender here,'' Sautter said Sunday. ``It underscores the whole
idea of an open convention.''
   Simon acknowledges, though, that Wisconsin's primary, a week
from Tuesday, is a key test.
   ``In a state like Wisconsin, where politics is synonymous with
the word `progressive,' we have the opportunity to communicate that
the Democrats don't have to settle for a weak alternative,''
campaign spokesman Terry Michael said. ``We need to make that case
in Wisconsin.''
   What happens if Simon loses?
   ``We have to reassess at that point,'' Michael said.
   Even longtime supporters said Simon must win in Wisconsin or
think seriously about abandoning his quest for the White House.
   ``The big questions are whether his campaign after Wisconsin is
credible and raising money,'' said Rep. Richard Durbin, D-Ill. ``If
the answer to those two things is `yes,' he'll be pressing
forward.''
   Simon's only victory so far was at home in the Illinois primary.
   He has placed third, fourth or fifth in most other primaries and
caucuses, sat out Super Tuesday races in 20 states and ranks fifth
among five candidates in delegates to the Democratic National
Convention in July.
   ``He's by no means out of it, and I'm sticking with him as long
as he wants to stay in,'' said Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., voicing
sentiments of aides speaking for Reps. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, and
Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y.
   Yet Evans hedged when asked if he thinks Simon still has a
chance of becoming the Democratic nominee.
   ``It's very hard to say what's going to happen,'' Evans said.
``Strange things happen occasionally at conventions.''
   Other allies, though, said they have counseled Simon against
hurting his chances for re-election to the Senate by clinging to a
hopeless cause.
   ``I think he will continue to look at it as long as he doesn't
incur more debt,'' said Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., one of those who
urged Simon to bypass the Super Tuesday states.
   `You don't want to have a big debt when you're looking at
1990,'' Dixon said. ``I can't tell you what his present financial
shape is. But it's hoped he can walk away from this thing pretty
much as a wash.''
   Simon has repaid more than a half-million dollars' worth of bank
loans and he expects to use 20 staff members and spend $100,000 for
television advertising in the Wisconsin campaign, spokesman Michael
said.
</TEXT>
