<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FishingTips     03-28 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fishing Tips,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Fishing Methods Spread to Poor Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Research Council is out to prove
the Chinese proverb: ``Give a man a fish and you feed him once;
teach him how to fish and you feed him for life.''
   The council has seized on the idea _ an oft-quoted aphorism in
foreign aid circles _ and come up with a lot of ideas, from
pedal-power fishing craft more efficient than rowboats to
artificial mangrove branches made of aluminum wire bathed in
concrete. The fake branches provide the kind of surface that baby
oysters like to hang on, useful in places where cutting mangroves
is illegal.
   The council has recently published a book-length manual of
low-price fishing methods, called ``Fishing Technologies for
Developing Countries.'' It's not for big commercial fleets but for
traditional fishermen who account for a quarter of the world's
catch, about 20 million tons a year. They provide most of the fish
in Africa and Asia, but a much smaller proportion in Latin America.
   An estimated 200 million people depend on them.
   First thing most fishermen need is a boat. The high quality
hardwoods many peoples traditionally use have become dearer and
harder to find. Plywood is not too expensive, and plywood
catamarans developed in Western Samoa have lasted almost a decade.
Plastic tubes and ferro-concrete are ugly, but cheap and durable.
   The Japanese have found another use for six-inch plastic tubes.
Two of them, 30 inches long, are laid side by side with a two-inch
concrete plug that bisects them: the result offers four fatal dens
to unsuspecting octopi.
   In Venezuela they make octopus pots from old rubber tires.
   A boat has to move. Sailing has declined among Third World
fishermen in recent years, the council says, and instead there have
been ideas for cheap fuel: alcohol made from cassava (manioc) in
Fiji, coconut oil for mixing with diesel fuel in the Philippines.
The coconut oil clogged the fuel filters, and the Filipinos have
been trying to use charcoal from coconut shells to make gas for
fuel.
   Several ideas, some more effective, have come from the
Philippines. The academy says a system for cultured mussels
developed at Sapian Bay, on the island of Panay, uses rope-webs
floated from rafts instead of the more usual stakes driven into the
mud. It raised mussel production to more than five times the old
method.
   Advanced technology need not be too expensive, the council
points out. Fish are sensitive to the temperature of the water, and
move when it changes. A shift of one degree or even less can
indicate a place where fish may cluster. Ordinary thermometers are
not sensitive enough, but a simple electronic thermometer can show
differences of a tenth of a degree and cost less than $100.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 0122EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Fed-InterestRates     03-28 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fed-Interest Rates,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed-Watchers See New Concern About Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve has been trying to keep
the economic recovery alive following the October stock market
collapse, but many economists believe it is starting to worry more
about rising inflationary pressures.
   These analysts think the switch will mean that interest rates,
including mortgage rates, will not fall further and actually will
climb slightly in coming months.
   The central bank's top policy makers will meet behind closed
doors Tuesday to review monetary strategy. The decisions made by
the Federal Open Market Committee will not be revealed until
mid-May.
   While analysts are not looking for major policy changes to come
out of the meeting, they said recent comments by Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan indicate that the central bank has begun to
worry once again about inflationary pressures.
   The central bank tries to balance the competing economic goals
of supplying enough money to the financial system to keep the
economy expanding while guarding against supplying so much money
that inflation is rekindled.
   In congressional testimony earlier this month, Greenspan said he
was worried that inflationary bottlenecks could develop in U.S.
industries later this year.
   Greenspan said there were no signs of inflationary troubles at
present, but that the central bank would act fast at the first sign
that the economy was overheating. For the Fed, fighting inflation
means raising interest rates.
   Before the Oct. 19 collapse of stock prices, the Fed had been
tightening credit conditions out of fear that a weaker dollar would
increase U.S. inflation.
   But following the record 508-point drop in stock prices, the
central bank moved quickly to ease credit in order to keep the
country out of a recession.
   Analysts said they believed Greenspan's recent comments were an
indication the central bank is once again switching gears.
   ``I am not looking for any more interest rate declines. I think
the Fed is worried again about inflation,'' said David Seiders,
chief economist of the National Association of Home Builders.
   Mortgage rates, which hit a high of 11.58 percent immediately
before the stock crash last October, dipped into single-digits
earlier this year, falling to 9.84 percent in early February.
   But in recent weeks rates have been rising again, averaging 9.99
percent last week, according to a nationwide survey by the Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Seiders predicted that mortgage rates could top 11 percent by
the end of the year. Other analysts agreed that a variety of
interest rates would likely head higher in coming months,
especially if economic growth rebounds.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist for The Boston Co., said he
believed the central bank would make no outright change in policy
at its March meeting but would stand ready to tighten credit
conditions later in the year.
   ``If the economy picks up steam and produces inflationary
pressures, I wouldn't rule out a tightening move later this
spring,'' he said. ``The central bank is making people aware that
if inflation does heat up, they would tighten.''
   Lyle Gramley, chief economist for the Mortgage Bankers
Association, said he expected mortgage rates to fluctuate between
10 percent to 10.5 percent over the next two months as the Fed
watches for further indications of how the economy is performing.
   One key indicator the Fed will be watching is the monthly
unemployment report. The jobless rate dropped to an 8{-year low of
5.7 percent in February and Greenspan indicated that it was
unlikely the rate could fall much farther without triggering
inflationary pressures.
   ``If economic growth is too strong, the unemployment rate could
drop down into a danger zone which would generate an upturn in wage
increases,'' said Gramley, a former member of the Fed board. ``Once
you get that under way, it is very hard to stop and even harder to
reverse. That is what you want to avoid if you can.''
   Some economists said that the Fed would hold off making any
major change in direction until late next month when the government
releases its first estimate of overall economic growth, as measured
by the gross national product, for the January-March quarter.
   Roger Brinner, an economist with Data Resources Inc., said that
if growth was really weak in the first quarter, the Fed might be
persuaded that a further dose of easing was needed, especially
since this is a presidential election year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
