<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 0124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuperstarScientist Bjt   03-28 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Superstar Scientist, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Houston, Berkeley, Woo Hot Superconductivity Researcher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEWART TAGGART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Houston has suffered low oil prices, a troubled
space program and the near-exodus of its pro football team. Now it
wants to avoid another hit: the departure of superstar
superconductivity physicist Paul Chu.
   ``I think we need to be sure we don't drop the ball,'' says City
Councilman Jim Greenwood. ``It's probably more important to keep
Paul Chu as it was to keep the Houston Oilers.''
   Superconductivity, the potential of some materials to carry
electricity without energy loss, has become one of the hottest
areas in science today. And Chu, a 47-year-old University of
Houston physics professor, has become one of the hottest
researchers in superconductivity.
   The research promises to spawn tremendous advances in industry,
with applications in computers, transmission of electricity and
transportation, although many observers feel it will be decades
before any significant commercial products result.
   Early last year, Chu announced that his experiments with
materials showed evidence of superconductivity at temperatures
warmer than ever before achieved. The discovery brought
energy-saving practical applications within closer range.
   The news spread quickly and made Chu an overnight celebrity in
scientific circles. Job offers began rolling in. One university has
promised him a $20 million research package if he moves there, said
Chu, who isn't naming the school.
   The rumors have prompted Houston businessman Tom Wright to
organize a letter-writing campaign asking small business owners to
urge Chu to stay.
   ``We should go out of our way to make sure he likes it here,''
Wright said. ``Wherever major discoveries are made, industry grows
around it. ... In my mind, superconductivity will be bigger to this
area than NASA ever was.''
   Chu says he has made no decision, but is considering an offer
from the University of California-Berkeley. On March 6, the San
Francisco Examiner reported Chu had accepted a teaching and
research post there, and Berkeley officials continue to claim Chu
has taken the job.
   ``We are expecting him to come to Berkeley this fall,'' said
Geoffrey Chew, Berkeley's dean of physical sciences. ``He came here
last week, and confirmed that he had accepted the offer.''
   In recent weeks, Chu has not responded to numerous interview
requests. Through his secretary, Mike Albert, he says he remains
undecided.
   ``Paul has been agonizing over this decision for about a year
now,'' Roy Weinstein, dean of the University of Houston college of
Natural Sciences and Mathematics, said last week.
   Among the attractions of Berkeley for Chu are the university's
prestige, the favorable California weather and the closer proximity
to family members who live in California, Weinstein said.
   Since his major discovery, Chu has been appointed to the newly
created T.L.L. Temple Chair at the University of Houston, funded by
a $1.5 million endowment. His salary has been raised and he has
been named director of the Texas Center of Superconductivity at
University of Houston, a $30 million research unit to be built at
the university.
   ``I think that the superconductivity center is more important to
him than anything else,'' said University of Houston President
Richard Van Horn. ``We have perhaps more people working in
superconductivity than anywhere else.''
   Houston's relatively undiversified energy-based economy was hit
hard by the 1986 fall of oil prices. And operations of the nation's
space program, and the nearby Johnson Space Center here, came to a
virtual halt with the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger.
   The city's confidence was further battered last year by the near
departure of the Houston Oilers to Jacksonville, Fla. The team
eventually signed a 10-year lease to remain in Houston.
   Weinstein says he believes Chu will split his time between
California and Houston, but says the strain of such an arrangement
may be difficult for the quiet researcher.
   ``It's a question of whether he can do it,'' Weinstein said.
``He will have to confront it, test it, and see.''
</TEXT>
