<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 0149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-IowaDemocrats     03-28 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iowa Democrats,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Gains in Latest Step in Iowa Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis gained and Jesse Jackson
received a smaller boost as Iowa Democrats went through the latest
step in their lengthy process of choosing Democratic National
Convention delegates.
   Richard Gephardt, whose hopes had surged with a victory in last
month's Iowa precinct caucuses, faltered in the latest test
following poor showings in other states.
   ``It confirms what's going on nationally,'' said Bonnie
Campbell, Iowa Democratic chairwoman.
   Party activists over the weekend held county caucuses where they
elected delegates to congressional district conventions in May and
the state convention next summer. At those meetings they will elect
52 of the state's 58 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta. The state has six ``super delegates,'' party
leaders who automatically are delegates.
   With 97 of the state's 99 counties reporting results of their
conventions, Dukakis had 28.7 percent of the delegates to
Gephardt's 27.9 percent. Illinois Sen. Paul Simon was third with
26.4 percent, based on a strong showing in counties along the
border of his home state.
   Jackson pulled in 13.1 percent of the delegates, improving on
his performance in last month's precinct caucuses, while 3.9
percent remained uncommitted.
   In last month's precinct caucuses, Gephardt got 31 percent,
Simon 27 percent, Dukakis 22 percent and Jackson 9 percent.
   Dukakis backers had been quietly lobbying supporters of other
candidates to switch and unite behind a front-runner.
   ``I'm telling our people to treat everyone like you would your
next date,'' said Jerry Crawford, a Dukakis organizer. ``But for
some people it isn't time to get engaged yet.''
   The Dukakis forces targeted backers of former Arizona Gov. Bruce
Babbitt, who has dropped from the race, and succeeded in picking up
support.
   ``It looks like those people who defected, Dukakis picked up the
lion's share,'' said Ms. Campbell. ``Jackson picked up a few.''
   Party activists said Gephardt was damaged by his poor
performance in Saturday's Michigan caucuses.
   As word filtered out of Gephardt's third-place Michigan showing,
some of his backers apparently decided not to make the effort to
attend county conventions, many of which ran until the wee hours
Sunday morning.
</TEXT>
