<DOCNO> AP880328-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 0156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MichiganCaucuses     03-28 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Michigan Caucuses,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intense Effort Factor In Jackson Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF HOLYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said he was looking at the votes,
not the color of the voters, in his landslide victory over Michael
Dukakis in the state's presidential caucuses.
   Jackson's commanding 55 percent of the vote far outstripped the
state's black population, which according to the 1980 census is 13
percent.
   As usual, Jackson galvanized the black community, which
responded with a highly organized get-out-the-vote effort for
Saturday's caucuses.
   That provided him with a solid core of support _ but he didn't
stop there. Campaigning in Connecticut on Sunday, Jackson said his
first concern is to ``count the votes, not the color.''
   ``It's a campaign of growth, a campaign of hope,'' he said.
   Mary Holmes, deputy state coordinator for the Jackson campaign,
said, ``What feels so good is that it's a clear-cut victory. It's
all ours. You want to talk about the popular vote? We won that. You
want to talk about the majority of delegates? We won that too.''
   Holmes said the keys to the Jackson victory were the campaign's
plan to turn out the vote for the caucuses, and Jackson himself.
``It's the effect he has on people who hear him,'' she said.
   Her comments were echoed by Michigan House Speaker Gary Owen,
who said ``the major factor was the level of intensity of Jackson
supporters and the lack of intensity of other supporters.''
   Owen, who supports Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., said Sunday
that he had campaigned several days and found ``an overwhelming
lack of enthusiasm'' for any of the candidates except Jackson.
   ``I know there was excitement in seeing a presidential candidate
and hearing a presidential candidate, but I never felt that degree
of intensity among the crowds for those other candidates,'' he said.
   That intensity was reflected in the vote totals, where Jackson
buried Dukakis with 107,689 votes or 55 percent to Dukakis' 55,337
or 28 percent. Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt came in third with
24,995 or 13 percent. Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had 4,069 or 2
percent; and Gore had 3,818 or 2 percent.
   Those totals represented 94 percent of the vote counted. The
state Democratic Party said it would release final figures sometime
today.
   The delegate projections from those results showed Jackson with
74 of the state's 138 committed delegates, Dukakis with 50,
Gephardt 11, and uncommitted 3.
   Michigan also will send 12 uncommitted ``super delegates'' to
the July convention in Atlanta. They are Gov. James Blanchard and
the 11 members of the Democratic National Committee.
   Jackson particularly swamped Dukakis in the predominantly black
1st and 13th congressional districts, which cover Detroit. In the
1st, Jackson had 25,416 compared with 1,809 for Dukakis, while in
the 13th he had 17,725 to Dukakis's 1,539.
   However, if those figures are subtracted from the two
candidates' totals, Jackson still comes out ahead, 64,548 to 51,989.
   State Rep. Alma Stallworth, a Democrat from Detroit, said she
thinks those figures represent ``a lot of young people and new
voters who got involved for the first time.''
   Stallworth said the highly organized Jackson campaign also got a
boost from black churches, which urged people to vote.
   But she pointed out that Jackson also did well in mostly white
districts covering the western, southern and eastern Lower
Peninsula.
   State Rep. Ilona Varga, who supports Jackson, said he carried
her district, which is only 26 percent black, by attracting white
voters.
   ``I think it says something about our people. I think it says
something about our country,'' she said.
   ``He was saying what people wanted to hear,'' said state Sen.
David Holmes, D-Detroit. ``It all boils down to bread-and-butter
issues regardless of race, color or creed. He outworked, outtalked
and outcampaigned the other candidates in all 18 congressional
districts.''
   Zolton Ferency, a former state Democratic Party chairman, said
organized labor leaders liked Gephardt's tough trade stand, but
``his campaign was dying. They didn't want to back a loser.''
   Dukakis, on the other hand, wasn't well-known in Michigan and
had to introduce himself to the state's Democrats and then try to
get them to vote for him, Ferency said.
   Dukakis, he added, wasn't ``the kind of candidate that can
generate instant enthusiasm.''
</TEXT>
