<1ST_LINE>r w PM-IraqiDemonsration     03-28 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraqi Demonsration,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Angered by Chemical Attacks on Kurds Stage Violent
Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 people threw stones and bottles that
broke windows and smashed the front door of the Iraqi embassy in an
angry demonstration against chemical weapons attacks that killed
more than 5,000 Kurds last week.
   But local police said no one was arrested in Sunday's incident.
   A Supreme Court ruling last week knocked down a rule that had
kept all demonstrations, including peaceful ones, at least 500 feet
away from foreign embassies. However, the court still allowed
police to disperse groups congregating near embassies when they
``reasonably believe that a threat to the security or peace of the
embassy is present.''
   Iran has said Iraq used internationally banned poison gas bombs
in a March 20 air raid that killed 5,000 Kurdish villagers. A
leader of Kurdish rebels in the area of northeastern Iraq occupied
by Iran said at least 50 other Kurds were killed and scores wounded
Thursday when Iraqi planes bombed Seyo and Senan villages nearby.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, Cyprus, said the Iraqis used cyanide, mustard and other
unidentified nerve gases in the attacks ``to prevent the people
from joining Iranian combatants.''
   The attacks came in the latest confrontations of the 7{-year war
between Iran and Iraq which began in September 1980. Fighting has
recently intensified in the Kurdistan mountains for control of a
strategic area east of the Kirkuk oil fields, which produces more
than half the oil that finances Iraq's war effort.
   Many Kurds, a semi-nomadic Sunni Moslem people, have been
fighting the Baghdad government for years.
</TEXT>
