<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iacocca Wins Race Among Caucus Write-Ins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca, who
continues to disavow interest in the Democratic Party's
presidential nomination, won the plurality of write-in votes cast
in the Michigan presidential primary.
   Second place went to New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, who also says he
won't seek the party's nomination.
   Other non-candidates and notables also got backing from
write-ins.
   New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, who last week endorsed
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, picked up at least seven votes.
   Candidates who left the race early, Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt
and Deleware Sen. Joe Biden, each pulled minor support from
write-ins.
   So did candidates who battled for the nomination 16 years ago _
Edmund Muskie and George McGovern.
   Even Republican Sen. Robert Dole of Kansas, whose bid for the
GOP nomination is hanging by a frayed thread, received one vote in
the Democratic caucuses.
   And, how about rock star Ozzie Osbourne? Or maybe the Road
Runner's arch enemy Wile E. Coyote?
   They each got one vote. The Road Runner got no votes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Poll Shows Dukakis With Slim Lead Over Jackson In Wisconsin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis holds a slim
lead over Jesse Jackson but many likely Democratic voters are
undecided on a candidate going into Wisconsin's April 5
presidential preference primary, a new poll indicates.
   The Milwaukee Sentinel, in results being released in today's
editions, said the statewide public opinion poll conducted last
week showed Dukakis to be the choice of 28 percent of the likely
Democratic voters.
   Jackson, winner of the Michigan caucus vote Saturday, was the
choice of 25 percent, but another 25 percent of those likely to
vote for a Democrat in the primary were undecided.
   Among other Democratic candidates, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had
9 percent, Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt 7 percent and Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. 4 percent.
   On the Republican side, Vice President George Bush was the
choice of 62 percent of those likely to vote for a Republican,
while Kansas Sen. Robert Dole was the choice of 27 percent. The
Rev. Pat Robertson received 3 percent, and 7 percent were undecided.
   The Sentinel said its telephone survey of 798 randomly-selected
Wisconsin adults was conducted March 17-22.
   Among the sample of 158 people identified as likely to vote in
the Democratic primary, the margin of sampling error was plus or
minus 7.9 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Daily News Poll Shows Bush, Dukakis New York Front-Runners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the New York primary less than a month
away, a recent poll shows Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Vice President George Bush to be the clear favorites among
Democratic and Republican voters across the state. The Daily News
poll, published Sunday, had Dukakis favored by 45 percent of the
Democrats surveyed. His closest rival was Jesse Jackson, preferred
by 29 percent of the Democrats.
   None of the three other active Democratic candidates were
favored by more than 6 percent of the voters who participated in
the survey. Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt was favored by 6
percent, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon by 5 percent and Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore by 5 percent.
   On the Republican side, voters surveyed favored Bush by 68
percent, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole by 23 percent and former television
evangelist Pat Roberson by 4 percent.
   The poll, conducted for the Daily News by Chilton Research
Services of Radnor, Pa., surveyed 528 Democrats and 496 Republicans
who said they intended to vote in the primary. The poll was
conducted between Monday, March 21 and Thursday, March 24 and has a
margin for error of plus or minus 4.5 percentage points.
   Two hundred twenty-five Democratic delegates and 136 GOP
delegates are at stake in the April 19 primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson Pledges Conditional Bush Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Vice President George Bush becomes
the Republican Party's candidate for the presidency, he will have
the support of Pat Robertson.
   Robertson, a former television evangelist and current GOP
hopeful, also said over the weekend that if Bush is elected, he
most likely would not challenge him in 1992 if Bush opted for a
second term.
   ``It will all depend on what George Bush does as president,''
Robertson said in a news conference following a rally of his
supporters. ``Basically I would support the Republican president.
That would not be a wise thing _ to go against the president of
your own party.''
   But until the national convention, Robertson said he is
concentrating on his own campaign, a campaign he admits no longer
is aimed at the White House but at the future.
   And if he is to survive, Robertson told his supporters he must
win his home state's upcoming caucuses.
   Robertson placed third earlier this month behind Bush and Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole in Virginia's non-binding primary. He also was third
in his hometown of Virginia Beach.
</TEXT>
