<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-28 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Ridgeway's magic trick was a hit with
his audience, but it was a bomb as far as police were concerned.
   Ridgeway used the trick during his address on ``The Impact of
Special Events'' before public relations people at a downtown
hotel. He had been invited by Tom Jardine, vice president of public
relations for the Carlson Companies.
   ``The reason why Tom gives me a nice introduction is that I have
this dating book and it's really hot,'' Ridgeway told the group as
he opened a book and a flame magically shot out.
   The group laughed and Ridgeway, a public relations consultant,
finished his talk. But he left the book behind when he left the
hotel Thursday.
   A hotel employee called security guards when he opened the prop
and saw wires and batteries. A guard took it to a basement office,
checked it over and decided it was harmless.
   But hotel officials had second thoughts on Friday and called
police.
   ``There was a strange odor coming from it,'' said Sgt. Rick
Nelson of the bomb squad.
   Nelson wrapped the book in a lead-lined blanket, drove it to the
bomb squad's disposal range and blew it apart with a high-pressure
water cannon.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish firefighter says that after
traveling to eight American cities named Dublin on a three-week
visit to the United States, he is ready to return to the Dublin he
knows best.
   Seamus O'Connor, station officer of the Dublin, Ireland, Fire
Department and coordinator of the visit, wrapped up his tour with
five other Irish firefighters by shopping Sunday afternoon in this
Columbus suburb.
   Dublin, Ohio, with a population of 14,000, has been a city since
September and has planned a yearlong celebration. Dublin, Ireland,
is marking its 1,000th birthday this year.
   O'Connor, 44, said there are 16 cities named Dublin in the
United States, but ``four thousand miles is enough in one trip.''
   ``Maybe we'll visit the other Dublins during our 2000th
anniversary,'' he said.
   The firefighters have been to Dublins in Indiana, North
Carolina, Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, Georgia, Kentucky and
Ohio in an attempt to ``to share greetings of native Irish with the
offspring Dublins,'' O'Conner said.
   ``This is the biggest Dublin we've been to in the United States
and the most modern,'' O'Connor said of the Ohio city. ``But it's
very Irish-connected. They have many things planned around the
Irish, but I say `Never enough.'''
</TEXT>
