<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Wisconsin 650   03-28 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Wisconsin, 650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson's Michigan Victory Casts All Eyes Upon Wisconsin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's weekend victory in the Michigan
Democratic presidential caucuses raised the stakes in Wisconsin's
April 5 primary.
   Massachussets Gov. Michael S. Dukakis will begin an ``aggressive
campaign'' of television advertising in Wisconsin Tuesday and will
be in the state Thursday through April 5, said Dukakis' Wisconsin
campaign manager, Pat Forciea.
   ``We feel this is a two-person race,'' Forciea said.
   Some of the Dukakis advertising will be new, but he will not
take on Jackson in the commercials, Forciea said.
   ``None of the ads are zapping anybody,'' he said.
   Jackson edged Dukakis in Saturday's Michigan caucuses for his
first win in a major Northern industrial state.
   Jackson said he was confident he could follow Michigan with
another victory in Wisconsin ``because I've stood here with the
meat packers in Cudahy, the auto workers in Kenosha, and the paper
workers in De Pere.''
   Dukakis, who entered Saturday's caucuses as the front-runner and
ended in an almost 2-1 loss to Jackson, refused to categorize the
results as a significant setback.
   ``As I said in the beginning of this campaign, it's a
marathon,'' Dukakis said. ``You've asked me about inevitability. As
I have said on more than one occasion, nothing is inevitable about
anything in American politics.
   ``I hope when we finish up in California and New Jersey, I have
a lead I can take into the convention . . . and win the
nomination.''
   Dukakis and Jackson joined Sen. Albert Gore Jr., of Tennesee,
Rep. Richard Gephardt, of Missouri, and Sen. Paul Simon, of
Illinois, at a Democratic Party fund-raising dinner in Milwaukee
Saturday night.
   Both Dukakis and Jackson left Sunday for Connecticut to lobby
for last-minute support before that state's primary Tuesday, while
Simon and Gore remained in Wisconsin.
   Wisconsin Democratic Chairwoman Suellen Albrecht predicted
nearly two-thirds of the Wisconsin voters who go to the polls April
5 will vote for a Democrat, giving the state its largest role in
selecting a presidential nominee in 12 years.
   Albrecht said Wisconsin residents could expect to see
``full-blown'' campaigning efforts from all the remaining
Democratic candidates over the next 10 days.
   Prior to the Jefferson-Jackson Day dinner in Milwaukee, all the
candidates except Jackson joined about 1,500 people in an afternoon
labor rally and march to support nearly 600 Marathon Electric Corp.
shop workers represented by the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers Local 1791 who have been involved in a
four-month fight over wage cuts in Wausau.
   Dukakis, Gephardt, and Simon walked behind a bright orange
solidarity banner with the workers and their supporters.
   Each candidate wore orange armbands saying ``Solidarity Local
1791'' as they sought the vote of laborers in Wisconsin.
   ``You've got a fight on your hands, and I want you to know
you've got friends across the state and across the nation and we're
here,'' Gore told a rally at a downtown parking lot before the
march.
   Jackson sent former New Mexico Gov. Toney Anaya to show his
support.
   While the front-runners began planning strategy to capture
delegates in the remaining states, Gephardt prepared to meet with
family and advisers to decide whether he would pull out of the race
and run for re-election to Congress.
   Gephardt has canceled his Wisconsin schedule and scheduled a
news conference today where it is expected he will annouce he will
file as a candidate for re-election by Tuesday's deadline.
   Gephardt had said he needed to do well in Michigan to sustain a
candidacy that took off in Iowa but stumbled in the South on Super
Tuesday. He finished a disappointing third.
   Dukakis said the field of candidates probably would be narrowed
again after Wisconsin's primary. Jackson declined to comment on
whether a Wisconsin victory would make him the front-runner. But
Jackson also said he had been the front-runner for a year.
</TEXT>
