<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 0504EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Prisoners     03-28 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Prisoners,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels, Opposition Members Leave Prison Under Amnesty Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Contra rebel freed after more than
four years in prison said he will rejoin the Contras, who
negotiated his release under an amnesty agreement with the leftist
Sandinista government.
   Roberto Amador was among 100 people who walked out of the Zona
Franca jail on the outskirts of the capital Sunday as a result of
the agreement, part of a government-rebel cease-fire accord signed
last week in Sapoa.
   ``I will continue being a major in the FDN,'' Amador said,
referring to the Contra military arm, the National Democratic
Force, which will still be allowed to operate in designated
cease-fire zones. Sandinista and Contra leaders were to meet in
Sapoa again today to determine where those zones will be located.
   When he was freed, Amador received a hug from his wife, Melba,
who returned from Miami on Saturday with their two sons.
   ``It's a benediction from God that this happened,'' he said of
his release. Amador, 43, was captured on Oct. 3, 1983, when
Sandinista troops shot down the DC-3 supply plane he was piloting
for the Contra rebels.
   Two other captured crew members, Jaime Lau and Wilfredo
Gutierrez, also were released Sunday. But a fourth, Miguel Angel
Lopez, was not included on the list, said Amador, who also was a
major in the now-disbanded National Guard of President Anastasio
Somoza who was toppled in the 1979 Sandinista revolution.
   Gonzalo Ramirez, president of the Nicaraguan Red Cross, said on
Sunday that Contra negotiators had asked for Amador's freedom
during last week's talks.
   Isidora Zapata, a mother of two, also left the prison Sunday.
   ``I was condemned to 30 years in jail for counterrevolutionary
activities,'' said Mrs. Zapata, the only woman among those released.
   ``I was jailed since April 16, 1982, and since then have seen my
two children very little,'' she said. ``My husband died the same
year I went to jail. I don't know what he died of.''
   Also among those released were 12 members of the Independent
Liberal Party and 12 from the Social Christian Party.
   ``All were activists in our party and not Contras, which they
were accused of being,'' said Eduardo Coronado, an Independent
Liberal.
   Relatives embraced the prisoners as they left the jail, but
there was a tinge of anxiety.
   ``They say I don't have anything to fear,'' said Feliz Pedro
Chavaria Gomez, 32. ``I'm happy, but I hope it (the cease-fire)
doesn't fail.'' He said he was arrested in 1980 and charged with
being a counterrevolutionary.
   The prisoner release was the first step in an amnesty the
government agreed to last week when it signed an accord with the
U.S.-backed Contra leadership that calls for a formal 60-day
cease-fire to begin April 1.
   The amnesty law, passed Saturday by the National Assembly, could
affect the fate of an estimated 3,300 politial prisoners.
</TEXT>
