<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0435 03-28 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 5 grafs after 4th graf bgng ``Noriega has ....''
Picks up pvs 5th graf bgng ``Abrams, the ....''</NOTE>
<HEAD>US Offering Blunt Prescription for Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is sending
Panamanians the blunt message that their nation's crisis will end
if the military turns on Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``Ultimately, I think it's going to have to be the (National)
Guard itself that gets rid of him,'' Assistant Secretary of State
Elliott Abrams said Sunday.
   Abrams, appearing on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation'' expressed hope
that the military strongman would be forced out in ``a matter of
days.''
   Noriega has been indicted by a U.S. federal grand jury on drug
trafficking charges. The Reagan administration has demanded that
Noriega step down and go into exile.
   The New York Times, in today's editions, says administration
officials considered forcible extradition of Noriega to the United
States.
   Panamanian opposition leaders in Washington said they understood
from the administration and from leaders in Latin America that the
United States had considered seeking to have Noriega arrested in
Costa Rica, the newspaper said.
   The Times also said the Panamanian strongman had tried to
arrange a visit to Costa Rica over the weekend. According to senior
Latin American diplomats, the Times said, Noriega wanted to discuss
his political future with Costa Rica's President Oscar Arias
Sanchez and Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez of Spain.
   Gonzalez was in Costa Rica over the weekend. Spain has offered
Noriega asylum if the United States agrees not to ask Madrid for
his extradition.
   Panamanian opposition leaders said Arias rejected Noriega's
request for a meeting and also refused to see a top deputy of the
general.
   Abrams, the State Department official in charge of Central and
Latin American policy, acknowledged that he is surprised the
military leader is still in power in the face of U.S. opposition
and a general strike at home.
   ``I guessed wrong. I thought he'd be gone by now,'' Abrams said.
``I think he's clinging at this point by his fingertips.''
   Abrams made the comments as he pointed out that Noriega has not
been able to pay his military supporters.
   On Saturday, bankers rejected a Panamanian government demand for
$70 million in their vaults. The government's attempt to secure the
funds came after it was unable to meet the 15,000-member military's
payroll.
   Noriega ordered a shake-up of his forces after a failed coup on
March 16. Over the weekend, he sent in troops and police to reopen
Panama City's flour mills in an attempt to break the general strike
aimed at ousting the military leader.
   The Panamanian government has been strapped for cash because of
economic sanctions taken by the United States. U.S. military aid to
Panama was suspended by Congress last year as the political
situation began to deteriorate.
   Abrams, however, said ``it's got to be the National Guard
itself'' that forces Noriega out of power. ``He just won't leave.
... He doesn't care about Panama. He doesn't care about the defense
forces. He doesn't care about the economy. He doesn't care about
the people.''
   Asked about any possible threat to U.S. citizens in the country,
Abrams said the United States intends to protect the 50,000
military people and civilians there.
   ``If there is a threat from Gen. Noriega, it won't last long,''
he said.
   Abrams, speaking with reporters following his television
appearance, was asked whether the United States would use its
military to protect its interests in Panama.
   ``We have an obligation to protect Americans in Panama, the
bases, and a treaty right and obligation to protect the (Panama)
Canal and we will do it,'' he responded.
   Abrams repeated administration assertions that an offer from the
Dominican Republic to give asylum to Noriega is not good enough,
and that it would be better if the military leader accepted a
similar offer from Spain.
   ``The way to end this crisis is to get him out of the country,''
Abrams said.
</TEXT>
