<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraReaction     03-28 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Reaction,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Exiles in South Florida Pray But Doubt Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SWEETWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan exiles and supporters prayed
for peace in a special outdoors Mass, but many worried that Contra
leaders had been too eager to sign a cease-fire agreement with the
Sandinistas.
   More than 300 people, palm fronds in hand, gathered in this
Nicaraguan enclave to pray in a special outdoors Palm Sunday Mass.
   ``All the deaths were for nothing if they signed a treaty in
just four hours,'' said Segundo Marenco, a member of the exile
group that organized the Mass. ``They haven't asked for the
retirement of Cuban troops from Nicaragua. It's just another way to
buy time for the Sandinistas.''
   ``We are looking for peace _ peace with freedom. The resistance
is going to continue to resist until their rights are respected,''
said retired Army Gen. John Singlaub, who has waged a public and
private battle to keep the Contras fighting.
   The gathering came a day after a handful of demonstrators _ one
who punched Contra official Enrique Sanchez in the mouth _
protested the cease-fire agreement outside a Miami hotel where
rebel leaders were holding closed-door meetings.
   ``The general feeling is confusion _ what will happen now in
Nicaragua,'' Roberto Serrano, an engineer who has worked as a wine
importer since leaving his homeland, said at the Mass. ``We have to
wait and see.''
   ``We want peace in Nicaragua, but we don't believe we have
enough guarantees to go back, for we believe the Sandinistas don't
like to be at peace inside Nicaragua,'' exile Eduardo Salgado said.
   Under the pact, which declares a cease-fire until June 1, the
Contras agreed not to accept any more U.S. military aid. In return,
the Sandinistas promised a gradual amnesty for Contras and
unrestricted freedom of expression that would allow them a role in
Nicaragua's political process.
</TEXT>
