<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficerArrested     03-28 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Officer Arrested,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Officer Held In Wife's Shooting Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty police officer pleaded with his
colleagues to kill him after he apparently fatally shot his
24-year-old wife, a sheriff's recruit, during a struggle over a
gun, neighbors said.
   Pablo J. Agrio, 29, a four-year veteran of the San Diego Police
Department, was being held today without bail in the death of Alma
Catalina, police said.
   He was booked for investigation of homicide, and the district
attorney's office will decide today what charges to file, said
police Officer Pete Westrick. However, investigators believe the
shooting was accidental, he said.
   April Montera, a neighbor of Agrio, said he greeted police in
tears after they responded Saturday night to an emergency call at
the Paradise Hills condominium.
   ``He was waving his arms and telling the cops to shoot him,''
said Mrs. Montera.
   Agrio told investigators that he and his wife exchanged blows
during an argument, and then his wife seized the gun and pointed it
at him, said Sgt. Anne O'Dell, a police spokeswoman.
   ``During the struggle over the handgun, the weapon discharged
and struck Mrs. Agrio in the head, killing her instantly,'' the
sergeant said.
   The weapon may have been the officer's firearm, O'Dell said.
   The couple's son, 18-month-old Pablolita, apparently slept
through the altercation, neighbors said.
   Alma Catalina, a recruit correctional officer at the San Diego
County Sheriff's Academy, was scheduled to graduate this spring.
</TEXT>
