<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeditionTrial     03-28 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sedition Trial,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury May Begin Deliberations This Week In Sedition Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-week-old sedition trial in which
white supremacists are accused of plotting to overthrow the
government by force could go to the all-white jury this week if the
defense completes its case.
   Prosecutors contend the 13 defendants conspired to replace the
federal government with an Aryan nation. The defendants say the
government is trying to silence its critics.
   The defense started presenting its case last week in the sixth
week of the trial and several defendants plan to take the stand.
   Prosecutors predicted when the trial began Feb. 16 that they
would spend two months and call 200 witnesses, but they rested
Monday after five weeks and 106 witnesses.
   U.S. District Judge Morris Arnold has repeatedly reminded the
jury, ``Mere disagreement with the government is not seditious
conspiracy.''
   Seditious conspiracy, he said, requires two or more persons to
plot to bring down the government by actions that produce, or are
likely to produce, imminent lawless action.
   The government contends the sedition defendants robbed,
counterfeited, bombed and murdered, and witnesses have testified
how money to do so was distributed.
   A key government witness, unindicted co-conspirator James
Ellison, led an Arkansas white supremacist group _ the Covenant,
the Sword and the Arm of the Lord _ until his arrest in 1985. He is
serving 20 years in prison.
   Ellison said defendant Louis Ray Beam Jr. called for war against
the government, and that co-defendant Robert Edward Miles provided
him with a 30-gallon barrel of cyanide that could be used to poison
the water of a large city like Washington, D.C., or New York City.
   Beam testified that the real issue in the trial was whether
there would be liberty or tyranny. ``In America today, dissidents
in some ways are treated as bad as dissidents in the Soviet
Union,'' he said.
   Miles says the government wants to silence him because he's a
gadfly. ``Sometimes the government gets out its flyswatter,'' Miles
said.
   Of the 14 defendants originally charged, 10 were accused of
seditious conspiracy; one was acquitted for lack of evidence. Five
defendants, including one of the sedition defendants, are accused
of plotting to kill a federal judge and an FBI agent. Two sedition
defendants are accused of the interstate transportation of stolen
money.
</TEXT>
