<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Train Joyride,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Take 50 mph Joyride On Stolen Locomotive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men stole a locomotive and took it on a
three-mile joyride at speeds up to 50 mph before it derailed,
Chicago & North Western Railroad officials said.
   No injuries were reported in the derailment late Saturday on the
city's North Side, railroad spokesman Fred Bloedorn said.
   The unidentified men boarded the 1,500-horsepower, 112-ton
freight locomotive at a rail yard and fled after a rail tower
operator switched it to another rail yard and it jumped the tracks
because of its speed, he said.
   The 25-year-old locomotive, valued at $100,000 to $150,000, was
badly dented when it fell on its side, but crews were not
immediately able to determine how much repairs will cost, he said.
