<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,0807</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says It Captured More Than 500 Square Miles Of Iraqi
Territory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with Iran reporting downing two
Iraqi jets, Iranian rebels claim attack. UPDATES with more details
on ship attacks, Kurd protests. Pickup 16th graf pvs ``Iran's
Prime...''; EDITS to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said today its Revolutionary Guards
killed or wounded 300 Iraqis in a battle in northeast Iraq and now
hold more than 500 square miles of the strategic Kurdistan region.
   Also today, Iran attacked two supertankers in the Persian Gulf,
setting them ablaze, and Iraqi-backed rebels claimed several
thousand of their fighters attacked Iranian troops in southwest
Iran.
   Iraq has admitted losing some territory in Kurdistan. If the
Iranian claim is confirmed, it would mark Iraq's biggest military
setback in the 7{-year-old war since the Iranians battled to within
six miles of Basra 13 months ago.
   Iran said its troops in Kurdistan were within three miles of a
hydroelectric dam supplying most of the power for the region as
well as electricity for Baghdad, the Iraqi capital. The fighting
also was reportedly within 70 miles of oilfields producing more
than half of Iraq's total output, vital to the country's war effort.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
said the Iranians _ who have thrust into the Kurdistan mountains in
a 13-day-old offensive _ ``fiercely repelled'' a counter-attack by
Iraq's 5th Army Corps around Lake Darbandikhan during the night.
   Amid another wave of Iraqi air raids on towns in western Iran,
the Iranians said their fighter planes shot down two Iraqi
warplanes in the Kurdistan battle zone today.
   The Iraqi-backed Iranian rebels said their National Liberation
Army launched a major offensive on a 14-mile front in Iran's
Khuzestan province near the town of Shush.
   The rebels claimed in a communique issued in Baghdad that 15
brigades pushed across the border to drive Iranian forces out of
positions and were threatening a highway southwest of the garrison
city of Dezful.
   The communique reported heavy Iranian casualties with ``a large
number of tanks captured.'' There was no independent confirmation.
   The Iranian rebels said the assault involved several thousand
fighters and was the biggest it mounted since it launched a
campaign against the Iranian regime a year ago.
   In the gulf, Iranian gunboats today attacked the 337,733-ton
Danish supertanker Karama Maersk off the southern emirate of
Sharjah, setting it on fire, gulf-based shipping executives
reported.
   Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit reported there were no
casualties on the vessel.
   Three hours later, the gunboats attacked the 219,287-ton
Norwegian-operated tanker Golar Kansai in the same area and set it
ablaze, said the officials, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   It was not immediately known if there were any casualties aboard
the Norwegian tanker. Salvage tugs went to aid the stricken vessels.
   Also today, Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said
two U.N. officials, Dr. Manuel Carmona and James Holger, arrived in
Tehran to probe Iraq's alleged use of chemical weapons against
three Kurdish towns in Iraq.
   The Iranians claimed 5,000 Iraqi Kurds were killed and 5,000
injured two weeks ago when Iraqi warplanes dropped cyanide and
mustard gas bombs on the towns after they had been captured in the
Iranian offensive.
   The reported chemical attacks sparked protests in the West. In
Washington about 100 people stoned the Iraqi Embassy and about 50
Kurds protested outside an Iraqi mission in Vienna on Sunday.
   In London today, about 200 Kurds ended a peaceful candelight
vigil outside the U.S. Embassy but refused to hand over a petition
demanding U.S. action after embassy officials declined to meet with
them.
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi was quoted today by IRNA
as saying Iran's offensive in Iraq ``has brought the possibility of
an Iranian military victory and punishment of the aggressor
closer.''
   The agency quoted Revolutionary Guards Minister Mohsen
Rafiq-Doust as saying in Tehran after a Cabinet meeting Sunday that
the Iranians have overrun 540 square miles of Iraqi territory.
   The Iranians have pushed about 15 miles into the Lake
Darbandikhan area, Iranian communiques said. They claim to have
killed or wounded nearly 13,500 Iraqis, captured more than 5,000
and destroyed 225 tanks and armored vehicles in fighting since
March 16.
   The Iranians said they have seized the eastern and southern
shores of Lake Darbandikhan, cutting off large number of Iraqis.
   Iran reported its troops were within three miles of the
hydroelectric dam on the southern end of the 10-mile-long lake
after capturing the Shaakh Shamshir heights overlooking the dam.
   Iran said the front line lies 70 miles east of the Kirkuk
oilfields, which produce 1.5 million barrels of oil a day.
</TEXT>
