<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Journalists     03-28 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Journalists,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: 26 Journalists Killed, 59 Assaulted, 180 Arrested in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-six journalists were killed last year
while covering the news, a jump of 11 over 1986, according to a
report by a journalists' group. Eleven of the deaths occurred in
the Philippines.
   The report released Sunday by the Committee to Protect
Journalists also listed 59 assaults on journalists and more than
185 arrests or kidnappings of journalists.
   Eleven journalists were forced to leave their own countries
under threats, and 32 foreign journalists were expelled from the
countries where they were working, the committee also said.
   ``These figures are a grim reminder that even in the midst of a
worldwide communications revolution, some still feel the temptation
to kill the messenger,'' said committee chairman Josh Friedman.
   In 1986, the committee documented the killings of 15
journalists, 56 assaults and more than 190 arrests or kidnappings.
Another 37 journalists were expelled, and eight left countries
under threat.
   In the Philippines, the committee said, most attacks against
journalists ``took place within a series of retaliatory actions
perpetrated by guerillas on one side, and military and paramilitary
(or vigilante) personnel on the other.''
   Five of the 11 killed in the Philippines, more than any other
country, were killed Aug. 27 by armed men who broke into a radio
station. The victims reportedly had ties with an anti-communist
radio commentator.
   The Committee to Protect Journalists is a non-profit,
non-partisan organization founded in 1981 by a group of American
reporters and editors.
</TEXT>
