<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FishersvsSurfers     03-28 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fishers vs Surfers,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Groups Battle Over Hook, Line and Surfer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEBASTIAN INLET, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An uneasy truce reigned between
surfers and fishermen after the two sides fought over the right to
use the waters around a popular jetty.
   The two groups hurled obscenities, bottles, lead sinkers and
fists at each other Friday after surfers accused fishermen of
deliberately casting their hooks and lines too close to them.
   The Brevard County Sheriff's office broke up the fight and
posted a deputy on the disputed jetty at Sebastian Inlet State
Recreational Park, which lies about 80 miles southeast of Orlando.
There were no arrests.
   Deputy Jeff Ludwig said fishermen often cast off the jetty's
north railing while surfers frequently come within 10 years of the
jetty. But Ludwig reported no problems over the weekend as surfers
stayed 40 yards north of the jetty while fishermen cast their lines
mostly from the south side.
   ``It's probably because I'm standing here,'' Ludwig said.
   Tom Cross, 32, a surfer from nearby Melbourne Beach, agreed.
   ``I think with that sheriff's deputy out there on the jetty,
people are going to be a little more careful how they cast,'' Cross
said.
   Fishermen claim the jetty is the best fishing spot around and
say surfers can ride the waves elsewhere.
   ``People should show a little consideration for one another,''
said Gary Hoover, who admitted he intentionally hooked a surfer
once for entering his fishing spot.
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said Hoover, 27, of nearby Satellite Beach.
``You've only got how many miles of beach in Florida and only a
couple of spots where fishermen like to fish. I don't think they
should be surfing this close to the jetty.''
</TEXT>
