<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0414 03-28 0951</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0414,0966</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>August Wilson's `Joe Turner's Come and Gone' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 grafs at end with quotes from other critics. Herald is
cq in 9th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a Pittsburgh boardinghouse in 1911, the
children and grandchildren of slavery grapple with a world that
won't let them forget the past and denies them the future.
   It is the setting for ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone,'' August
Wilson's heartfelt and haunting tale of a church deacon's obsessive
search for his missing wife as well as for his identity as a black
man.
   The play, which opened Sunday at Broadway's Ethel Barrymore
Theater, is Wilson's third work to arrive in New York since 1984.
Following ``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom'' and ``Fences,'' it reaffirms
and enlarges his reputation as a major American playwright.
   ``Joe Turner'' is Wilson's most ambitious play. In it, he blends
African mysticism with compelling, naturalistic drama. The
production, beautifully directed by Lloyd Richards, is rich in
poetry, humor and an almost visionary sense of time, place and
character.
   The story unfolds slowly. Wilson weaves his spell gradually.
It's his steady accumulation of detail that fascinates and finally
mesmerizes.
   Some memorable figures live in this homey boardinghouse, run by
Seth Holly, an ambitious entrepreneur, and his hard-working,
good-natured wife, Bertha. The audience gets to know them all. In
this play, more so than in ``Ma Rainey'' or ``Fences,'' even the
minor characters have lives of their own.
   Chief among the boardinghouse inhabitants is Bynum Walker, a
self-styled ``conjurin' man'' who believes in incantations, the
beneficial effects of roots and herbs, blood sacrifice and voodoo.
He is a link to a black man's African past, although his magic has
been Americanized. Bynum sacrifices the neighbor's pigeons and uses
weeds from Seth's garden as healing herbs.
   Also living in the house is Jeremy Furlow, a hot-headed young
man, recently arrived from the South and not yet aware that things
won't be much different up North. He takes up with Mattie Campbell,
a frail woman who visits the voodoo man for help in finding her
lost mate and decides to stay instead. She stands in contrast to
another resident, Molly Cunningham, a resolutely realistic woman
who knows she can't expect much out of life.
   Into the lives of these transients comes a strange, menacing man
wearing a long black coat and traveling with his young daughter.
Herald Loomis is looking for his wife, Martha. The couple was
separated years earlier when Loomis was forced into a chain gang by
the infamous, real-life bounty hunter, Joe Turner.
   Loomis believes his wife is in the Pittsburgh area. With the
help of Bynum and a white traveling salesman named Rutherford
Selig, he intends to find her.
   The deacon, described aptly by Bynum as ``a man in search of his
own song,'' is the play's most disturbing character. It's his story
that brings each of the play's two acts to dramatic conclusions. At
the end of Act 1, the stage erupts in a joyous religious dance
called a ``juba.'' During this mystical and spiritual frenzy,
Loomis has visions of the not-so-distant past, a time of slavery
and ``bones walking on water.''
   It's not until the second act that Loomis finally confronts his
wife and then slashes himself with a knife to exorcise the ghosts
of long ago. It's not a sacrifice but rather a cleansing, enabling
Loomis to face the future. Whether he and his wife will be able to
pick up the pieces of their severed marriage is unclear but at
least they will be able to try.
   Richards, who also directed ``Fences'' and ``Ma Rainey,'' gets
some fine ensemble work out of his large cast. Particularly
impressive are Delroy Lindo as the tormented deacon, Ed Hall as the
homespun magic man and Mel Winkler as the exasperated boardinghouse
owner. Wilson has also written a tender, funny scene for two
children, and Richards has coaxed two beautiful performances from
Richard Parnell Habersham and Jamila Perry.
   The warm, solid boardinghouse setting by Scott Bradley is capped
by a splendid rooftop view of Pittsburgh and a bridge spanning the
entire stage. It's an evocative reminder that most of the people in
this home are travelers, displaced from the South and still not
comfortable in the North.
   ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' is one more piece in the mosaic
Wilson is creating about black life in 20th century America, one
play for each decade. ``Fences'' is set in the 1950s, while ``Ma
Rainey'' takes place in the 1920s. ``Joe Turner'' may be set even
further in the past, but it is a play that resonates with such
feeling that it leaps across the years to speak powerfully and
movingly to today.
   Among other critics, Frank Rich of The New York Times said that
Wilson ``has once again shown us how in another man's freedom we
find our own.'' The play is Wilson's ``most profound and
theatrically adventurous telling of his story to date,'' Rich wrote.
   ``Here is a lovely, moving play that carries you with it like a
matchbox on a flood,'' wrote Clive Barnes of the New York Post.
   Linda Winer of New York Newsday was equally impressed. ``Joe
Turner'' is August Wilson's ``best play yet _ which means it's a
stunner,'' she wrote. The play has ``a breadth that connects the
dots of neglected history into a picture we will never forget
again.''
   But Howard Kissel of the Daily News said while there are
``scenes of great power,'' ``you feel that in his eagerness to
envision a place where reconcilations abound, Wilson has minimized
the conflict the characters and the period require.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
