<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Rollins 1stLd-Writethru a0517 03-28 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Rollins, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0517,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Police Say Howard Rollins Jr. Arrested On Drug, Traffic
Charges
^Eds: CORRECTS dateline to Baton Rouge, where arrested occurred.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard Rollins Jr., co-star of the NBC
series ``Heat of the Night,'' was arrested on drug and traffic
charges after being stopped for going more than 100 mph on an
interstate, authorities said.
   A state trooper who stopped the actor early Sunday said he found
two bags of a rock-like substance suspected of being cocaine in
Rollins' coat pockets. Rollins' blood alcohol level also was above
the legal limit for intoxication, according to a breath test, he
said.
   The actor was charged with possessing cocaine, first-offense
drunken driving and speeding, and was released on $5,000 bond.
   There was no answer to a telephone call to Rollins' room at the
Hammond Holiday Inn.
   Rollins, who co-starred as Chief of Detectives Virgil Tibbs in
the two-hour television remake of ``Heat of the Night'' and in a
six-part series of the same name, had a commission as a sheriff's
deputy, said Senior Trooper Allen Coburn, who arrested the actor.
   ``He had a badge holder with a Livingston Parish Sheriff's
Office badge and a full commission from the sheriff,'' Coburn said.
``He didn't say anything about it, but he made sure I saw it while
he was getting his driver's license.''
   Rollins, 37, of Baltimore, told police he was in Hammond to make
a movie. ``Heat of the Night'' was filmed in Hammond.
   Coburn said he spotted Rollins' car traveling east on Interstate
12 at a little over 100 mph. Rollins pulled his car to the side of
the interstate and offered no resistance, Coburn said.
   ``He took his coat off while doing the sobriety test. After the
test, I picked up the coat, checked the pockets for weapons and
found two bags of suspected cocaine,'' Coburn said. Each bag
appeared to hold about one-eighth of an ounce of a rock-like
substance, he said.
   Coburn said a breath test indicated that Rollins' blood alcohol
level was 0.15 percent. The law sets intoxication as 0.10 percent
or more.
   Rollins' court date probably will be set in six to eight weeks.
   In addition to ``Heat of the Night,'' in which Carroll O'Connor
co-stars, Rollins' films include ``Ragtime'' in 1981, in which he
was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor, and
``A Soldier's Story'' in 1984.
   In 1985, Rollins starred as a ruthless cocaine dealer in the
television movie ``The Children of Times Square.''
</TEXT>
