<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CitizensCorps 1stLd-Writethru a0441 03-28 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Citizens Corps, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lede to restore dropped word; subs 5th graf, The plan,
to delete superfluous word.</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Democrats Discussing New `Domestic Peace Corps'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he was down and out, on the heels of the
Donna Rice scandal, Gary Hart quit the Democratic campaign and, in
practically the same breath, made the case for something called
``national service.''
   ``I would say to the young people of this country, the torch of
idealism burns bright in your hearts,'' said Hart. ``It should lead
you to public service and national service. It should lead you to
want to make this country better.''
   That was May 1987. On Feb. 29, 1988, Hart was back in the race
but as evidenced at the polls, no one was really listening.
   And so the call for ``national service'' was hardly a burning
issue when Sen. Sam Nunn addressed the Democratic Leadership
Council in Williamsburg, Va. _ and urged the setting up of a
``citizens corps'' to perform voluntary national service.
   The plan could well emerge as a cornerstone of the Democratic
presidential campaign, the 1988 version of John Kennedy's 1960 call
to create a Peace Corps to perform good work overseas.
   It's a ``something for something'' approach to government.
   Young people would commit themselves to public service _ be it
military service or civilian social service _ in return for living
expenses plus a $10,000-a-year voucher. ``Like the G.I. bill,''
Nunn said, the benefits could be used to cover school costs,
vocational training or a home-ownership subsidy.
   The proposal is not new to the presidential campaign. Not only
was it one of Hart's cornerstone ``new ideas,'' but Paul Simon and
Bruce Babbitt also embraced the concept in their campaigns, and on
the Republican side, Alexander Haig Jr. proposed such a program
before he dropped out.
   Hart, Babbitt, Simon, Nunn and Haig. All well and good. But the
proposal won't go anywhere unless one of the nominees adopts it as
his own and the Democratic Leadership Council has laid considerable
groundwork.
   The DLC is the group of moderate Democrats who helped dream up
the Southern regional primaries and hoped the 1988 process would
swing the Democratic party into the political center.
   ``I am convinced that national service can revitalize the spirit
of civic responsibility and enterprise that built this nation and
remains its greatest strength,'' Nunn said.
   Among the goals of the DLC program, Nunn said, are:
   _To increase the number of military volunteers and help remedy
``some of our most urgent social problems, like widespread
illiteracy and inadequate child care and health care.''
   _``Offer a decentralized and non-bureaucratic way to deliver
human services to needy citizens.''
   _``The DLC plan would link federal student aid to national
service,'' he said, contending the program thus would be a ``road
to opportunity and upward mobility for our young people.''
   Anticipating the first question about such a plan, Nunn added,
``Such a program, of course, won't be free. Nothing worthwhile ever
is.
   ``I believe, however, that a large portion of the costs of this
program (estimated in some quarters at $6 billion a year) can be
financed by shifting federal funds already being expended on
student aid.'' In the long run, he said, ``the program, like the
G.I. bill, will return huge revenues to the Treasury because every
additional college graduate in America will earn $640,000 more over
their working life as compared to someone who doesn't go to
college.''
   Nunn's concept and the idealistic appeal from Hart recall
Kennedy's Peace Corps, an enduring element of his legacy even 25
years after his death.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Jonathan Wolman is The AP's assistant bureau
chief in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
