<HEAD>Argentine Storm Leaves At Least 21 Dead, 59,000 Evacuated</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto BAI1</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rain storm whipped through
central Argentina, killing at least 21 people and forcing 59,000 to
leave their homes, civil defense officials said today.
   At least 11 children drowned as floodwaters in some low-lying
areas near Buenos Aires reached up to six feet. Several other
people were electrocuted while crossing flooded streets where live
electrical wires had fallen, authorities said.
   Authorities said the storm, which lasted for four days, ended
today.
   Among the hardest hit areas were Quilmes, Avellaneda and Lomas
de Zamora south of Buenos Aires. Horse-drawn carts, makeshift rafts
and boats were used to evacuate residents. Some people took refuge
on the roofs of their homes, officials said.
   Evacuees were taken to emergency shelters in churches, schools,
sports clubs and office buildings. Health authorities have warned
of a possible outbreak of hepatitis following the storm.
