<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1014EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LouisianaBudget     03-28 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Louisiana Budget,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roemer To Sign Bills, Start Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer says the unprecedented
authority given him by the Legislature to repair the state's
finances will be tempered by compassion and his awareness that
lawmakers are looking over his shoulder.
   Budget officials worked through the weekend to come up with a
list of proposed cuts to present to Roemer today after the
Legislature wound up a special session by approving the emergency
bills. The governor was expected to sign the package today.
   The budgetary authority is aimed at meeting a fiscal crisis
which threatens to bankrupt the state.
   In addition to giving Roemer power to cut entire state programs
and close institutions through June 30, the end of the fiscal year,
lawmakers granted the administration the right to raise fees for
state services without public hearings or legislative oversight.
   After lawmakers finished work Saturday, Roemer said the
temporary budget authority will be tempered ``by my compassion and
good sense that they (legislators) will be coming back in three and
a half weeks to look over my shoulder.''
   The governor said he was aiming for $50 million in spending cuts
for the remaining quarter of the fiscal year and $22 million in fee
increases.
   The rest of the $200 million deficit expected this fiscal year
will be met by issuing short-term bonds or delaying payments for
services rendered to the state, Roemer said. He also said layoffs
of an undetermined number of state employees would be needed.
   Over a full year, the spending cuts would total about $200
million if the Legislature did not change them during its regular
session beginning in April, while the fee hikes would bring in
about $88 million, he said.
   ``Those are the targets. I don't know if I will be able to reach
either,'' he said.
   Commissioner of Administration Brian Kendrick said budget
officials worked through the weekend to come up with the list of
proposed cuts.
   Kendrick also said work would begin on the new Louisiana
Recovery Corp., created by the Legislature to govern a statewide
taxing district that could impose up to a 1 percent sales tax. The
tax would finance the issuance of bonds that would pay off the
state's $1.3 billion long-term debt.
   The administration-dominated commission cannot issue bonds or
impose the levy until the Legislature drops the same amount from
the current 4-cent state sales tax.
   The administration will ask the Louisiana Supreme Court to rule
on the consitutionality of the commission. If it does not pass
legal muster, the state will use short-term bonds to finance the
debt, Kendrick said.
   ``Those are the only two ways out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
