<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Esposito     03-28 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Esposito,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Won't Hear NY Political Boss' Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear an
appeal by former New York City political boss Meade Esposito, who
sought to prevent public disclosure of certain court documents.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling challenged by
Esposito, the former Brooklyn Democratic boss convicted of giving
illegal gratuities to Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y.
   Esposito sought to conceal information contained in pretrial
requests he and Biaggi made to suppress wiretap evidence obtained
by federal law enforcement officials.
   The New York Times, the New York Daily News and The Associated
Press asked that the information be made public.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in favor of the news
organizations in January.
   The appeals court said revealing the information, with some
deletions made by a federal judge, would not violate Esposito's
privacy rights.
   Esposito was convicted last Sept. 22 of giving, and Biaggi of
accepting, illegally gratuities in the form of free vacations.
   In a separate prosecution, Biaggi is on trial in New York City
with six others accused of turning the Wedtech Corporation into a
racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to
get government contracts.
   In the appeal acted on today, Esposito said allowing public
disclosure of the documents from the Biaggi-Esposito case would
have an unconstitutional chilling effect on all defendants.
   It could prevent defendants from making pretrial motions to
suppress evidence for fear that information contained in the
motions would be made public, Esposito said.
   The case is Esposito vs. New York Times, 87-1319.
</TEXT>
