<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Libya     03-28 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Libya,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi to Withdraw Troops from Border with Egypt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi said today he is
withdrawing Libyan troops from the Egyptian border and promised
Libya would not use force to undermine the Egyptian state.
   If carried out, the Libyan leader's decision would represent an
unprecedented conciliatory move. Gadhafi began feuding with Egypt
about 15 years ago.
   Gadhafi's announcement followed a series of smaller-scale
reciprocal goodwill gestures between the two countries in recent
weeks.
   Gadhafi made the announcement in a speech at a former British
base at the Mediterranean city of Tobruk near the Egyptian border.
The speech, broadcast live by Libyan television and monitored in
London, was delivered at a ceremony marking the 18th anniversary of
Britain's evacuation of military bases in Libya.
   In another departure from long-standing hostile policy toward
Cairo, Gadhafi said Libya would not use force to overthrow
President Hosni Mubarak's government or get it to renounce its 1979
peace treaty with Israel. The treaty was among numerous sore spots
in Egyptian-Libyan friction.
   The speech contained one anti-Egyptian barb, however, with
Gadhafi charging that Egypt ``abandoned'' the Arab world when it
signed the American-mediated Camp David agreements with Israel.
   ``I hereby declare the withdrawal of all military troops from
along the Libyan-Egyptian artificial borders,'' Gadhafi said.
   ``I want to emphasize to the Egyptian people and army that the
Libyan eastern military zone (along the border) will finally be
abolished.''
   Gadhafi did not say how many troops Libya has along the border.
Neither did he specify a time frame for the pullback.
   The Egyptian-Libyan feud began in 1972 when Cairo rejected
Gadhafi's bid for immediate merger of the two countries.
   Egypt blamed Gadhafi for a series of bombings in Cairo and other
cities in 1975 and 1976, and the two countries fought a five-day
border war in July 1977. The political tension deepened when Egypt
since the peace treaty with Israel and moved closer to the United
States.
   Gadhafi, who overthrew the Libyan monarchy in a military coup in
1969, offered to let Egypt verify the troop withdrawal.
   ``If Egypt wants to ascertain this, it will be able to observe,
and we accept any verification commission or any observer or
monitor who would be satisfied that this region is completely
evacuated by military forces,'' he said.
   The Libyan leader said his forces will be withdrawn ``without us
asking for anything in return from the Egyptian side.''
</TEXT>
