<DOCNO> AP880328-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1053EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Recess     03-28 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Recess,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Agrees to Hear Appeal of Convicted South Carolina Killer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to hear the
appeal of a convicted killer who said his rights were violated when
he was denied an opportunity to talk to his lawyer during a trial
recess.
   The court said it will review a ruling that denied a new trial
to the South Carolina man.
   The defendant, Donald Ray Perry, was convicted of murder,
kidnapping and criminal sexual assault in the killing of Mary
Heimberger, whose body was found on March 7, 1981, in a wooded area
in Richland County, S.C. He was sentenced to life in prison.
   Perry confessed to police that he had shot the victim, but said
it was an accident.
   Ms. Heimberger had been raped, shot in both kneecaps and fatally
shot in the chest.
   During a 15-minute trial recess while Perry was testifying, his
lawyer sought to speak to him to advise him about his rights on
cross-examination. But the judge refused to allow them to talk.
   Perry filed a federal court appeal in 1985 and a judge ruled
that his rights were violated. The judge said denying Perry the
right to talk to his laywer during a recess, no matter how brief,
is grounds for throwing out the conviction.
   But the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the
conviction in November.
   ``Not every limitation of the relationship between a defendant
and his attorney violates the defendant's right to counsel,'' the
appeals court said.
   The appeals court said barring a defendant from meeting with his
lawyer during a brief trial recess is not automatic grounds for
declaring a new trial. There must be evidence that the denial
prejudiced the case against the defendant, the appeals court said.
   The appeals court relied in part on two Supreme Court rulings in
1984 that reinstated criminal convictions of two defendants who
said they were denied effective legal assistance at their trials.
   The high court said a claim of ineffective representation must
be examined in the context of whether the trial produced a just
result.
   The appeals court said that standard also should apply to
Perry's claim.
   ``It would make little sense to maintain a per se (automatic)
rule of reversal for a brief restriction on consultation, but to
inquire into prejudice if Perry had been represented incompetently
throughout,'' the appeals court said.
   ``To reverse automatically a conviction because of an absence of
consultation during one brief, fortuitous recess in a trial which
spanned nearly two weeks would be to confer a benefit upon a
criminal defendant who may not deserve it,'' the appeals court
added.
   It also said, ``The evidence against Perry was overwhelming,''
and there was no indication that denying him the chance to confer
with his lawyer prior to cross-examination altered his testimony
significantly.
   ``It would be wrong to exalt technical perfection at the expense
of our society's legitimate and weighty interest in punishing
offenders,'' the appeals court said.
   The case is Perry vs. Leeke, 87-6325,
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1101EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia 1stLd-Writethru a0528 03-28 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0528,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Continues In Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with report from
Nagorno-Karabakh. PICKS up 3rd graf, `Pravda said ...' EDITS to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike today slowed transportation and
closed most factories in the largest city in a region that
Armenians want to unite with their republic, a witness said.
   The director of the only hotel in Stepanakert said all but
essential services were shut down today because of a strike.
   ``The bread factory and the milk factory are working. The others
are not working. Everyone is sitting at home,'' the director of the
Karabakh Hotel said in a telephone interview. He said he was an
ethnic Armenian but refused to give his name.
   About 30 percent of Stepanakert's public transport was shut
down, he said. Communist Party representatives in the city called
workers to meetings at factories today and urged them to return to
work Tuesday, he said.
   Stepanakert is the largest city in Nagorno-Karabakh, a mainly
Armenian region in the republic of Azerbaijan which activists are
seeking to unite with Armenia. At least 32 people have died in
ethnic violence between Armenians and Azeris since protests began
in February.
   Armenian activists have said a general strike began Wednesday in
parts of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Pravda, the Communist Party daily, reported today the strikes
and unrest in Azerbaijan have disrupted the economy and cost the
region millions of dollars in lost revenues.
   The Communist Party daily said action by Armenianis has
``aggravated the economic situation not only in the autonomous
region but also, partly, in the entire republic.''
   
   Pravda said the auto and trucking industries alone lost about
$6.5 million in January and February. The railway industry lost
about $360,000.
   The article gave little indication about how the money was lost
but quoted a railway official in Azerbaijan as saying freight cars
had not been unloaded.
   The official, Garik Sarkisyan, was quoted by Pravda as saying
the situation was ``bad'' and ``loss of time and money has become
the usual thing.''
   Pravda said Yerevan, the capital of the Armenian republic, was
``relatively calm'' with no incidents over the weekend ``connected
with national relations.''
   Moscow dissidents, in telephone contact during the weekend with
Armenian sources, described Yerevan as ``a dead city,'' with people
staying off the streets to protest a government crackdown on public
demonstrations.
   The official press acknowledged that most businesses were closed
in Stepanakert, the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh, over the
weekend, but gave no information on the situation this morning.
   According to various reports from dissident and official sources
over the weekend, the general strike appeared to have taken place
in Stepanakert, but in other areas most businesses were open.
   An administrator of the Yerevan Hotel, who spoke on condition of
anonymnity, said the city's businesses were open today. Other calls
to Yerevan did not go through.
   Western reporters have been barred from the region, and
telephone service has been largely cut off.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, including Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other members of the top leadership,
called last week for improvement of social and economic conditions
in the contested area, but it did not deal directly with the
annexation issue.
   Activists interpreted that as a rejection of their demands and
called for a general strike.
   Tass said today the Communist Party Central Committee and
government's Council of Ministers approved plans for construction
of more schools _ including Armenian schools _ in Nagorno-Karabakh
and other regions of Azerbaijain where ethnic Armenians live.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
