<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Trump-Plaza     03-28 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trump-Plaza,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Donald Trump Buys Plaza; Wants To Win Fifth Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate magnate Donald Trump, the new owner
of the Plaza hotel, says he plans to make the Fifth Avenue landmark
even posher in an effort to make it the second five-star hotel in
Manhattan.
   He vowed that the Plaza, already the city's most famous hotel,
would become the most luxurious hotel in the world under the
supervision of his wife, Ivana. The hotel is a four-star
establishment.
   The only Manhattan hotel with the distinction of having five
stars is the Carlyle Hotel, at Madison Avenue and 76th Street.
   Built in 1907 in the style of a French chateau, the Plaza has
been cited by the city's Landmarks Preservation Commission as a
``superb example of the elegance and opulence that characterized
the period just before World War I.''
   The hotel, with its famed public spaces and its commanding site
overlooking Central Park, has become one of New York's most
recognizable buildings through its frequent movie appearances,
including a starring role in ``Plaza Suite.'' More recently, the
Plaza provided an upscale encampment for ``Crocodile Dundee.''
   But it has lost some of its luster under a succession of owners
in recent years and is in the midst of a major renovation.
   Its latest owners were Texas financier Robert Bass and the
Japanese-based Aoki Corp., which bought it last October from Westin
Hotels.
   Trump, when he announced announced Saturday that he had
purchased the Plaza Hotel for $390 million, said he would not
change its name. ``It's got the most important name in the world,
and it's going to remain that way,'' he said.
   Trump lives just two blocks from the Plaza at his Trump Tower
high-rise apartment building. He won out in a bidding contest
against two other Manhattan developers, Philip Pilevsky and Arthur
Cohen, who wanted to convert part of the hotel into cooperative
apartments.
   Room rates at the Plaza start at $195 a night. Trump said he
hoped to lure some year-round guests to the hotel at rental rates
of $400,000 to $500,000 a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
