<DOCNO> AP880328-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1121EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Portugal-Strike     03-28 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Portugal-Strike,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Shuts Factories, Banks, Airports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-hour general strike today shut
factories, airports and banks across Portugal as hundreds of
thousands of workers staged the biggest industrial action in the
country's history to protest government labor reforms.
   The Communist and Socialist labor federations, united for the
first time, claimed the strike was a victory for the unions over
the center-right government of Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva.
   Cavaco Silva, whose Social Democrats hold a solid parliamentary
majority, said the strike would not cause him to alter a single
line of a government bill that would make it easier for businesses
to fire workers. He said the legislation is crucial to attracting
investment in Portugal and modernizing the economy.
   Labor leaders said 85 percent of union members supported the
strike.
   ``The government cannot act as if were deaf, dumb and blind in
the face of this massive protest,'' said Manuel Carvalho da Silva,
a leader of the Communist-dominated General Confederation of
Portuguese Workers.
   But the government said in a statement ``the country is working
normally apart from the transport sector where there have been some
clear cases of sabotage.'' The Labor Ministry said unions were
exaggerating the extent of support for the strike.
   Twenty-two in-coming flights and 29 departures were cancelled at
Lisbon Airport and many other international flights were diverted,
officials said.
   Most flights of the state-owned airline TAP-Air Portugal were
cancelled at Oporto Airport in the north and Faro in the south.
   State-owned public transport companies were hit hardest by the
strike. Train services were paralyzed across the country. Bus,
trams, subway and ferry services were reduced to skeleton services
required under strike law.
   Police said two shots were fired at a private bus in the
northern city of Porto. No one was injured. Traffic was not heavily
congested in most cities as many workers stayed home, police said.
   The government says existing labor legislation, passed in the
wake of a leftist military coup that returned Portugal to democracy
in 1975, is so protective that it is almost impossible for
companies to dismiss workers.
   Cavaco Silva says this deters investors and is prejudicial to
workers because it encourages companies to hire them on short-term
contracts, use child labor and keep wages low.
   The government says the new legislation will still provide
greater protection than workers enjoy in any other West European
country or the United States.
   Unions and the leading Socialist opposition party say the
legislation will give managers the power to fire workers ``whenever
and `whyever' they like.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
