<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Evacuation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fumes Ignite On Plane, Trigger Fire Alert And Evacuation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `The four ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
one passenger admitted to hospital.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines jet was evacuated when fuel
vapors briefly ignited, sparking what passengers thought was a fire
and closing the airport for 20 minutes, authorities said. Four
people were slightly injured.
   Flight 288, originating in San Diego with 144 passengers and
seven crew members aboard, landed safely at 8:20 p.m. Sunday at
Metropolitan Airport in Romulus, about 20 miles west of Detroit.
   As the Boeing 727 waited for clearance to taxi to its gate,
residual fuel in the exhaust system of the auxiliary power unit
sparked a ``flash'' on the plane's right wing, Northwest spokesman
William Wren said.
   It was immediately extinguished without damage to the plane,
Wren said.
   The flash was seen by a controller in the airport tower,
passengers aboard Flight 288 and by people aboard another plane
taxiing behind it, said Mort Edelstein, a spokesman for the Federal
Aviation Administration in Chicago.
   ``I saw a flash and I looked down and I felt heat on my face,
and I looked out and there's a big flame on my window and all I
could see was red,'' Northwest passenger Mike Soderling of San
Diego told radio station WCXI.
   ``This lady next to me was screaming `Fire, fire,''' Soderling
said. ``My first reaction was to get my luggage, but then I threw
it down and ran to the door.''
   The pilot triggered an automatic device that extinguished the
flash, but by that time, the plane had been evacuated and airport
firefighters were summoned, Edelstein said.
   An initial FAA examination of the plane revealed no burned parts
or other signs of an actual fire, he said. Northwest officials
stressed that no fire had occurred.
   Three of the injured passengers suffered minor cuts and bruises
while sliding down evacuation chutes, Annapolis Hospital nursing
supervisor Mary Smith said. None was admitted. The fourth
passenger, a 64-year-old woman, was in good condition today at
William Beaumont Hospital in Royal Oak, suffering from trauma and
knee and elbow injuries, said hospital spokeswoman Carol Jonson.
   The auxiliary power unit runs the aircraft's electrical, air
conditioning and other systems while it is on the ground and
operates separately from the engines, Wren said.
   Edelstein said the plane will remain grounded while FAA
investigators examine it further.
</TEXT>
