<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Israel     03-28 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Government Reaches Agreement with Walsh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent Counsel Lawrence Walsh has reached
agreement with Israel after year-long negotiations for its
cooperation in his investigation of the Iran-Contra affair, both
sides announced today.
   Under the accord, Israel has given Walsh the historical and
financial chronologies covering its role in the shipment of U.S.
weapons to Iran in 1985 and 1986, said an Israeli official.
   ``He (Walsh) will get what he wants without us having to give up
what we wanted,'' said the official, speaking on condition he not
be named.
   Israel had sought immunity from prosecution for the four key
Israeli players in the arms sales, profits from which were diverted
to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   Two former White House aides and two U.S. businessmen have been
indicted in the United States for conspiracy to defraud the
government in the funds' diversion.
   Israel also gave Walsh written answers to questions posed by the
congressional investigators who received the Israeli chronologies
last summer, said the official.
   ``The government of the state of Israel and the office of the
Independent Counsel have signed an agreement covering the
cooperation of the government of Israel in the Iran-Contra
investigation,'' Walsh's office said in a prepared statement.
   Walsh's spokesman, Jim Wieghart, and Israeli Embassy spokesman
Yossi Gal said the terms of the agreement are confidential.
   Israel had turned over the chronologies to the congressional
Iran-Contra committees but refused to give them to Walsh pending
his promise to refrain from prosecuting the four Israelis involved
in the affair.
   Negotiations with Walsh were further complicated when he
subpoenaed the four Israelis: former Foreign Ministry director
David Kimche, former counter-terrorism adviser Amiram Nir,
businessman Yaakov Nimrodi and his U.S.-born associate, Al
Schwimmer.
   In asking for immunity, Israel contended that the four acted at
the request of the Israeli government and therefore were not
accountable as individuals.
   Two senior Israeli officials held talks with Walsh's office 10
days ago to wind up the negotiations, which have been going on
since early 1987. The Israeli government approved the accord, said
the Israeli official.
   ``The negotiations were difficult,'' said Wieghart. ``Israel is
a sovereign state with certain national security interests, which
they have to defend. We recognized that, but on the other hand, we
had our needs in this investigation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
