<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Group Calls for End to One-party Government in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of intellectuals has called
for an end to one-party government in this communist state in the
first such written statement by an official body, newspapers
reported Monday.
   The group, charged with outlining proposed changes in
Yugoslavia's constitution, asked Sunday for an ``abolition of the
monopolistic rule'' of the Communist Party, according to the
state-run Borba lectuals called for ``putting the
party into a competitive position with other (parties).''
   The statement by the unions of Serbian writers, philosophers and
sociologists was adopted at daily. The intela meeting of the writers on
Sunday.
   Several leading intellectuals in Serbia, the largest republic,
and Slovenia, the most economically developed region, have made
recent appeals for political pluralism. They have said it is a
precondition for overcoming the country's worst economic and
political crisis in history.
   In addition to rising ethnic tensions, Yugoslavia is faced with
a $20 billion foreign debt, 170 percent inflation, dropping living
standards and growing labor unrest.
   The statement also called for changes in the constitution to
allow more human rights and abolish laws permitting prosecution of
dissidents, the newspapers reported.
</TEXT>
