<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Uganda-Pardon ,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Activist Freed in Uganda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president pardoned and freed a human
rights activist Monday who had been held for 13 months.
   The release of Lance Sera Muwanga, 43, was announced in a letter
from President Yoweri Museveni to the Uganda Human Rights
Activists. Muwanga is secretary-general of that group.
   After he was freed, Muwanga appealed for release of hundreds of
other people he said were held as political detainees in Uganda. He
also pledged to carry on fighting for human rights in the East
African nation.
   The president's letter said the activist had been pardoned on
humanitarian grounds. Muwanga has been under guard in a Kampala
hospital for several weeks for treatment of cancer of the lymph
glands.
   Muwanga said he has never been given a reason for his detention.
He was arrested Feb. 25, 1987, two weeks after he accused
Museveni's troops of torturing and killing civilians in northern
Uganda, where the government is fighting an insurgency.
</TEXT>
