<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0493 03-28 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Brings Return Of Winter Weather, Thunderstorms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Winter storm ...,' with 4 grafs to add
details of Rockies snow storm.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow showers were scattered over the eastern Great Lakes region
today, while a strong storm system over the northern and central
Plains brought a return of winter weather to the northern Rockies.
   Meanwhile, springlike thunderstorms developed Sunday over the
High Plains of Texas and across South Dakota in the warmer air
ahead of the storm system.
   Wind gusts of 60 mph were clocked Sunday night in the northern
mountain ranges and Mojave area of California.
   Strong winds also hit the Plains, gusting to 61 mph late Sunday
evening at Goodland, Kan., and to 59 mph at La Junta, Colo., as
colder air poured into the region. Warm, southerly winds ahead of
the cold front gusted to 63 mph at Gage, Okla., and to 62 mph at
Garden City, Kan.
   Temperatures across much of western Nebraska, northeast Colorado
and northwest Kansas plummeted 25 to 40 degrees in a six-hour
period late Sunday. Readings ranged from the low 30s to upper 40s
early today.
   In the Rocky Mountain states, up to a foot of snow fell in some
areas. A rancher in central Montana reported drifts of 1 to 3 feet,
and nearly 270 miles of Interstate 15 were covered with snow, from
Butte to the Canadian border. Interstate 90 had blowing snow east
of Bozeman and near Livingston.
   In Colorado, the mercury plunged after a weekend of unseasonably
warm weather in the 70s and 80s and snow fell in many areas.
Snowmass, Winter Park and Vail ski areas all received 8 inches of
snowfall overnight, while 6 inches was reported at Aspen.
   Snowfall and slippery roads were blamed for a traffic death west
of Golden today when a tanker truck slid off a highway, killing the
driver.
   Winter storm watches covered southeast Wyoming, western Nebraska
and northwest Kansas today and tonight.
   The storms over Texas on Sunday evening were accompanied by
1{-inch diamter hail near Cotton Center, while hail an inch in
diameter fell at Tulia.
   Rain also fell in sections of the Dakotas, while snowshowers
were scattered from western Nebraska into the central Colorado
Rockies.
   Skies were clear early today across the Southeast.
   Many sections of the West and Plains enjoyed unseasonably high
temperatures again Sunday, with records broken in numerous cities.
Denver warmed to 78, breaking the 76-degree mark set in 1986.
Goodland, Kan., hit 87, besting the 78-degree record of 1971. Grand
Island, Neb., reached 81, topping the 78 mark of 1905. Tucson,
Ariz., reached 94, beating the 92 mark set in 1986.
   The forecast today called for showers and thunderstorms from the
southern Plains to the upper Mississippi Valley, with severe
thunderstorms possible across parts of western and northern Texas
into western and central Oklahoma; snow over the Rockies and in the
western portions of the northern and central Plains; rain in
western Washington and Oregon; a few morning flurries over northern
Maine; and windy conditions in the Great Plains and the Southwest.
   Highs were expected to be in the 30s or 40s from New England
across the northern Great Lakes, northern Minnesota, the Dakotas,
western portions of the central Plains, the Rockies and
Intermountain West to Washington state; the 70s in coastal
California; and the 70s or 80s from the southern Atlantic states
across the Tennessee, lower Ohio and lower Mississippi valleys,
Missouri, the southern Plains and southern New Mexico to the desert
Southwest. Elsewhere, readings will be in the 50s or 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 1
degree at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 78 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 52 fair; Boston 37 partly cloudy; Buffalo 32
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 46 fair; Cincinnati 33 fair; Cleveland 27
fair; Detroit 30 partly cloudy; Miami 73 fair; New York 42 windy;
Philadelphia 42 cloudy; Pittsburgh 30 fair; Portland, Maine 37
cloudy; Washington 40 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 40 cloudy; Chicago 42 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 68 cloudy; Denver 37 dust; Des Moines 62 windy;
Indianapolis 36 fair; Kansas City 63 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 45
windy; Nashville 41 fair; New Orleans 55 fair; St. Louis 54 partly
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 56 partly cloudy; Anchorage 27 cloudy; Las
Vegas 57 windy; Los Angeles 60 fair; Phoenix 76 fair; Salt Lake
City 34 partly cloudy; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 58 windy;
Seattle 37 fair.
   _Canada: Toronto 28 fair.
</TEXT>
