<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Blizzard     03-28 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Blizzard,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Highways Closed After Late-Winter Blizzard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late winter blizzard paralyzed dozens
of cities and towns in western Canada on Monday, closing major
highways and stranding more than 1,000 motorists.
   The storm began Sunday and travelers were forced to seek
overnight shelter in school gyms and hockey rinks along the
Trans-Canada Highway east of the Olympic city of Calgary and along
Highway 2 from Calgary to Edmonton.
   When the blizzard struck Calgary International Airport on
Sunday, more than 120 passengers on an Air Canada jet spent seven
hours on the runway, unable to take off. Visibility was too poor
for the crew to get the plane back to the terminal building a few
hundred yards away.
   ``Most of us just slept and we had our breakfast on the plane,''
said one passenger, Spiro Plagakis, an engineer from Montreal.
   The wet snow toppled power lines, leaving many communities
without electricity or telephone service.
   The town of Camrose, 42 miles southeast of Edmonton, got more
than 20 inches of snow.
</TEXT>
