<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-28 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WYOMING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't quite gold at the end of the
rainbow, but one amateur sleuth didn't complain about his jackpot.
   Dale McRae struck silver _ or, more accurately, a laminated card
declaring him the winner of a treasure hunt _ at the base of a
telephone pole guy wire at Katherine Drive and Monroe Avenue on
Friday.
   ``I reached down at the base of the guy wire, and there it
was,'' McRae said. ``I didn't even look. I just knew that was it.''
   Joe Cramer, who owns a car care shop in this Grand Rapids
suburb, each year offers a prize of silver to the first person to
solve a complicated riddle. Cramer issued a 77-word riddle on Nov.
20 to start the latest hunt and gave short clues on the 20th of
each following month.
   The original riddle mentioned a large woman singer _ maybe Kate
Smith? And Monroe came from the mention ``first'' (mono) and
``caviar'' (roe).
   McRae recognized in the final clue a mathematical formula for
calculating the sides of a triangle, and the riddle suggested
looking for a ``little support.'' He spied the triangular shape of
the wire and the pole, and the prize was his.
   McRae's wife, Kathy, said their home is too small to properly
display the silver serving tray, engraved cup and silver coins they
won, but she added, ``Someday we'll have a big house, and then
we'll really be able to enjoy it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beach-goers seeking to escape the
city found something unexpected: a quarter-mile-long swath of sand
imprinted with a cityscape of Los Angeles by a 14-ton concrete
roller.
   ``I like it, but I think it is a bit crazy,'' said Sandra
Soderberg, 20, a tourist from Sweden who witnessed the progression
Sunday of the ``Santa Monica Art Tool.''
   With a $60,000 commission from the seaside city, the National
Endowment for the Arts and another non-profit arts group, artist
Carl Cheng crafted his unusual device to bring art to the masses.
   Designs carved into the surface of the roller left _ for the
moment at least _ two-inch-tall sand replicas of such city scenes
as the Memorial Coliseum and a traffic-choked freeway.
   ``I like going to the general public and making a project
interesting to them, not just the art collectors, said Cheng, 46,
of Los Angeles.
   Initial reviews were favorable.
   ``It's wonderful,'' said Paul Schneider, 47, of Los Angeles. ``I
like the fact that the city is putting its money into art that can
be appreciated by thousands of people. It's art that is also an
event.''
   Cheng's work is the second commissioned for Santa Monica beaches
as part of a 10-piece ``Natural Elements Sculpture Park.''
   The roller will go on permanent display near the Santa Monica
pier.
</TEXT>
