<2ND_LINE>PM-Chambers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0539,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors in Chambers Trial Say They Could Have Reached Verdict</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `As part ...,' with 1 graf to recast,
clarifying that a sexual encounter that turned rough was part of
Chambers' story before his plea.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the Robert Chambers murder trial said
today that the jury, though bogged down in circumstantial evidence,
could have reached a verdict.
   ``I feel very firmly that we could have reached a verdict,''
said juror Cole Wallace, interviewed on ABC's ``Good Morning
America'' program.
   ``We never reached a dead end,'' said juror Mike Ognibene,
interviewed on the same program. ``We were judging with a
circumstantial case and there was a great deal of discretion
involved in reaching the decision.''
   Chambers agreed to plead guilty last Friday to first-degree
manslaughter and an unrelated burglary charge to end his trial on
murder charges in the death of Jennifer Dawn Levin during a Central
Park tryst. The agreement followed nine days of deliberations and
both the prosecution and defense feared a hung jury.
   As part of the plea bargain, Chambers, who had maintained since
his arrest that he killed Miss Levin accidentally during a sexual
encounter that turned rough, acknowledged he intended to hurt the
18-year-old woman the night of her death.
   Chambers entered the Rikers Island jail Saturday to await
sentencing April 15. He faces a five-to-15-year prison term for
killing Miss Levin under the bargain.
   ``We were shocked that that's how it ended,'' juror Ginny Hoesl
said of the plea bargain in an interview on ``CBS This Morning.''
She said Chambers would have been convicted, but it was impossible
to say on what charge.
   Betsy Shankin, a friend of Jennifer Levin's, said on the same
program that she would have preferred a jury verdict, but was
satisfied that Chambers had to admit his guilt as part of his plea.
She wished for a longer sentence, however, saying, ``I don't think
it will ever be enough for him.''
   On Sunday, Monsignor Thomas Leonard, who helped counsel Chambers
after his arrest, said Chambers would issue a statement soon about
the killing.
   ``I think that ... he will make some sort of statement of how
sorry he is for the trouble this has caused the Levin family and
for his own family,'' he said.
   In a separate development, Chambers' lawyer, Jack Litman,
ridiculed allegations by Assistant District Attorney Linda
Fairstein that his client forged $7,000 worth of stolen checks in
October and used some of it to buy drugs.
   ``The scandalous claims by the prosecutors are made in an
obvious attempt to save face for having allowed Robert Chambers to
receive a sentence in the range of reckless manslaughter when they
proclaimed from the rooftop that Robert Chambers intentionally
murdered Jennifer Levin,'' he said Saturday.
   Fairstein said she didn't want to provoke a mistrial by making
the allegation public earlier.
   As part of the plea bargain, Chambers is immune from prosecution
from any other past crimes.
   Prosecutors had said that the burglary to which Chambers pleaded
guilty was committed to support his cocaine habit, for which he was
institutionalized twice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
