<DOCNO> AP880328-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorkerNotice     03-28 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Worker Notice,380</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats failed again today to end
debate on a bill that would require the government to notify
100,000 to 300,000 workers a year that they risk cancer and other
disabling diseases from exposure to toxic substances on the job.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said a fourth
attempt at ending what some proponents of the legislation have
branded as a Republican filibuster will be made Tuesday. Two
attempts last week failed.
   Byrd indicated, however, that tomorrow's move could be the last
effort to force a final Senate vote on the House-passed bill if its
sponsors cannot muster the 60 votes necessary to limit further
debate to 30 hours.
   Unlike ending a filibuster, passage of a bill requires only a
simple majority _ 51 votes if all 100 senators are present.
   The 41-44 vote today to cut off debate indicated that Sens.
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the
chief authors of the bill, had picked up only slight support by
exempting farm workers and companies with less than 100 full-time
employees.
   Metzenbaum and Hatch mustered 33 votes last week for ending a
threat by Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Dan Quayle, R-Ind., to
prolong the debate indefinitely and prevent the Senate from moving
on to other measures.
   A few southern Democrats and liberal Republicans who had voted
with Hatch and Quayle last week voted with Metzenbaum and Kennedy
today.
   The bill would establish a panel of experts to identify the most
hazardous substances in workplaces and the groups of employees most
susceptible to disabling diseases because of exposure to them.
   The National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health would
be required to notify 100,000 to 300,000 of those workers every
year at an annual cost of $25 million.
   Employers then would be required to finance medical monitoring
program for them at a cost of up to $250 each annually.
   If, as a result of the monitoring, a physician recommends
transferring an employee to less hazardous work, employers would
have to pay the same level of wages and benefits to the worker in
the new job. In the event no other job is available, the employee
would be entitled to full wages and benefits for up to a year after
leaving a job.
</TEXT>
