<HEAD>South African Jailed for Spying in Zambia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court sentenced a South African to
prison for 50 years after he was convicted of spying for the
Pretoria government.
   Isiah Moyo, 32, of Johannesburg, was found guilty of gathering
classified information on Zambian strategic installations and the
guerrilla-backed African National Congress headquarters in Lusaka.
   Moyo, who is black, is a former soldier in the South African
military.
   He had pleaded innocent to the charges. But the high court
commissioner rejected his defense that police and the ANC had
framed him.
   The ANC says its goals, which can only be achieved by the
overthrow of the white government in South Africa, are for one-man,
one-vote in a unitary state.
