<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Israel     03-28 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US `Regrets' Israeli Moves On West Bank and Gaza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department, which has restricted
American travel to the West Bank and Gaza, today said it regretted
Israel's decision to seal off the territories for three days in
expectation of major demonstrations called by the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   Spokesman Charles E. Redman said the Israeli move would have an
impact on commerce, visits between family members and the press.
   Both Israelis and Arabs will be prevented from entering the two
areas. The only exception will be the 65,000 Jewish settlers who
live in the territories.
   A total of 119 Palestinian Arabs and an Israeli soldier have
died since violent protests broke out Dec. 9. The State Department,
citing ``continuing disturbances,'' last Friday advised U.S.
citizens to avoid travel to the areas until further notice.
   The warning also could have an impact on tourism and business,
especially during Holy Week.
   Redman reaffirmed, meanwhile, that U.S. policy prohibits dealing
with the PLO as well as negotiating or recognizing the group until
it accepts Israel's right to exist and disavows terrorism.
   The spokesman said Secretary of State George P. Shultz's meeting
here Saturday with two American members of the Palestine National
Council did not conflict with the 13-year-old policy.
   The council considers itself the legislative arm of the
Palestinian nationalist movement. One of the two Palestinians,
Edward Said, said he informed PLO chairman Yasser Arafat before he
and Ibrahim Abu-Lughod met with Shultz.
   Redman said that the PLO and the council were not ``synonymous''
and that ``our restrictions on dealing with the PLO remain as
always.''
   Shultz will go to the Middle East on Sunday for five days of
talks with Arab and Israeli leaders on his proposal to open
negotiations by May 1.
   He will make stops in Israel, Jordan, Syria, Egypt and Saudi
Arabia.
   Shultz presented his proposal to Arab and Israeli leaders four
weeks ago
   and asked for a reply by mid-March. So far, only Egypt has
endorsed his plan.
</TEXT>
