<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Day,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dennis Day Removed From Intensive Care Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Dennis Day is out of the
intensive care unit at the hospital where he was admitted earlier
this month with a head injury, but remains in serious condition, a
spokesman said Monday.
   Day's ``vital signs are stable and he is showing some response
to visitors and members of his family. He is not speaking, but he
is improved,'' said Armen Markarian, spokesman for St. John's
Hospital.
   Day, 71, was hospitalized March 9 after falling at his Bel-Air
home. He underwent immediate surgery to relieve pressure on his
brain; a second operation for the same problem was performed March
19.
   Day was diagnosed last July as suffering from amyotropic lateral
sclerosis. The progressive nerve disorder, also known as Lou
Gehrig's disease, causes a loss of muscle control.
   Day, who was born Eugene Denis McNulty in New York City, began
his career with comedian Jack Benny in 1939. An accomplished tenor,
Day played the innocent foil to Benny's character on television and
radio, breaking into song to counter Benny's anger or tricking him
into letting him sing.
</TEXT>
