<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-Wisconsin     03-28 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Wisconsin,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Leans on Blue-Collar Workers for Wisconsin Primary Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says he can win Wisconsin's
pivotal Democratic primary ``because I've stood here with the meat
packers in Cudahy, the auto workers in Kenosha and the paper
workers in De Pere.''
   From Iowa's bankrupt farmers to laid-off appliance workers in
Illinois, Jackson has stood side-by-side with the nation's
displaced and disaffected and in the process forged a winning
coalition.
   Jackson's campaign for ``economic justice'' has touched a chord
and it may be enough to deliver another victory over Michael
Dukakis in Wisconsin next Tuesday, aides to both candidates said
Monday.
   Support from blue-collar workers is crucial to Jackson's chances
in Wisconsin since Jackson's core black constituency makes up only
3 percent of the state's population. Jackson consistently carries
about 10 percent of the white vote, but has moved beyond that in
some states, notably in heavily-white Vermont earlier this month
and on Saturday in Michigan, where he won some predominantly white
areas on top of black Detroit wards.
   Tony Tsakakis, a national campaign aide to Massachusetts Gov.
Dukakis, said Wisconsin is a two-man race. Even though he feels
Dukakis will win, Tsakakis said he could not rule out a Jackson
victory.
   ``It's going to be the reverand and us through the convention,''
said Tsakakis.
   Bob Burns, a member of Jackson's national staff working in
Wisconsin, said Jackson would rely heavily on labor support in a
push to win Wisconsin.
   ``In every race where we have competed, we felt we would come in
No. 1 or No. 2 and Wisconsin is no different,'' Burns said.
   Both men referred to a Milwaukee Sentinel poll released Monday
that showed Dukakis leading Jackson 28 percent to 25 percent among
likely Democratic voters.
   The poll was conducted March 17-22, before Jackson's weekend win
in Michigan.
   ``It is not a measure of our new-found momentum as our
rock-bottom strength,'' Burns said.
   Even Republican Gov. Tommy Thompson, a supporter of Vice
President George Bush, said Monday if he were a Democrat, he would
vote for Jackson.
   Under Wisconsin's open primary, Thompson legally could take a
Democratic ballot, but does not plan to do so.
   ``Just because he is a Democrat doesn't mean I can't like him,''
said Thompson, who joined Jackson earlier this month in Kenosha to
protest plans by Chrysler Corp. to close an auto plant there, a
move that will throw 5,500 people out of work.
   It is those auto workers in Kenosha, strikers at the Patrick
Cudahy meat packing plant in Cudahy and striking paper workers in
De Pere that Jackson is depending on to help him carry Wisconsin,
as he has done in other states.
   The day after Super Tuesday, Jackson was in the Chicago suburbs
of Cicero where workers were worried about the planned closing of a
General Electric plant thtat makes Hotpoint refrigerators. Jackson
was met under dreary, damp skies by a rally of about 200 people,
organized by the sheet metal workers union. They carried signs that
said, ``Jesse, help us save our jobs,'' and ``Unemployment, made by
GE.''
   Workers said they believed Jackson would make a difference for
them.
   ``Nothing has changed here. I've been working here 23 years. I
believe Jackson would make a change,'' said Mack Fundes.
   Phil Haney, a Kenosha auto worker who came to Milwaukee on
Saturday to see Jackson, said he felt the same way.
   ``He's been on the picket lines,'' Haney said.
   Haney said if Jackson were president, he would expect him to
push for legislation to promote more business investment at home
and help for workers displaced by plant closings and new
technologies.
</TEXT>
