<HEAD>Father Who Gave Up Life Preserver For Son Presumed Drowned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `A search ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
search resuming today. CORRECTS spelling of last name from Trenkel
to Trenkle throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father who gave up his life preserver to
save his son's life after their boat overturned and filled with
water in the swift Sandy River was still missing today and presumed
drowned.
   George Earl Trenkle, 40, of Blackfoot, Idaho, tossed a seat
cushion to his son, George Edward Trenkle, 18, after they and a
third man hit a log and were thrown from their boat into the frigid
water Saturday, Multnomah County sheriff's Deputy Bob Boertien said.
   The younger Trenkle said Sunday that he tried to throw the
cushion to his father after reaching safety, but he didn't have the
strength.
   ``I threw the thing to him, but I was so tired, it really didn't
go that far,'' Trenkle said.
   ``I could just see his head as he went around a bend,'' he
added. ``I yelled, `Dad!' a couple of times, and he said he would
be OK.''
   The third man in the boat, Roland Parkhurst, 40, of nearby
Gresham, was a paraplegic and was wearing a life jacket. Witnesses
pulled the younger Trenkle and Parkhurst from the river.
   The pair were taken to a hospital in Gresham, where they were
treated and released. The boat was found overturned and washed
ashore about a half-mile downstream from where it hit a submerged
log that almost destroyed its bow.
   A search for the elder Trenkle resumed late this morning.
   ``We were floating down river; my dad was rowing. We just got
started, and he was having trouble rowing. He was kind of new at
it,'' Trenkle said Sunday in a telephone interview with The
Oregonian newspaper from his uncle's house in Salem.
   After the boat overturned, Trenkle said he managed to climb on
top of it at one point. His father had hold of the boat, and
Parkhurst held his foot as they tried to make it to shore.
   ``Then we hit the rapids, and we all separated from the boat,''
Trenkle said.
   ``I was under water for quite a while.'' Then, he said, his
father pulled him up to the surface and gave him a seat cushion
that he had found.
   Trenkle, a high school senior, said his father worked as a fire
boss for the U.S. Bureau of Land Management, and was in Portland
for a business meeting. He said his father and Parkhurst had known
each other since high school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
