<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Guber     03-28 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Guber,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadway Producer Lee Guber Dead at 67</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer Lee Guber, who helped bring Broadway
entertainment to theaters and concert halls throughout the country,
has died of brain cancer. He was 67.
   Guber, who died at his Manhattan home Sunday, produced nearly a
dozen shows on Broadway, including productions of ``The King and
I,'' ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' ``Gypsy,'' ``I Do! I Do!'' and ``How
to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying.''
   He also headed a suburban entertainment chain that included the
Westbury Music Fair on Long Island, the Valley Forge Music Fair
outside Philadelphia, the Shady Grove Music Theater outside
Washington and the Painters Mill Music Fair in the suburbs of
Baltimore.
   Guber and his partner, Shelly Gross, booked such entertainers as
Judy Garland, Jack Benny, Sammy Davis Jr., Liberace and Stevie
Wonder. They also brought productions of Broadway musicals to
suburban theaters.
   Guber's last production, however, was one of several flops in
his career. ``Rags,'' a $5 million musical about immigrants, ran on
Broadway for only four performances before closing in August 1986.
   Guber was born in Philadelphia and met Gross at Central High
School there. With a third partner, Frank Ford, they began their
theatrical career in 1955 with productions at the Valley Forge
theater in Devon, Pa.
   Married three times, Guber divorced his second wife, broadcaster
Barbara Walters, in 1976 after a 13-year marriage.
   He is survived by his third wife, Lois Wyse, whom he married in
1982, as well as by three children from his prior marriages, two
stepchildren, a sister, a brother and eight grandchildren.
   Funeral services are planned Wednesday at Temple Emanu-El in
Manhattan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
