<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Mideast     03-28 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US `Regrets' Israeli Moves On West Bank and Gaza</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department criticized Israel on
Monday for sealing off the West Bank and Gaza for three days in
expectation of major demonstrations called by the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   ``We regret the decision because of the impact it will have on
commerce, on visits with family members and the press,'' spokesman
Charles E. Redman said.
   Last Friday, the department advised U.S. citizens to avoid
travel to the areas because of continuing disturbances. This also
was likely to affect local business because tourists are attracted
to the West Bank during Holy Week.
   Israel's decision will keep Israelis and Arabs from entering the
territories. The only exceptions will be the 65,000 Jewish settlers
who live there among 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs.
   A total of 119 Palestinians and an Israeli soldier have died
since violent protests broke out in the West Bank and Gaza on Dec.
9. Secretary of State George P. Shultz will launch a new drive in
Jerusalem on Sunday to hold negotiations for Palestinian self-rule
beginning May 1.
   He plans two stops in Israel and in Jordan, the two key
countries, and also stops in Syria, Saudi Arabia and Egypt.
Spokesman Redman said Shultz would like to meet with Palestinians
while he is in the region.
   On Tuesday, he is scheduled to meet here with representatives of
the Arab League, which is a group of the 21 Arab countries and the
PLO.
   Shultz will leave Washington on Thursday and spend more than two
days in Rome meeting with Italian officials and attending religious
services.
   Redman reaffirmed, meanwhile, that U.S. policy prohibits
``dealing'' with the PLO as well as negotiating or recognizing the
group until it accepts Israel's right to exist and disavows
terrorism.
   The spokesman said Shultz's meeting here Saturday with two
American members of the Palestine National Council did not conflict
with the 13-year-old policy, which also was written into law in
1984.
   The council considers itself the legislative arm of the
Palestinian nationalist movement. One of the two
Palestinian-Americans, Edward Said, said he informed PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat before he and Ibrahim Abu-Lughod met with Shultz, and
Arafat approved.
   Israel protested the meeting.
   Redman said the PLO and the council were not ``synonymous'' and
that ``our restrictions on dealing with the PLO remain as always.''
   The spokesman said Shultz's meeting with Said and Abu-Lughod,
who are university professors, was ``not a negotiating format.''
   Shultz presented his proposal for negotiations to Arab and
Israeli leaders four weeks ago and asked for a reply by mid-March.
So far, only Egypt has endorsed his plan.
   Still, Redman said the proposal was ``under serious and active
consideration by the parties.'' He said Shultz would emphasize the
plan was a fair and balanced approach to the 40-year Arab-Israeli
dispute.
   ``Nobody has said no,'' Redman said. ``We are going to continue
to work on this proposal to see if we can't get something going.''
   Asked about a report that Shultz would take with him an
invitation to a United Nations conference on the Middle East to
begin April 15, the spokesman said: ``It sounds pretty flaky.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
