<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Okinawa-Panama     03-28 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Okinawa-Panama,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Carrier To Pass Through Panama Canal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon, breaking its normal silence
about ship movements, said Monday the helicopter carrier USS
Okinawa would begin a transit of the Panama Canal on Tuesday.
   The Defense Department described the movement in a statement as
``routine'' and something ``which has been planned for several
months.''
   The Pentagon said the statement was issued in hopes of avoiding
rumors and speculation in Panama about the carrier's presence in
the waterway.
   The Reagan administration has been applying economic pressure in
hopes of ousting strongman Gen. Manuel A. Noriega, but has made
clear it is not taking any military moves against the general.
   The Okinawa is steaming through the canal on the last leg of an
around-the-world journey that saw it deploy in the Persian Gulf to
support mine-sweeping operations. The carrier dropped off its
mine-sweeping helicopters earlier this month in Norfolk, Va., and
is now destined for its home port in San Diego.
</TEXT>
