<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Protest     03-28 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Protest,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>60 Protesters Arrested at Iraqi Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 60 people Monday during a
demonstration in which protesters tried to force their way into the
Iraqi Embassy and hurled stones through the windows.
   The crowd was protesting Iraq's alleged use of chemical weapons
in Kurdish regions in its 7{-year-old war with Iran.
   Interior Minister Karl Blecha met with the Iraqi ambassador,
Wahbi A. Razak al-Qaraguli, and expressed the government's regrets,
said Karl Newole, spokesman for the minister.
   Protesters and police said shots were fired when some in the
crowd tried to force their way into the embassy. Police spokesman
Martin Muellgassner said no one was injured.
   Muellgassner said it was not clear who fired or what kind of
weapon was used. He reported four to six shots, fired inside the
building.
   On Austrian radio, a protester who was not identified said an
embassy employee fired into the street with an automatic weapon.
   A statement from a group of Kurdish groups, carried by the
Austria Press Agency, protested the shooting. It said a delegation
of demonstrators had wanted to enter the embassy to protest ``the
massacre of Kurds in Iraq.''
   Iran accused Iran last week of dropping cyanide and mustard gas
bombs March 16 and 17 on three Kurdish towns in Iraq that killed
5,000 people and wounded 5,000. The towns had been captured in an
Iranian offensive.
   One of Monday's demonstrators told Austrian radio a delegation
of three or four people had wanted to present a protest to embassy
officials. The Kurdish statement said the shots were fired as the
delegation tried to enter the building.
   People gathered outside the embassy at 10:20 a.m. in a heavy
rain. Some carried posters saying, ``Stop The Massacre,'' or
``Freedom For Kurds.''
   Muellgassner said the crowd surged toward the embassy and five
to 10 people pushed through the door, but embassy personnel managed
to force them back. The four policemen regularly posted at the
embassy were outside, he said.
   Newole said the Iraqi ambassador asked Blecha for increased
protection and Blecha said an investigation would be conducted to
determine whether it was necessary.
   According to police, protesters threw stones through the windows
after the shots were fired. A demonstrator interviewed by Austrian
radio said the crowd began the protest ``with peaceful intentions.''
   Demonstrators said about 70 people took part, but some fled when
shots were fired.
   Some of the Kurds allegedly wounded in the Iraqi attacks were
expected in Vienna on Tuesday for medical treatment. They
originially were to have arrived Monday and there was no
explanation for the delay.
</TEXT>
