<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Synagogue Defaced,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2 Synagogues In Marked With Graffiti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graffiti will remain on the walls
of a synagogue through Passover as a reminder that anti-Jewish
attitudes remain widespread, a rabbi said.
   Some of the red scrawling at Temple Beth-El was partially erased
Sunday, but some will remain through the holiday, which begins
Friday and marks Jewish deliverance from slavery, said Rabbi Alan
Cohen.
   Meanwhile, police have assigned an investigator to the vandalism
at Temple Beth-El and Temple Beth David in Palm Beach Gardens, but
there were no leads and no arrests, Sgt. Michael Fulk said Monday.
The temples were defaced over the weekend.
   Acts of vandalism against Jews, their institutions and property
rose nationally in 1987 but declined in Florida and Palm Beach
County, according to the Anti-Defamation League, which monitors
racist incidents. Sixteen anti-Semitic acts were reported in Palm
Beach County last year, down from 17 the year before.
