<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorkerNotice     03-28 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worker Notice,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filibuster Continues on Bill Requiring Worker Notice of Toxics
Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of a bill to warn as many as
300,000 workers a year that they risk cancer or other diseases from
job exposure to toxic chemicals failed Monday on a third attempt to
stop a Republican filibuster.
   Sens. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
the chief sponsors of the union-sought legislation, mustered only
41 of the 60 votes needed to end debate and force a vote on the
measure itself.
   The bill is aimed at addressing what the National Institute of
Occupational Safety and Health estimates is one in every four
Americans who has been exposed to carcinogens at work, most of them
unaware of it.
   ``This bill is about people getting cancer in the workplace and
learning about it too late to do anything about it,'' Metzenbaum
said. ``The American Cancer Society estimates we can save 250,000
lives in the next 10 years by implementing it.''
   A fourth and possibly final attempt at ending the filibuster is
scheduled Tuesday. Supporters of the bill believe if they get
another 14 or 15 votes then, they can prevent Senate Majority
Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., from giving up on the effort to win
its passage this year.
   A virtually identical measure was passed by the House on a
225-186 vote last November. Administration officials have said they
would urge President Reagan to veto if it reaches his desk.
   Although the filibuster primarily is the work of Republican
Sens. Orrin Hatch of Utah and Dan Quayle of Indiana, a small group
of southern Democrats who want to avoid a showdown vote are helping
keep it alive.
   Metzenbaum and Kennedy were able to get just 33 votes last week
for ending the filibuster. At least one southern Democrat and a few
liberal Republicans who had voted with Hatch and Quayle last week
voted with Metzenbaum and Kennedy on Monday.
   The bill would establish a panel of seven scientific experts to
identify the most hazardous substances in workplaces and the groups
of employees most susceptible to disabling diseases because of
exposure to them.
   The National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health would
be required to notify between 100,000 and 300,000 of those workers
every year at an annual cost of $25 million. Employers then would
be required to finance medical monitoring programs for them at a
cost of up to $250 each annually.
   If a physician recommends transferring a monitored employee to
less hazardous work, he or she would have to be paid the same level
of wages and benefits to them in the new job. If no other job is
available, the employee is entitled to full wages for up to a year
after leaving work.
   In addition to unions, the bill is supported by public health
groups, the chemical and electronic industries and several major
companies, most of which have instituted such notification programs
on their own.
   However, it is opposed by small businesses and large trade
associations such as the National Association of Manufacturers and
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which claim the bill would expose
companies to liability suits from current and former employees.
   ``If this bill passes, there is going to be a liability crisis
in this country like we've never seen before,'' Hatch said.
``You're going to have billions and billions of dollars in
lawsuits.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1716EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     03-28 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine City Councilmen Injured In Bomb Attack In The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists threw three bombs
into a city council building in the southern town of Matara on
Monday, injuring nine councilors, police said.
   A police statement issued in Colombo said the attack was
launched by youths riding motor cycles in Matara, about 88 miles
south of the capital.
   Nine council men were wounded, including four of them seriously,
the statement said. The victims belonged to different political
parties, including the governing United National Party.
   The attack was carried out by six members of the outlawed
Peoples' Liberation Front, an ultra-nationalist Sinhalese group,
the statement said. The group has vowed to kill anyone who supports
an Indian-sponsored peace accord signed in July. The accord aimed
at ending the Tamil ethnic conflict.
   Sinhalese extremists claim the accord gives too many concessions
to the Tamils.
   The Peoples' Front has killed more than 220 people in the past
five months, according to official statements made last week. Many
of the victims have been members of the majority Sinhalese
community, who have supported the accord or not expressed
opposition to it.
   Meanwhile, residents in the eastern town of Batticaloa said in
telephone interviews that tension was increasing in the east after
Tamil youth looted and burned 25 Moslem-owned shops on Saturday in
Kalmunai. Most of the Moslem shops closed down after the arson
attacks.
   A Roman Catholic priest, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said: ``The whole area is very tense after the attack. Large
contingents of Indian troops backed by helicopters are all over the
place.''
   More than 50,000 Indian peacekeeing troops are in the eastern
and northern Sri Lanka to disarm Tamil militants who oppose the
peace pact. They have been battling the rebels since last October.
   Moslem leaders, including Moslem Religious Affairs Minister
Mohamed Haniffa Mohamed, have claimed that Indian troops were
responsible for the attack on the shops on Saturday.
   Sources in the government said that Mohamed and three other
Moslem lawmakers told the high-level National Security meeting that
Indian peacekeeping troops were involved.
   The attack took place after the troops had cordoned off the area
and imposed a curfew, the lawmakers told the meeting, according to
the sources.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people, most
of whom are Sinhalese. Tamils say they are discriminated against by
the Sinhalese, who control the government and the military.
   Tamil militants are fighting for a separate homeland in the
Northern and Eastern Provinces where most of the Tamils live.
</TEXT>
