<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     03-28 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Voters to Join His Rising Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson poked fun at his
better-financed Democratic presidential rivals on Monday and urged
voters to catch the ``fever of hope'' and join his own rising White
House campaign.
   Jackson, who scored a landslide victory over Michael Dukakis in
the Michigan caucuses on Saturday, is far behind in the polls in
advance of Tuesday's contest in Connecticut.
   But he is in a neck-and-neck race with Dukakis in The Associated
Press national delegate count, and has received more votes in the
primary contests to date than any of his rivals.
   He said his campaign lacks the financial ``big boulders'' that
some of his opponents can claim.
   ``I have little rocks,'' he said. ``But I throw them straight.''
   ``We have the most gold and silver medals'' in the primaries and
caucuses so far, Jackson proclaimed. ``We can win.''
   He said his campaign has a ``small budget, a strong message and
a clear vision.''
   Jackson began his day by making it clear that he expects the
party to nominate him if he winds up the primary season with the
most delegates and the most votes.
   ``Becoming the nominee is logical and proper'' if he achieves
those goals, he said in an interview on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America.''
   He questioned the idea that party leaders _ many of whom view
him as a sure loser in a general election campaign _ might turn to
another contender.
   ``They would not have given me the nomination. I would have
earned it from the people,'' he said.
   ``I don't believe in collecting a group of favorite sons, and
then selecting one, the people elect what's left,'' he added.
   Jackson did not address the issue of Democratic Party acceptance
as he closed out his low-budget, high-energy Connecticut campaign.
   But in stops in Middletown, at a crime and drug-ridden area of
Waterbury and a well-attended outdoor rally in Hartford, he managed
to ridicule better-financed opponents.
   ``We don't have no Rolls Royces and no big stretch limousines on
the road to the White House. We're walking but we know the road
better,'' he said.
   In another jab, he said, ``we're not getting endorsements from
the top down. We're getting votes from the bottom up.''
   Jackson stressed his message that the powerless can gain power
if they have hope.
   He said people in wheelchairs, the homeless and others who come
to hear him ``have the fever of hope.''
   ``There's nothing more powerful in the world than the people
whose hope has been raised.''
   In his stop in The Mt. Olive Church of God and Christ in
Waterbury, Jackson drew his loudest cheers when he condemned drug
use. ``We the people must say down with dope and up with hope,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
