<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra-Israel Bjt   03-28 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra-Israel, Bjt,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Hands Over Classified Documents To Independent Counsel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has handed over classified documents to
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh for his Iran-Contra
investigation under a cooperation agreement reached after year-long
negotiations, an Israeli official said Monday.
   In return, Walsh apparently agreed to revoke the subpoenas he
issued to four Israelis who arranged the 1985 and 1986 shipment of
U.S.-made anti-tank and anti-aircraft missiles to Iran, the
official and a U.S. lawyer indicated.
   ``He will get what he wants without us having to give up what we
wanted,'' said the Israeli official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Melvin Rishe, a lawyer representing the Israeli government, said
``we have reached terms of how we would proceed, making litigation
unnecessary.''
   Israel's government wanted the subpoenas dropped, contending
that all four Israelis were acting under its orders and thus were
immune from prosecution and questioning by U.S. officials.
   The agreement with Walsh is ``on a government-to-government''
basis, according to Israeli embassy spokesman Yossi Gal, which
means any questions for the four must be channeled through official
Israeli representatives.
   Walsh and the Israeli Embassy issued brief statements announcing
the cooperation agreement, but said the contents will remain
classified.
   ``The government of the state of Israel and the office of the
independent counsel have signed an agreement covering the
cooperation of the government of Israel in the Iran-Contra
investigation,'' Walsh said in a prepared statement.
   ``Independent counsel Walsh expressed satisfaction with the
agreement and said his office looks forward to continued
cooperation with the state of Israel,'' the statement said. The
Israeli statement was almost identical.
   The documents handed over to Walsh include detailed financial
and historical chronologies prepared by Israel for the
congressional Iran-Contra committees last summer, said the Israeli
official.
   When Israel gave the chronologies to Congress, it stipulated
that Walsh be denied access to the documents because of his refusal
to grant immunity to the four Israelis.
   Along with the documents, Walsh has also been given written
answers to the questions posed last year by the congressional
investigators with regard to the chronologies, the official said.
   The documents are expected to help Walsh answer some of his
questions about Israel's Swiss bank account, which handled the
funds for the shipments to Iran.
   Walsh wanted the information to help him corroborate his case
against former White House aides Oliver North and John Poindexter,
as well as businessmen Richard Secord and his partner Albert Hakim.
All four have been indicted on charges of defrauding the U.S.
government through the arms sales and the diversion of profits to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   Last year, Walsh subpoenaed Israeli businessmen Yaakov Nimrodi
and Al Schwimmer, as well as former foreign ministry director David
Kimche and government counter-terrorism adviser Amiram Nir. Nir
resigned from his post last week.
   The agreement was finalized 10 days ago by two senior government
representatives who held talks in Washington with Walsh and his
staff. The Israeli government approved the accord, the Israeli
official said.
   ``The negotiations were difficult,'' said Walsh spokesman Jim
Wieghart. ``Israel is a sovereign state with certain national
security interests, which they have to defend. We recognized that,
but on the other hand, we had our needs in this investigation,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
