<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlackHeroine     03-28 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Heroine,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Officials Pay Homage to Early Settler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Biddy Mason, a former slave who became a
wealthy landowner and co-founder of the city's first black church,
won recognition from civic officials 97 years after her death.
   ``She is an example of the courage of black women in the early
days of this city,'' Mayor Tom Bradley said during a Palm Sunday
service at Mrs. Mason's gravesite. ``Our young people need to know
about her.''
   The philanthropist, who helped found the First African Methodist
Episcopal Church and the city's first elementary school for black
children, was buried in an unmarked grave and nearly forgotten
after her death in 1891.
   Bradley and about 3,000 members of the church unveiled a
tombstone hailing Mrs. Mason as a humanitarian.
   Mrs. Mason was born a slave in Mississippi in 1818 and, with her
three daughters, became the property of a Mormon family that moved
to Utah. She and her family later walked to California, where she
won her freedom in 1856.
   A midwife by trade, Mrs. Mason accumulated vast amounts of land,
often as payment from clients.
   ``When I was going through school, we never talked about
Biddy,'' said Linda Cox, a Mason descendant. But her 9-year-old
daughter, Cheryl, came home from school one day recently and said:
``Mommy, part of our family is in the history books,'' Mrs. Cox
said.
</TEXT>
