<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TreasuryBills     03-28 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasury Bills,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields Mixed on Short-Term T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in Monday's auction, with the rates on
three-month bills declining while rates on six-month bills
increased.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 5.69 percent, down from 5.76 percent
last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 6.0 percent, up from 5.96 percent last
week.
   The rates on three-month bills were the lowest since they
averaged 5.65 percent on March 14. The six-month rate was the
highest since these bills averaged 6.03 percent on Feb. 16.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 5.85 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,856.20 and 6.27 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,696.70.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 6.77 percent last
week from 6.63 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
