<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SteigerTrial     03-28 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steiger Trial,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extortion Trial of Former Key Mecham Aide Starts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began Monday in the
political extortion trial of Sam Steiger, an ex-congressman and
former aide to Gov. Evan Mecham.
   Steiger, 59, was charged last fall with one count of theft by
extortion, accused of trying to influence the vote of a member of
the state Board of Pardons and Paroles.
   Judge Ronald S. Reinstein of Maricopa County Superior Court told
prospective jurors that the trial probably would last until
mid-April.
   Steiger is accused of having told parole board member Ronald D.
Johnson in an Oct. 1 telephone conversation that unless he voted
against a motion that day seeking the resignation of parole board
executive director Patricia Costello, he would lose his position on
the parole board or as a part-time justice of the peace.
   Johnson voted with three other board members to oust Ms.
Costello, who had Steiger's and Mecham's backing, and she stepped
down that day.
   The next day, Steiger allegedly sent Johnson a letter saying
Johnson's permission to serve as a part-time justice of the peace
was revoked and also that he could be fired from the parole board
if he defied the order.
   A key to the prosecution's case will be three tape recordings of
telephone converstations with Steiger. Reinstein ruled last week
that prosecutor Michael Cudahy, an assistant state attorney
general, could use the tapes.
   Defense attorney Thomas Karas had argued against their
admissibility, saying that they were secretly taped in calls to
Steiger at his home in Prescott and therefore violated his privacy.
   Steiger, who was paid more than $77,000 a year as a special
assistant to Mecham until his resignation Nov. 9, faces two to five
years in prison if convicted of the class four felony.
   Until he resigned about a month after his October indictment, he
served as one of several top aides to Mecham, who took office in
January 1987.
</TEXT>
