<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SurrogateMom 1stLd-Writethru a0633 03-28 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Surrogate Mom, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby M's Dad: Don't Let Child See Surrogate Mom For Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to update with afternoon testimony; minor
editing throughout to shorten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NR2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angry and bitter William Stern
testified Monday that Baby M should be kept from her biological
mother for several years to protect the child from emotional harm
and exploitation.
   Stern, testifying in what is expected to be the final legal
chapter of the 2-year-old dispute, characterized surrogate mother
Mary Beth Whitehead-Gould as untrustworthy and capable of
undermining his relationship with the child, legally known as
Melissa Stern.
   ``Mary Beth will do anything and say anything to get her way,''
Stern said in 2{ hours of emotional testimony that ended with him
crying.
   The hearing, expected to last several days, was ordered by the
New Jersey Supreme Court in its landmark Feb. 3 decision that
declared surrogacy-for-pay illegal and restored Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould's parental rights, but left intact a judge's order
awarding custody of the child to the Sterns.
   Stern and his wife, Elizabeth, of Tenafly, decided to have a
child through a surrogate mother because they feared Mrs. Stern,
42, who suffers from a mild form of multiple sclerosis, would
suffer complications during pregnancy.
   Mrs. Stern testified the possibility of both sides cooperating
in the future was remote.
   ``We don't share common values with Mary Beth, we don't think
about things in the same way and we don't react to situations in
the same way,'' Mrs. Stern testified. ``We are poles apart.''
   The Sterns are seeking to cut off contact between Melissa and
Mrs. Whitehead-Gould, perhaps until the child's 10th birthday. Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould now visits the child once a week for two hours
under supervision at a children's social services center.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould is seeking two, eight-hour weekly visits at
her home, later expanded to include weekends, half the summer and
some holidays. She was accompanied to court by her second husband,
Wall Street accountant Dean Gould, with whom she is expecting a
child.
   The Sterns agreed to pay $10,000 to Mrs. Whitehead-Gould to bear
them a child and Mrs. Whitehead-Gould was artificially inseminated
with Stern's sperm.
   After the baby was born _ she turned 2 on Sunday _ Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould changed her mind and refused to surrender the child.
   In testimony Monday, Stern said Melissa should be protected,
likening her to a sapling that needs to secure its roots.
   ``If anything is done to interrupt those roots, I'm afraid
Melissa does not have much of a future,'' said Stern, a biochemist.
   He said that immediate contact with Mrs. Whitehead-Gould could
``force Melissa into the situation where she would have to choose
between us.''
   Stern said he and his wife have formed a warm, loving
relationship with Melissa. And his wife testified, `To precious
little Melissa, I know I'm her mother.''
   Under two hours of cross-examination by Mrs. Whitehead-Gould's
attorney, Joel Siegal, Stern said he feared she would exploit the
child by writing a book that could lead to a photo of Melissa on
the book jacket, a film, a videocassette and even a promotional
tour for the book.
   But Stern acknowledged that Melissa does not seem to have been
harmed so far by her contact with Mrs. Whitehead-Gould.
   His testimony ended with questions from the judge on what
religion the child would be exposed to. Stern, who is Jewish and
whose relatives other than his parents all died in the Holocaust,
broke into tears. He drank a cup of water and composed himself,
saying he expected to expose the child to a Unitarian church. Mrs.
Stern is not Jewish.
</TEXT>
