<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--DEATesting     03-28 0129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--DEA Testing,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Tests 28 Headquarters Employees for Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Drug Enforcement Administration on Monday
tested 75 headquarters employees for drugs, marking the start of
random drug testing procedures covering all 5,000 of the agency's
workers.
   The DEA has been testing agent trainees for drugs since June
1986.
   The agency has 2,800 agents and 2,200 support personnel.
   Agents found to be using drugs illegally will be dismissed.
Non-agents in less sensitive positions may face suspension or
reprimands for first-time offenses, said DEA deputy administrator
Thomas C. Kelly.
   The agency's Office of Professional Responsibility will conduct
inquiries when test results suggest show drug use.
   All 650 tests administered to the agency's trainees since
mid-1986 have failed to turn up any evidence of illegal drug use.
