<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Allred-Friars     03-28 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allred-Friars,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Steamed at Friars Club, Goes to State for Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first female member of the
Friars Club of Beverly Hills filed a sex discrimination complaint
Monday because she is being denied use of its health club.
   ``Obviously, such second-class citizenship within the club could
deter many women from joining,'' said attorney Gloria Allred,
noting she pays the same dues as male club members.
   ``The fight for women's equality will not end until women are
permitted both in the board rooms and the steam rooms,'' she said.
   The state Board of Equalization can disallow business tax
expenses at private clubs that discriminate under a rule that took
effect Jan. 1. Equalization board member Conway Collis said he
wanted to inspect the Friars Club facilities this week.
   When Allred became the Friars' first female dues-paying member
in its 32-year history in May, she was greeted warmly by comedian
and Friars President Milton Berle. Frank Sinatra and Dean Martin
are also members, and President Reagan is a past president.
   The Friars Club is primarily a theatrical social club.
   In January, Allred asked Friars officials about arrangements for
women wishing to use the sauna, steam room and whirlpool. There are
four women in the club, but Allred is the only one who wants to use
the health club.
   ``There is no legal requirement on the part of the club to
afford you the use of the health club facilities,'' Friars Club
legal chairman William Sarnoff said in a letter of reply.
   There was no immediate comment from the Friars Club on Monday,
and a message was left for Sarnoff at club.
</TEXT>
