<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Government     03-28 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Government,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China To Overhaul Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China announced Monday a major reorganization of
its top bureaucracy to cut the state's role in direct management of
the economy, eliminate 10,000 jobs and modernize operations.
   State Councillor Song Ping, head of the Communist Party
Organization Department, said 14 ministries under the State Council
will be abolished, one will be reorganized, and 10 new ministries
will be set up.
   The State Council is equivalent to China's Cabinet.
   Song told a meeting of the National People's Congress, China's
legislature, that the reorganization will mean a net reduction of
five organs under the State Council, and is to be accomplished
within three months of approval by the present session of the
congress.
   The reorganization will lay the groundwork for further
restructuring of the State Council, Song said.
   He said the government will no longer manage enterprises
directly, as it has under Soviet-style central planning. Government
departments instead will be responsible for general planning,
finances, supervision and regulation.
   The changes, according to Song, will be aimed at overcoming such
problems as inefficiency, overstaffing, overlapping functions,
overly rigid low-level management, insufficient overall control and
lack of clarity about duties.
   He said the the staff directly under the State Council will be
reduced from 50,000 to 40,000.
   The 10,000 people to be pared from State Council payrolls will
be transferred to units handling taxation, finance, prices,
auditing, supervision, statistics and law enforcement. Many will
join companies and institutions engaged in information, consultancy
and research, he said.
   The National People's Congress, which convened last week, is
also to pass a law guaranteeing the rights of factory managers to
run their plants without undue interference from the government.
   The 10 new units to be created are the ministries of personnel,
labor, materials, transportation, energy, construction, aeronautics
and astronautics industry, water resources, machine building and
electronics and the State Planning Commission.
   The planning commission will be comprised of the present
planning and economic commissions. Song said the commission will be
in charge of formulating China's economic and social development
strategies and will no longer be involved in direct management of
trade and industrial operations.
   Economic expert Yao Yilin, vice premier and head of the present
State Planning Commission, is expected to head the new, more
powerful commission.
   The Labor and Personnel Ministry will be split into two
ministries, with the new Personnel Ministry in charge of
introducing a civil servant system.
   The new Transportation Ministry will combine the ministries of
railways and communications and the State Air Transport Control
Administration.
   The proposed Energy Ministry was described by Song as a
superbody encompassing the work of the ministries of the coal
industry, petroleum industry and nuclear industry.
   Xinhua News Agency, the state news agency, will become a
separate institution under the State Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
