<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     03-28 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Politician Arrested in Explosion Case, Expelled from
Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ An opposition leader was arrested
in connection with an explosion at a bridge and two Americans
staying with him are under house arrest, according to party and
other reports Monday.
   Joseph Douze, second in command of the centrist Christian
Democratic Party, was arrested Saturday and charged in the
explosion March 22 under the Croix des Bouquets Bridge, party
leader Sylvio Claude said. The blast caused no damage or injuries.
   Claude said Douze, a physician with dual Haitian and American
citizenship, had been planted in the party by the government and he
had been expelled.
   Douze, provisional vice president of the party, was shown on
government television Saturday night during an army search of his
home.
   Nancy Horn of Wells Tannery, Pa., and James Gunnels of Macon,
Ga., told The Associated Press by telephone they were friends of
Douze's staying at his home in Thomassin, outside Port-au-Prince.
   Ms. Horn said she was an associate of Douze and had been in
Haiti since 1967. Gunnels said he was a visiting businessman.
   The officer who directed the search of Douze's home said on
television Sunday the Americans ``have a certain responsibility in
the affair,'' but did not elaborate.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jeffrey Lite said consular officials had
been in contact with the Americans. Lite said they were forbidden
to leave the house, but he did not know whether they would be
formally arrested.
   Anaise Chavenet, spokeswoman for the Information Ministry, told
the AP the Americans were under surveillance, not house arrest,
while the army investigates whether they were involved in the
bombing.
   Both Americans denied knowledge of the explosion.
   ``I know nothing about this affair,'' Gunnels said. ``I was just
a guest in his home for a few days.''
   According to Ms. Horn, Douze is in his mid-40s and spent several
years in the United States during the Duvalier family dictatorship,
which lasted from 1957 to February 1986.
   Claude accused President Leslie Manigat's government of planting
people in his party with instructions to discredit and destroy it.
Claude, a Protestant clergymen, was one of the four most popular
presidential candidates in Nov. 29 elections that were suspended
because of violence.
   In its report Sunday, Television Nationale said Douze was
arrested for possession of detonators, wiring for explosives, a
remote control detonating device and automatic rifles.
   Jocelin Brochard, a former army corporal and the Christian
Democrats head of security, and two women were arrested last
Wednesday in connection with the bridge explosion.
   Several sticks of dynamite, two assault rifles and a large bag
of marijuana were found on the roof of the women's home in Bel-Air,
a Port-au-Prince slum, police said.
   Brochard said on state televison that Douze supplied the weapons.
   Claude denied knowing Brochard or Douze were involved in the
bombing, and said some party members who advocated violence had
been expelled in the past.
</TEXT>
