<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarketShootings     03-28 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Market Shootings,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Suspect In Market Massacre Turns Himself In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GERRY EVERDING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspect in the slayings of five people in a
supermarket last year turned himself in to federal marshals Monday,
authorities said.
   Donnie Blankenship entered the U.S. marshal's office in the
Federal Courthouse at midday and said he wanted to have his bond
lifted, Assistant U.S. Attorney Frederick Buckles said.
   Blankenship was jailed a short time later, Buckles said.
   Police began searching for Blankenship on Friday after a grand
jury indicted him and another man on five counts of murder each in
the slayings at a National supermarket on the city's north side
Sept. 4.
   One suspect, Marvin Jennings, 27, of Overland, was arrested
Friday. Blankenship, 26, of Hanley Hills, had last been seen Friday
night in north St. Louis.
   Investigators believe two men entered the supermarket after it
closed, possibly by posing as a cleaning crew. A security guard was
taken by surprise and killed. Six other employees were ordered to
lie on the floor and were shot in the back of the head. Two people
survived.
   Until about two weeks ago, Blankenship had been jailed since
November on a charge of felony possession of a firearm, a
.38-caliber revolver believed to be the one taken from the security
guard during the robbery, Buckles said. Buckles said Blankenship
had previously been convicted of assaulting a postal service
employee.
   Blankenship was in custody on the weapons charges until about
two weeks ago, when he used his aunt's house to make a $10,000 bond
and was released, police said.
   Blankenship was arrested after police found the revolver in the
trunk of a car that had been stopped for speeding. The driver of
the vehicle said he had bought the gun from Blankenship, his
nephew, in late September, police said.

</TEXT>
