<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Pena-Contras     03-28 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pena-Contras,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Disavows Knowledge of Aid's Bid To Sell Weapons to Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright said Monday he was
unaware that his friend and adviser, Richard Pena, had tried to
sell weapons to the Contras through former White House aide Lt.
Col. Oliver L. North's secret Contra aid operation.
   ``I don't know a thing in the world about that,'' Wright,
D-Texas, said when asked by reporters about an arms-sale offer made
by Pena in August 1986, three months before disclosure of the
Iran-Contra weapons and money affair shut down the North network.
   Wright said if Pena was involved in such activity, it was ``at a
time when he wasn't directly working with me.''
   The speaker has a record of opposition to U.S. military aid to
the Contra rebels tyring to overthrow the Nicaraguan government. He
also has been active in working toward a negotiated peace in
Nicaragua.
   In an Aug. 15, 1986, letter, Pena wrote to a front company set
up by North's associate, Richard Miller, offering to procure
grenades, bombs, mines and boots from two South American companies.
   The letter went to World Affairs Counselors, a Cayman Islands
front company formed by Miller and his partner, Frank Gomez, to
handle their Contra transactions for North.
   Wright said he first learned of the matter when contacted last
week by The Associated Press, which obtained a copy of Pena's
letter.
   He said he knew of no activity by Pena that was ``unethical or
illegal or at all dishonest.''
   He said Pena was a friend and ``very knowledgeable person''
whose Spanish speaking ability has helped Wright pick up
conversational details the speaker sometimes misses regarding
Central American issues.
   Pena has been one of Wright's advisers on Central America over
the past several years and as recently as January was the Texas
Democrat's paid emissary to the region as the warring factions
wrangled over starting cease-fire talks, Wright aide Marshall Lynam
said. He said Pena was on the speaker's payroll for a few days on
each of three occasions.
   Pena now works for a lobbying firm, Cassidy and Associates. His
office said he was on vacation and had not checked in for messages
as of Monday.
   Pena was deposed by the congressional committees investigating
the secret sale of U.S. weapons to Iran and the diversion of funds
to the Contras. Pena told investigators he contacted Miller in
hopes of making a deal for part of the $70 million in renewed
Contra military aid that Congress approved in the fall of 1986,
according to a Capitol Hill source who read Pena's deposition.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
deposition contained no mention of Wright or North. Pena said he
knew Miller was involved with the Contras.
   Pena indicated to investigators that he thought he could offer
the Contras a better deal than they would get through other U.S.
purchasing routes, the source said.
   It was unclear why Pena would have gone to Miller, a
non-government businessman, and the Cayman company to arrange the
deal rather than through U.S. government channels.
   Pena worked as a House Foreign Affairs Committee staff
consultant from August 1982 to November 1985, a job for which
Wright recommended him.
   One former staff member for the congressional Iran-Contra
investigating committees said the committee staff decided not to
pursue the Pena matter because it appeared to be an isolated
incident, rather than an integral part of the North network.
   Miller pleaded guilty in the Iran-Contra case, along with
conservative fund-raiser Carl ``Spitz'' Channell, to conspiring
with North to defraud the government by raising money through a
tax-exempt foundation to purchase weapons for the Contras.
   Miller worked with North, then a National Security Council aide,
raising private money to help the Contras during the congressional
ban on U.S. aid.
   Miller's company, International Business Communications, routed
nearly $3 million through the Caymans, which was disbursed at
North's direction to the rebel effort, the Iran-Contra committees'
report said.
   North has been charged along with President Reagan's former
national security adviser, Rear Adm. John M. Poindexter, and two
other men with conspiring to defraud the United States of $17
million in Iran arms sale proceeds and for operating a secret
Contra assistance program during the aid ban.
</TEXT>
