<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalBriefs     03-28 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama Democratic Chairman Exploring Bloc Vote for Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Alabama Democratic
Party said Monday he is exploring the possibility of forming a
Southern group of uncommitted delegates to endorse an ``electable''
presidential candidate.
   ``We've got to keep one eye, if not two eyes, on the November
general election,'' said John Baker of Montgomery. ``I'm tired of
the Democratic Party having a ticket that can't carry but one or
two states. I'm embarrassed by losing four out of the last five
elections.''
   The party chairman hopes to find 50 to 100 Southern ``super
delegates'' who are interested in making a joint endorsement.
Unlike delegates elected in the Super Tuesday primary, the party
officials and others dubbed super delegates are not committed to a
particular candidate.
   Baker sent letters to Alabama's 12 super delegates and to 13
Southern party chairman to see if they were interested in trying to
make a joint endorsement.
   ``It's possible this group could make a commitment at the same
time. That would be a tremendous boost to someone,'' Baker said.
But it's too early at this point to say which of the Democratic
candidates might be electable in November, he added.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Super Tuesday TV Coverage Poor, Analyst Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>Washington (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lead-off presidential caucuses received
twice as much television coverage as all 20 Super Tuesday contests
this year on network evening newscasts, a media analyst says.
   Robert Lichter, co-director of the Center for Media and Public
Affairs, said the Super Tuesday primaries and caucuses also got
short shrift compared to the New Hampshire primary on Feb. 16.
   Iowans chose 89 GOP and Democratic delegates in their Feb. 8
caucuses, which were the subject of 105 stories, Lichter said. In
New Hampshire only 40 delegates were chosen, and more than 80
stories were aired.
   Super Tuesday, by contrast, had 2,056 delegates at stake but the
three major networks ran only 53 stories, Lichter said.
   Lichter labeled Super Tuesday a failure because it failed to
shift the focus of attention to the South. ``The media shined a
1,000-watt spotlight on the early primaries and a one-watt
flashlight on Super Tuesday,'' he said.
</TEXT>
