<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Palau     03-28 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palau,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate OKs Implementation of Pact With Trust Territory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Monday approved a resolution
authorizing the Reagan administration to implement the proposed
compact of free association between the United States and the
Pacific trust territory of Palau.
   The voice-vote action sent the measure to the House, where
similar legislation has been stalled by an investigation by the
Interior Committee into allegations of governmental corruption in
Palau.
   The Senate resolution would permit the compact, which would end
40 years of U.S. trusteeship over Palau, to be implemented so long
as there is no pending legal challenge to a plebescite last summer
in the islands.
   Palauan dissidents have talked of filing a court suit
challenging the legality of the plebescite in which a majority of
voters approved amending their constitution to drop its prohibition
against nuclear weapons in Palau.
   Leaders of the Interior Committee have sent congressional
investigators to Palau to probe allegations that senior Palau
officials may be involved with the smuggling of Southeast Asia
heroin into the United States.
   The investigators also are looking into reports that Palau
officials have have received unjustified payments from a British
company that built a power plant for the Palau government.
   The administration, which sees Palau as a militarily strategic
area, has been pressing Congress to allow it to implement the
compact so it can get the United Nations to cancel the trusteeship
imposed after World War II.
   Under the proposed compact, the United States would handle
military and diplomatic affairs for Palau, whose ailing economy
would get some $428 million in U.S. aid in the first 15 years of
the 50-year pact.
</TEXT>
