<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Rates,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Refuses To Delay Postal Rate Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused Monday to stop next
Sunday's hike in postal rates, ruling he lacked jurisdiction to
order the Postal Service to delay the increase for two months.
   U.S. District Judge Charles R. Richey ruled that he did not have
jurisdiction to rule on a request by trade groups representing
mail-order and direct-mail firms for an injunction delaying the
imposition of the new postal rates until June 4.
   But Richey said the trade groups could take their complaint to
the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here.
   The plaintiffs, including the Mail Order Association of America,
the Third Class Mail Association and the Magazine Publishers
Association, contended that any increase before June 4 was illegal.
   The suit charged that the Postal Rate Commission calculated the
rate hike to take effect on that date and that the Postal Service
lacked authority to charge higher rates before then.
   The Postal Service will raise an extra $700 million by raising
rates in April instead of June, the lawsuit said.
   On Sunday, the cost of first-class stamps will increase from 22
cents to 25 cents with corresponding hikes for second, third and
fourth-class mail.
</TEXT>
