<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Pool 1stLd-Writethru a0644 03-28 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Pool, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0644,0757</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Confiscates Media Pool Film</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs with Pentagon statement; pick up 5th `The
official'. DELETES last graf pvs to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Navy confiscated film from a
member of a Pentagon news pool in the Persian Gulf for security
reasons, but the Pentagon said Monday afternoon it was being
returned.
   Thomas Salyer, a photographer for United Press International,
said intelligence officers refused to return 36 of 61 negatives he
took of an abandoned Iranian gunboat seized Thursday by the guided
missile frigate Reuben James in the Strait of Hormuz.
   It was the first known confiscation of material from a pool
member.
   U.S. officials had directed earlier that some portions of tape
taken by an NBC cameraman in the pool be blocked out. The team
later was allowed to dub a version of its own tape with those
portions excluded.
   In Washington, the Pentagon released a statement Monday from the
U.S. Central Command saying Salyer's film was being returned.
   ``Three rolls of film were developed and half of the exposures
were withheld from the UPI photographer by Navy officials after a
determination was made at the scene that the information revealed
in the film was classified,'' it said.
   ``In retrospect, the decision to classify the film was overly
cautious. Officers at the U.S. Central Command reviewed the list of
materials found on the boat, and have have found no sensitive
materials to warrant continued withholding of the film.''
   The official concern in both cases was over showing certain
artillery shells found in the boat, the serial numbers on its gun _
a 25mm anti-aircraft weapon _ and a large box that was sealed but
believed to contain ammunition.
   The wooden box was not opened aboard the Reuben James, and U.S.
officers refused to speculate on what it contained.
   Standing rules governing the Pentagon news pools provide that
all written, audio and pictorial material must be cleared for
security by U.S. officials at the Department of Defense before it
can be released and distributed generally to media being served by
the pool.
   This material is scrutinized at the operational level, such as
aboard ships, but is not censored. If there is a question
concerning security, it is referred to the Department of Defense.
   Although the system has been in effect for several years, the
Persian Gulf is the first place it has been used for coverage of
real military operations rather than maneuvers and exercises.
   Since the news pools were instituted for the gulf in July, there
have been several cases in which pool escort officers alerted
Defense Department officials to a potental security problem in
written news copy, but in all cases it was cleared by the Pentagon
as written.
   The Pentagon also has not objected to any audio, video or photo
reports obtained by the pool journalists.
   Salyer said he was asked to submit his film for examination by
intelligence experts aboard the USS Coronado, command ship of the
Joint Task Force Middle East and its gulf-based component, the
Middle East Force.
   He said that after three officers had spent several hours
examining it, he was told some of the film would be kept because
when blown up to larger size it revealed the serial numbers of the
gun, or disclosed other valuable intelligence data.
   Salyer, noting that he had earlier been allowed to ship some
other film of the boat and the nighttime operation to recover it,
said he thought the officers ``overreacted'' in confiscating the
second batch of pictures.
   He said the Navy also seemed to be imposing a ``double
standard'' on him that didn't apply to others.
   ``We were all told in advance that the boat material would be
subjected to security review,'' Salyer said. ``After looking at the
film, they said I could have only a part of it back and I could
appeal through the Freedom of Information Act for the rest of it.''
   Experienced pool participants could recall no previous occasion
when any news material was confiscated.
   Maj. Barry Willey, a public affairs officer assigned to the pool
from the U.S. Central Command headquarters in Tampa, Fla., said he
also did not recall a precedent.
   Willey said the decision to withhold the film was made here
because there was no way to get it to the Pentagon for review ``in
a timely manner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
