<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IsraelBus     03-28 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel Bus,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Claim army issued distorted report on bus incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten American and European academics on Monday
disputed the army account of an incident involving the visitors'
tour bus that led to a clash in which Israeli soldiers fatally shot
two Palestinians.
   ``The version released by the army spokesman is, to put it
mildly, a gross distortion,'' said Zachary Lockman, who teaches
Middle East history at Harvard University.
   ``We're quite concerned about our trip being used as a pretext
for what followed,'' he told a news conference about the incident
Sunday.
   An army spokesman said Sunday that soldiers went to the rescue
of an Israeli tour bus under attack in the Arab town of Salfit, 20
miles north of Jerusalem.
   He said the bus driver mistakenly entered Salfit, and
Palestinans stoned the vehicle and then attacked soldiers sent to
the scene. The soldiers responded with gunfire that killed two
Palestinians, he said.
   On Monday, an army spokeswoman said soldiers entered the town
becaue of reports of a hijacked bus.
   ``They quickly discovered there was nothing wrong and began to
withdraw, when the soldiers were attacked by a large group of
hundreds of Arabs throwing bottles, pieces of metal and concrete
blocks,'' said the spokeswoman, who was not identified in line with
military regulations.
   Lockman, joined by other other professors at the news
conference, said the vehicle was clearly marked as a bus from Bir
Zeit University, an Arab institution. He said their group had gone
to Salfit to talk with Palestinians.
   He said villagers greeted them warmly and the town was peaceful
throughout the 30- to 45-minute stay.
   Lockman, who speaks Hebrew, said he overheard an army officer at
a checkpoint tell his commanding officer by radio ``that we (the
tour group) had not been under any threat whatsoever.'' He said an
army helicopter flew over Salfit during the group's visit.
   He added that as the bus left the area it went by a force of
soldiers heading toward the town.
   Jack Taft, a lecturer in peace and conflict studies at the
University of California at Berkeley, noted that the army
frequently bars reporters from scenes of conflict.
   ``I think that's the central point,'' he said. ``The army as the
sole source of information can fabricate any story it likes.''
</TEXT>
