<DOCNO> AP880328-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2316EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     03-28 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Resume, Cutoff Dispute Remains Unresolved</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N.-sponsored Afghanistan talks resumed Monday,
after a weekend recess and word that Moscow remains unyielding in
the dispute over foreign arms supplies to parties in the conflict.
   Pakistan's chief negotiator said the question of ``symmetry'' _
simultaneous cessation of Soviet military aid to the Kabul
government and U.S. aid to the Moslem guerrillas fighting it _ was
the final unresolved issue.
   Acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani said that, for ``the United
States and Pakistan (it) is of major concern.''
   It is outside the formal scope of the indirect Geneva talks
between Islamabad and Kabul, but the superpowers are the designated
guarantors of any peace settlement. The United States has said it
will accept that role only if there is a ``balance of obligations.''
   Speaking to reporters before a formal session with U.N. mediator
Diego Cordovez, Noorani said the moment Moscow agrees on a
symmetrical cutoff of arms aid, ``my pen is with me and I will
sign.''
   Over the weekend, Noorani met with special Soviet envoy Nikolay
Kozyrev, who has been following the talks from the wings since the
latest round began March 2.
   Sources close to the Pakistani delegation said Kozyrev made
clear that Moscow remains firm on the arms cutoff. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz, meeting last week with Soviet Foreign
Minister A. Eduard Shevardnadze in Washington, indicated
flexibility in the U.S. stand.
   Shultz suggested the superpowers agree at least on a temporary
freeze or ``something close to it.'' But Shevardnadze ruled out
symmetry. The Soviets reject the U.S. symmetry demand as amounting
to interference with relations between two states, noting that
Moscow and Kabul are bound by international treaties.
   Kozyrev reportedly suggested Pakistan go ahead and sign the
three main accords without waiting for U.S. and Soviet agreement on
the fourth, spelling out the superpower guarantees.
   Shevardnadze struck that note last week at a Washington news
conference when he said the ``Afghan question can be resolved
without U.S. guarantees.''
   The text of the peace package, said to comprise about 25
typewritten pages, has been translated and scrutinized by legal
experts. Noorani says he considers the documents complete.
Afghanistan was reported still opposed to having the text refer to
``international boundaries'' because of what it considers a border
dispute dating to Pakistan's independence.
   Sources close to the talks, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said they were confident that question could be settled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
