<DOCNO> AP880328-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Economy     03-28 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Economy,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation-Fighting Pact Extended Through May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government, business and labor have agreed to
hold the line on wages and prices and extend an inflation-fighting
program through May.
   The so-called Economic Solidarity Pact has been in effect since
December and President Miguel de la Madrid said it seems to be
stemming inflation, which hit a record annual rate 159.2 percent
last year.
   De la Madrid and representatives of business and labor signed
the extension in a ceremony at the presidential palace Sunday. He
said Mexico may soon be able to get inflation down to about 2
percent a month, according to a statement from the presidential
office.
   At the signing ceremony, the president said more must be done to
solve Mexico's economic problems. Besides inflation, those include
high unemployment and the second-highest foreign debt in the
developing world, $105 billion.
   ``There should be satisfaction with what has been achieved so
far, but at the same time there should be a recognition that the
work ahead will be difficult and complex,'' he said.
   Under the extended agreement, the value of the peso _ 2,280 to
the dollar _ and the minimum daily wage of 8,000 pesos, or about
$3.50, will remain steady through May.
   De la Madrid's government agreed not to raise the price of goods
and services it provides or controls through through that period,
and business leaders said they would keep prices steady.
   The Bank of Mexico, the nation's central bank, said it would
lower interest rates on several financial instruments.
   Last week, the president said a ``minority'' in the private
sector had violated the pact. On Sunday, he urged violators to
follow the example of the vast majority of businesses in honoring
the anti-inflation program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
