<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2058EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PunjabViolence     03-28 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Punjab Violence,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Radicals Kill 18 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen believed to be Sikh radicals
killed at least 18 people in attacks within a 20-mile radius of
Amritsar, the Sikh holy city, police said Monday.
   They said victims Sunday included four members of a Hindu family
killed in their home and a Sikh policeman visiting a village for
his sister's wedding.
   The constable's uncle also was killed.
   Attacks by militants have taken 550 lives so far this year. At
least 1,000 people were killed in 1987 by Sikhs fighting for an
independent homeland in Punjab, the only province of India where
members of the sect form a majority.
   Most victims have been Hindus and moderate Sikhs who oppose the
militants.
   Police said men with automatic rifles killed four members of a
Hindu family in Manowal, a village 20 miles west of Amritsar. A
neighbor who came when he heard gunfire also was killed.
   Others slain included seven employees of a brick kiln _ four
Hindus and three Sikhs _ and two Sikh members of the Marxist
Communist Party.
   Bodies of two other men killed were not identified.
   Officials said they did not know the motives for the killings.
   Sikhs account for 2 percent of India's 800 million people, the
vast majority of whom are Hindus.
   Amritsar is home to the sect's main shrine, the Golden Temple,
and the center of the militant movement for a separate Sikh nation
in the northern province, India's most productive agricultural
region.
</TEXT>
