<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-28 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Leaves Folks Shivering, Where They Were Basking On
Sunday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front raced across the Rockies and Plains states Monday,
bringing cold and snow to an area that had basked in springlike
weather over the weekend. A blizzard hit parts of Montana.
   The temperature early Monday afternoon plunged to 33 degrees in
Pueblo, Colo., where a day earlier it had reached 85 degrees.
Similar bone-chilling drops were reported across a wide region.
   A blizzard raged across parts of Montana during the morning
hours. Strong winds produced subzero wind-chill readings and poor
visibility.
   Before moving out by midday, the storm system also covered roads
with ice and left 2 inches of wind-whipped snow in much of Utah. A
rash of accidents, including a fatal car-train collision, was
blamed on the storm there.
   Snow and gusty winds were also reported as far east as the
central Plains. A high wind warning was posted in the mountains of
New Mexico, and wind advisories were posted in some Texas mountain
passes and the mountains of Southern California.
   An advisory for snow was posted for the northern and central
mountains and the northeastern plains of Colorado, and a winter
storm watch was been posted through Tuesday morning for
northwestern Kansas.
   Farther south, the front created some fears of severe
thunderstorms and possible tornadoes in parts of southeastern
Kansas, Oklahoma and west-central Texas.
   In northern and central Minnesota, the precipitation took the
form of a mixture of rain, freezing drizzle and snow, while showers
and thunderstorms were numerous across southern Wisconsin, northern
and central Illinois, and northeastern Missouri, and from
southwestern Iowa to north-central Texas.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m.
EST included 0.89 inch at Rockford, Ill.; 0.85 inch at Peoria,
Ill.; 0.56 inch at Madison, Wis.; 0.48 inch at Dubuque, Iowa, and
Moline, Ill., and 0.47 inch at Cedar Rapids, Iowa.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 18
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 92 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
The early morning low for the nation was zero at Yellowstone Park.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for showers and thunderstorms in
the southern and central Plains and the Mississippi Valley to the
Great Lakes, with snow in parts of northern Minnesota and Upper
Michigan. Rain showers, with snow in the higher elevations, also
were forecast across the Pacific Northwest into the northern
Rockies.
   Temperatures in the 30s and 40s were forecast from the northern
and central Rockies through the northern and central Plains to
Upper Michigan, and across northern New England; in the 70s in
Southern California and southern Arizona, and from the Rio Grande
Valley of Texas to the southern and mid-Atlantic Coast states; in
the 80s in south-central Texas and across the Florida Peninsula,
and in the 50s and 60s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
