<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0638 03-28 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fierce Fighting Continues On Land, More Missiles By Sea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 17th graf pvs, IRNA said ... UPDATING
with U.N. activity. Picks up 18th graf pvs, In the ... with minor
editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Monday its Revolutionary Guards
repulsed an Iraqi counterattack in their drive into Kurdistan and
now hold more than 540 square miles of the strategic region in
northeast Iraq.
   Iranian gunboats attacked two supertankers in the Persian Gulf,
setting them ablaze. And Iraqi-backed opponents of Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini claimed several thousand of their fighters
overran Iranian positions in southwest Iran.
   Iraq, which has admitted it has lost ground in the mountainous
northeast, vowed to ``destroy the Iranian aggressors with all
available means.''
   Baghdad's official news agency said the Iraqis fired three
long-range missiles into the holy city of Qom, 100 miles south of
Tehran, while warplanes bombed four Iranian towns to avenge
``Iranian attacks on our cities and border.''
   Qom is the seat of Iran's religious hierarchy and crucible of
Khomeini's 1979 Islamic revolution.
   Tehran Radio said 11 civilians were killed in the missile
attacks and the air raids on Dezful, Ilam, Borujerd and Kuhdasht.
   Iran said its artillery hammered ``military and industrial
targets'' in the southern city of Basra, shelled daily for more
than a month, and five other border towns.
   If the Iranian claim of a major advance into Kurdistan is true,
it would mark Iraq's worst military setback since the Iranians
fought to within six miles of Basra a year ago. Iran still occupies
land east of the battered city.
   The Iraqi army's Al-Qadessiyah daily, heightening the belief
that the Iranians have made gains, exhorted soldiers to ``pour your
rage and fire on the heads of the Persians who have gone too far.''
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
said the Iranians ``fiercely repelled'' a counterattack by Iraq's
5th Army Corps around Lake Darbandikhan before dawn Monday.
   It gave no indication of further Iranian advances in the
13-day-old Val-Fajr-10 offensive.
   But it quoted Revolutionary Guards Minister Mohsen Rafiq-Doust
as saying in Tehran on Sunday night that his men have overrun 540
square miles of Kurdistan.
   IRNA also reported that Iranian jet fighters shot down two Iraqi
warplanes in the battle zone Monday.
   Iraqi-backed Iranian rebels said their National Liberation Army
launched a major offensive on a 14-mile front in Iran's oil-rich
southwestern Khuzestan province near the town of Shush.
   The rebels claimed in a communique that 15 brigades of its
fighters pushed into Khuzestan to drive Iranians out of positions
and threaten a key highway southwest of the garrison city of Dezful.
   It reported heavy Iranian casualties with ``a large number of
tanks captured.''
   IRNA said Iraqi soldiers and ``counterrevolutionaries,'' a usual
reference by the Iranian media to the rebels, launched a ``futile
infiltration attempt'' that was repulsed by the Iranian forces. It
said 1,000 attackers were killed or wounded.
   At the United Nations on Monday, Iraq condemned the world body's
sending a team to look into Iranian charges of chemical warfare and
asked it to instead investigate what it said was Iranian torture of
Iraqi POWs.
   In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar,
Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq said the United Nations was
ignoring Iran's own use of chemical arms and letting Iran drag its
feet in implementing a cease-fire.
   In the Persian Gulf, the U.S. Navy completed its 18th escort
mission of the year. Two Kuwaiti tankers reached international
waters off Kuwait after steaming northbound from the Strait of
Hormuz, the Pentagon announced in Washington.
   The United States placed 11 Kuwaiti tankers last year under the
U.S. flag to protect them against Iranian attack.
   Iran attacks neutral shipping in the gulf to retaliate for Iraqi
raids on its oil intallations.
   Iranian gunboats Monday attacked the 337,733-ton Danish
supertanker Karama Maersk off the southern emirate of Sharjah,
setting it on fire, shipping executives reported.
   Three hours later, gunboats attacked the 219,287-ton
Norwegian-operated tanker Golar Kansai in the same area and set it
ablaze, the officials reported.
   No casualties were reported on either ship.
   Tehran communiques said the Iranians have pushed about 15 miles
into northeast Iraq and seized the eastern and southern shores of
Lake Darbabdikhan.
   They were reported to be within 3 miles of an important
hydroelectric dam on the southern end of the 10-mile-long lake.
   The facility supplies most of the power for the region and
Baghdad, 120 miles to the southwest.
</TEXT>
