<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Egypt     03-28 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Egypt,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libya Says It Will Withdraw Forces from Border With Egypt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOBRUK, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi said Monday he is
withdrawing Libyan forces from the border with Egypt but he did not
specify a time frame for the pullback.
   Such a move would represent a conciliatory gesture unprecedented
since Gadhafi's feud with Egypt began 16 years ago.
   The Libyan leader's announcement in this Mediterranean city 75
miles west of the Egyptian border followed a series of goodwill
gestures made by both countries in recent weeks.
   Gadhafi did not say how many troops Libya has along the border.
   ``I want to emphasize to the Egyptian people and army that the
Libyan eastern military zone (beside the border) will finally be
abolished,'' Gadhafi told a crowd of 2,500 gathered in Tobruk, once
a key British base.
   The ceremony marked the 18th anniversary of Britain's evacuation
of its military bases in Libya.
   Gadhafi said the border forces would be withdrawn ``without us
asking for anything in return from the Egyptian side,'' and he
offered to let Egypt verify the withdrawal.
   Gadhafi, who wore a bright red jumpsuit, paused repeatedly
during his 1{-hour speech as the crowd chanted ``Long live the
revolution!'' and anti-American slogans.
   Gadhafi also said Libya would not use force to undermine
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's government or to pressure it to
renounce the 1979 peace treaty with Israel. Egypt is the only Arab
country to have diplomatic relations with the Jewish state.
   But Gadhafi did say Monday that Egypt had ``abandoned'' the Arab
world when the late President Anwar Sadat signed the U.S.-mediated
Camp David peace pact with Israel.
   Western and African diplomatic observers in Libya called
Gadhafi's overtures an enormous change, but said they had been
expected.
   They said Monday's announcement reflected Gadhafi's confidence
in his position at home.
   In his speech, Gadhafi also discussed civil rights in Libya. He
said arrests should only be made through court order. Critics say
that under the current system, some Libyans are arbitrarily
arrested by revolutionary committees.
   In the past month, Gadhafi has made several moves to increase
human rights, including releasing inmates at a political prison and
calling for the abolition of the death penalty.
   The Egyptian-Libyan feud began in 1972 when Cairo rejected
Gadhafi's bid to merge the two countries.
   Egypt blamed Gadhafi for a series of terrorist bombings in Cairo
and other cities in 1975 and 1976, and the two countries fought a
five-day border war in July 1977. Both have maintained large
military forces beside the frontier.
   Gadhafi has ruled Libya since a military coup in 1969 overthrew
the monarchy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
