<DOCNO> AP880328-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan-US-Nuclear     03-28 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-US-Nuclear,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Checking With US About Missing Nuclear Scientist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Monday it has asked
the United States about a missing scientist said to have gone to
America with documents about a Taiwanese program for developing
nuclear weapons.
   The Foreign Ministry statement was the first public
acknowledgment that Taiwan was in touch with Washington about the
case of Col. Chang Hsien-yi, 45, deputy director of the Nuclear
Energy Research Center at the military-run Chungshan Institute of
Science and Technology. He disappeared in January.
   ``Because many people believe Col. Chang is in the United States
this ministry has contacted the American Institute in Taiwan
several times on this event,'' the statement said.
   It said American agency told the ministry it had no information
on Chang's whereabouts but was investigating. The institute
oversees U.S. interests in Taiwan since diplomatic ties were cut in
1979, when the United States recognized the mainland Chinese
government in Beijing.
   Taiwan newspapers, citing sources they did not identify, claimed
Chang worked for the CIA and fled to the United States with secret
information about plans to develop nuclear weapons on Taiwan.
   In recent weeks, officials have repeated Taiwan's position that
it has not developed nuclear weapons. They say they do not know
Chang's whereabouts and are investigating his disappearance.
</TEXT>
