<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0695 03-28 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Wins Kemp Endorsement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 10th graf pvs, ``He talked xxx, to
UPDATE with Bush comments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush on Monday picked up the endorsement
of Rep. Jack Kemp, who said of the vice president: ``He's earned
it.''
   The New York congressman, who withdrew from the race earlier
this month after disappointing showings in GOP contests, said his
endorsement of Bush was ``unequivocal'' and that he would
vigorously campaign for him.
   Bush said the endorsement ``means a lot to me'' and called his
former rival ``a rising star in the Republican Party nationally.''
   Kemp, appearing with Bush at a news conference as the vice
president began a three-day campaign sweep through Wisconsin, told
reporters that the subject of a possible vice presidential bid did
not come up in his talks with Bush.
   Bush, asked whether he had considered extending an invitation to
Kemp to join him on a national ticket, said such speculation was
premature.
   ``It's too early to get into the vice presidency question,''
Bush said. Commenting on his recent wins in Republican primary
races, Bush said ``the numbers are strong.''
   However, turning to the subject of Sen. Bob Dole's campaign, the
vice president said he did not want to say anything that might be
construed as an effort to pressure Dole to formally withdraw.
   ``I'm just going to keep on campaigning. Each person has to make
that decision on his own,'' Bush said.
   However, Kemp said that recent remarks by Dole, including a
speech earlier Monday in Washington, during which he thanked his
supporters, appeared tantamount to a withdrawal from the race.
   ``He talked in such a way to acknowledge his campaign has come
to a close,'' Kemp said. Dole had said last Friday that Bush's
nomination now seemed a ``foregone conclusion.''
   Later, Bush told an invitation-only rally in a high school in
Cedarburg, Wis., that ``I don't put too much stock in the polls,
but they do look good.''
   Still, he told his audience, ``I will not project an arrogance,
I will not project overconfidence.''
   He said Kemp's endorsement was ``good, because what we want to
do is to have this party unified, together, so we can whip the
Democrats.''
   ``One of the best things that happened to me was getting my
brains kicked out in Iowa,'' Bush added. ``Everybody had me dead
and buried. We were resurrected right there in New Hampshire. So
people say now things are going pretty well for you, and they are.''
   Kemp said that at the time he entered the GOP race, ``I believed
I was the best candidate for Republican conservatives. The voters
believed otherwise.''
   Turning to the Democratic race, Bush expressed admiration for
the growing strength of Jesse Jackson.
   ``The man's racking up delegates, and that's how you get
elected,'' Bush said. ``What he has done is very admirable. He hung
in there. He's doing very well by taking his case out to the
people.''
   Bush said that despite the numbers on the Republican side, he
wasn't taking anything for granted.
   ``I don't want to project that it's all over,'' he said.
   Kemp told the news conference: ``The time has come for all
Republicans to unite behind this man who has been a fine and loyal
vice president.''
   ``As one involved in the friendly competition, he's earned it,''
Kemp said. Then, turning to Bush, Kemp said: ``You can count on
Jack Kemp in '88.''
</TEXT>
