<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0693 03-28 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0693,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham `Insulted' by Prosecution Questioning in Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Mecham winding up testimony,
suggesting Senate call the trial without hearing third charge,
Senate leaders' response. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angry Gov. Evan Mecham took offense
during his impeachment trial Monday at a prosecutor's comparing his
actions to embezzlement.
   ``I resent so highly the word embezzlement in my presence. I'm
insulted by it,'' Mecham declared, ignoring orders by Arizona Chief
Justice Frank Gordon to refrain from commenting beyond answering
questions.
   Gordon, who already had ruled the question irrelevant,
admonished Mecham again, telling him, ``I hope you believe the
rules are for you, sir, as well as everybody else.''
   Mecham responded hotly, ``I have seen no witness who has been
insulted as I have been.''
   The outburst came after House prosecutor William French tried to
compare Mecham's loan of $80,000 to Mecham's auto dealership from a
protocol fund to a bank officer ``borrowing'' money from a bank
vault and later replacing it.
   ``That doesn't make the bank official any less guilty of
embezzlement, does it?'' said French, citing Mecham's repeated
references to the fact that his dealership paid back the loan with
interest.
   Defense attorney Jerris Leonard objected, and Gordon sustained
the objection.
   Mecham, who began his second round of testimony Friday and
completed it Monday, is charged with misusing state funds by
loaning the $80,000 to Mecham Pontiac. The charge is the second of
three against him.
   As he left the stand, he suggested the Senate drop the third
count _ that he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan _ and judge him
right away on the first two.
   In response to a question from a senator on how he thought they
should proceed, Mecham said he wouldn't mind if they decided to
``call this game at the end of six innings'' and forget the last
charge.
   He cited the effect of the hearing on his April 21 criminal
trial on charges of concealing the campaign loan.
   Outside the Senate chamber, Majority Leader Robert Usdane, who
like Mecham is a Republican, said the chances of dropping the third
count were ``about as good as me going out and jumping off the
highest building I can find.''
   He called the loan concealment charge ``one of the most serious
allegations that was made by the House.''
   Mecham also asked that the Senate at least postpone hearing the
third count until after his trial. But Minority Leader Alan
Stephens said that's as likely as ``as Jimmy Carter being elected
president of the United States again.''
   In his testimony Monday, Mecham maintained the loan was secure
with his company and a good investment for the money, which
originally raised by his inaugural committee.
   French, in a series of hypothetical questions, suggested Mecham
felt the money belonged to him, not the state.
   ``Could you have used the $80,000 to put a swimming pool and
tennis court in the back yard of your house?'' he asked Mecham.
   ``I probably could have done it if I'd invited all of the
legislators and cabinet officers to swim once a month,'' Mecham
said with a smile. He then added, ``I shouldn't jest with you on
these ridiculous questions.''
   However, he conceded that under his theory he could have loaned
the money to his wife for whatever she wanted to spend it on as
long as it was paid back with interest.
   Mecham also testified he could not recall whether his then-chief
of staff, Jim Colter, or anyone else advised that the loan was
politically unwise.
   ``We're all good Monday morning quarterbacks,'' said Mecham,
``and everybody decided it was a stupid thing to do after the
fact.''
   The protocol fund was set up after a state law barred use of the
funds to pay off Mecham's campaign debts. The prosecution claims
the money became a public fund for state promotion. Mecham claims
it remained private for use at his discretion.
   The 63-year-old Mecham, the first U.S. governor to face an
impeachment trial in six decades, in previous testimony denied a
charge that he tried to thwart investigation of an alleged death
threat on a grand jury witness.
   Besides the impeachment and criminal trials, Mecham also faces a
recall election May 17.
   In other developments Monday, jury selection began in the
political extortion trial of Sam Steiger, an ex-congressman and
former Mecham aide. He resigned after being charged with trying to
influence the vote of a member of the state Board of Pardons and
Paroles.
</TEXT>
