<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-JapanConstruction 1stLd-Writethru   03-28 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Construction, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0635,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Report Progress Toward Solving Building Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with progress reported as talks end for the
day</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Progress toward solving the dispute over
participation of U.S. contractors in Japanese construction projects
was reported Monday night as the two governments scheduled a third
day of negotiations.
   U.S. Deputy Trade Representative Michael B. Smith and Ichiro
Ozawa, deputy chief secretary of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's
cabinet, agreed to meet again Tuesday after sessions last Friday
night and most of Monday.
   ``There has been significant progress but we do not yet have an
agreement,'' said Smith's spokeswoman, Kelly Winkler. Both Smith
and Ozawa planned to consult their governments before Tuesday's
talk, she said. The Japanese Embassy said the talks were marked by
both progress and continung problems.
   Ozawa arrived last week and started formal negotiations Friday
in hope of averting further U.S. reprisals for exclusion of
American builders from the multibillion-dollar Japanese public
works boom.
   Congress late last year barred Japanese firms from U.S.
federally-funded public works because of lack of reciprocal access
for American companies. During his White House visit in January,
Takeshita promised to seek a solution but negotiations on both
sides of the Pacific failed to produce it. The United States was
reported on the verge of initiating a formal unfair trade action.
   Ms. Winkler said Monday's progress came both in defining the
Japanese public works projects to which U.S. bids would be admitted
and in clarifying the bidding procedure.
</TEXT>
