<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea-Chun     03-28 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea-Chun,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother of ex-President Chun Questioned Again in Corruption Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brother of former President Chun
Doo-hwan has been summoned for questioning Tuesday about a
multimillion-dollar scandal in a semiofficial development agency he
once headed, prosecutors reported.
   Kang Won-il, the prosecutor in charge of the case, and his
assistants said Monday that Chun Kyung-hwan, 46, and three of his
aides were to be questioned about the alleged embezzlement of up to
$14 million from the Seemaul (New Community) development program.
   Kang said investigators have uncovered evidence linking Chun
Kyung-hwan, a younger brother of the ex-president, with $9.3
million of the funds.
   Opposition leaders have called for investigations of other
members of the Chun family.
   Saemaul was founded in 1971 to promote urban and rural
development. Chun Kyung-hwan, appointed by his brother, headed the
agency from 1981 to 1987.
   He has been accused of using his position to obtain donations,
sell influence and divert government funds to invest in
profit-oriented projects.
   Prosecutors said that last week investigators found about a
dozen secret bank accounts the younger Chun used under false names.
   Scores of government officials have been questioned in the case,
but prosecutors said most would face minor reprimands and not
criminal prosecution.
   Opposition leader Kim Young-sam demanded Monday that the
investigation be expanded to cover all allegations of corruption
involving the administration of ex-President Chun. He was in office
from 1980 until last month when Roh Tae-woo was inaugurated after
winning the presidential election in December.
   ``The administration should not be allowed to terminate the
investigation of Chun Kyung-hwan's scandals,'' Kim said in
announcing his candidacy for next month's National Assembly
elections.
   Protests about the Saemaul case intensified after Chun
Kyung-hwan, using a false name, flew to Osaka, Japan, on March 18.
He returned to Korea two days later for questioning.
   The government probe of the scandal is seen by some political
observers as part of an effort by Roh to discredit the former
president and his supporters, who allegedly were attempting to
maintain power within the government.
   Roh, a former general who helped put Chun in power with military
backing, promised during the presidential election campaign to root
out official corruption.
</TEXT>
