<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Drugs 2dLd-Writethru a0736 03-28 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Drugs, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0736,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General Said To Quit in Reported Drug Scandal Involving
Brother</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs, source at president's office confirms
accounts of resignation. Pick up 5th graf pvs: Caracol had said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Alfredo Gutierrez
Marquez resigned after it was reported cocaine traffickers used an
airfield at his brother's ranch, a source at the president's office
said Monday.
   The source, speaking with the condition he not be identified,
said President Virgilio Barco accepted the resignation.
   Radio stations RCN, Caracol and Todelar had earlier reported the
attorney general's resignation.
   Both the president's press office and attorney general's office
had declined comment when asked about a report Sunday night by the
Intervision television news program. The report said a 5,000-foot
runway used by drug traffickers was owned by Libardo Gutierrez
Marquez, the attorney general's brother.
   The source in the president's office told The Associated Press
late Monday that in his letter of resignation, the attorney general
said his brother did own a farm that news reports said had a runway
used by drug smugglers.
   Caracol had said earlier the attorney general resigned shortly
after a confiscated drug plane was stolen March 1 from a military
air base and landed at the runway, but the later radio reports said
he quit on Monday.
   The government of Colombia has been at virtual war with drug
traffickers, who have killed a justice minister, an attorney
general, several judges, two newspaper editors and scores of
policemen and soldiers.
   Intervision said the runway in question was used by planes
belonging to Pablo Escobar, branded as a leader of the Medellin
cartel.
   The cartel smuggles most of the cocaine reaching the United
States, according to the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration.
   The United States asked for extradition of Escobar and four
other men named as members of the Medellin cartel. Medellin, a city
in northwest Colombia, is where most of Colombia's purported drug
traffickers live.
   The runway is on a farm near Medellin next to property belonging
to Escobar, Intervision said.
   The army last year seized a twin-engine propeller plane, an
Aerocommander, used for drug trafficking. The plane was stolen from
an air force base on March 1 and landed at the runway owned by the
attorney general's brother, Intervision said.
   It said the air force tracked the plane by radar and strafed it,
other aircraft and hangars. Two days later, army bulldozers
destroyed the runway.
   News media have said the attorney general suggested that the
government try to reach a truce with drug traffickers.
   Last month, at a dinner with foreign correspondents, Gutierrez
was asked if he thought the government should try to reach a truce
with the drug traffickers.
   Gutierrez said that would be up to the president and that his
job is to follow the president's orders.
   The president says the government will not surrender in its war
on drug trafficking.
   In a raid last week on a country estate owned by Escobar, the
army said it found tape recordings linking drug dealers with
someone close to the attorney general's office. The army gave no
details.
   The Escobar home was one of five homes belonging to drug
trafficking suspects where the army in the last two months found
arsenals that include U.S. military assault rifles, submachine
guns, shotguns, pistols, ammunition, hand grenades, stolen license
plates and army and police uniforms.
   Two of the homes were raided Sunday, the army said in a news
release.
</TEXT>
