<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Pilot     03-28 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Pilot,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Claims Responsibility for Bombay Airport Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group calling itself the Organization
of Arab Guerrilla Cells claimed responsibility Monday for a gun and
grenade attack which badly injured an Italian pilot at Bombay
airport in India last week.
   ``We claim responsibility for the attack launched against a
group of Zionist pilots working at the Italian airline (Alitalia)
at Bombay airport,'' said a typewritten statement from the
previously unknown group, dated March 26.
   The Arabic-language statement was received Monday by Reuters
news agency through a courier service in mostly Moslem west Beirut.
   Last Friday, an Arabic-speaking man who gave his name as Abbas
Mohammed Ali Shahadi shot and seriously wounded an Alitalia pilot
aboard an airport bus.
   Bombay police said the gun jammed after three or four shots and
Shahadi jumped off the bus and tossed two grenades at two off-duty
policemen. The grenades failed to explode and the two officers
chased Shahadi and caught him.
   The Italian Embassy in New Delhi said police had not determined
the gunman's nationality or motive. Police said he gave them only
his hame and no identity papers were found on him.
   ``The attack was in retaliation for the frantic campaign waged
by the Zionists and imperialists against the Arab nation,'' the
statement said.
   The breakaway Palestinian faction, Fatah-Revolutionary Council,
hinted last month it would retaliate for a life sentence passed by
an Italian court on its leader, the notorious Abu Nidal, in
absentia.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, and a top aide
were convicted of a 1985 terrorist massacre at a Rome airport. The
lone survivor of the four-man attack, the only defendant in
custody, was jailed for 30 years.
</TEXT>
