<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugRestitution     03-28 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Restitution,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Heroin Dealer Ordered To Pay $2 Million in Restitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge made creative use of the state's victims
compensation law Monday and ordered a heroin dealer with extensive
real estate holdings to pay $2 million in restitution toward drug
rehabilitation programs.
   Supreme Court Justice Lewis Douglass said he reached the figure
by multiplying the cost of drug rehabilitation by the number of
addicts Agapito Lopez could have supplied with the six ounces of
heroin seized when he was arrested.
   Douglass said in a telephone interview he believed it was the
first time a state law allowing restitution for crime victims was
used in a drug case.
   Defense attorney Frank Ortiz said he would appeal the order. He
argued that when legislators approved the restitution law, they
were thinking of crimes in which there is a specific victim, like
robbery or rape.
   He also argued that the law requires a hearing to be held for
any payment more than $10,000.
   Lopez, 44, was convicted in 1987 of drug sale and possession. He
is serving a 25-year-to-life sentence imposed by Douglass last year.
   According to the judge's calculations, if the six ounces that
were seized when Lopez was arrested in 1985 had made it to the
street, and each addict bought 20 bags of heroin, the six ounces
would have gone to about 900 addicts.
   Douglass said he contacted drug rehabilitation agencies to find
what the cost of the least expensive treatment would be and was
told it was $2,400 annually for outpatient care.
   He said he will ask Mayor Edward I. Koch to designate a drug
rehabilitation agency to receive the money.
   Lopez sold 2,200 bags of heroin to an undercover officer for
$26,000 and was arrested after the officer arranged for another
sale, according to Nancy Young, a spokesman for Brooklyn District
Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman.
   At that time, officers confiscated the six ounces of heroin and
seized $440,000 in cash from his apartment.
   Young said Lopez owned at least three houses in two boroughs of
New York City and a car dealership and other real estate in Puerto
Rico.
   He also had bank accounts with $60,000. The district attorney's
office will seize the assets needed to meet the restitution, Young
said.
</TEXT>
