<2ND_LINE>AM-Bryan Announces,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Declares Candidacy for U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Gov. Dick Bryan announced his
candidacy for the U.S. Senate on Monday with a swipe at Republican
incumbent Chic Hecht.
   ``If he was the kind of senator Nevada deserves, I would not
have made that decision'' to run, said Bryan, who is in the middle
of his second four-year term.
   The 50-year-old former attorney general has won praise for his
opposition to the government's proposed high-level nuclear dump at
Yucca Mountain and has held a wide margin over Hecht in polls taken
over the past year.
   Hecht, an upset victor over Democratic Sen. Howard Cannon six
years ago, accused Bryan of spouting empty rhetoric and added the
governor was trying to take credit for the economic benefits to
Nevada of the ``Reagan revolution.''
   Bryan urged Hecht to consider a lid of about $2.5 million on
spending, calling high-budget campaigns ``perhaps one of the great
scandals in America today'' and acknowledging he couldn't match the
$5 million to $6 million Hecht has said he could raise.
   Bryan plans to release a financial report next week that will
show he has raised $1.1 million so far.
   Bryan upset Republican Gov. Robert List in 1982 and was
re-elected in 1986 in a landslide over Patty Cafferata. At the
time, detractors said he would be merely a ``caretaker'' governor
while he prepared to run for the Senate.
   He was born in Las Vegas, graduated from the University of
Nevada-Reno and earned a law degree from the University of
California Hastings College of Law.
   Bryan served terms in the Assembly and state Senate before
becoming attorney general in 1978.
</TEXT>
