<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Asia-DrugWars Adv01   03-28 1085</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asia-Drug Wars, Adv 01,1105</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs April 1 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Asians Help Americans Cut Flow of Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BK1, March 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although saddled with drug
problems of their own, a number of Asian countries are extending
effective help to Americans trying to stem the flow of narcotics
into the United States, senior U.S. officials say.
   The United States regards Afghanistan, Iran, Laos and Syria as
patently uncooperative, but the officials say such countries as
Thailand, Malaysia, Burma, Pakistan and China, along with Hong
Kong, work closely with Americans in cutting Asian opium production
and tracking drug shipments and dealers.
   In March, for example, Asian-American teamwork led to the arrest
in New York City of an alleged drug baron the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration (DEA) says may have smuggled up to $1 billion worth
of heroin into the United States.
   The trail of Kon Yu-leung, a high-living Chinese carrying the
passports of at least six countries, reportedly had snaked down
from the opium fields of the ``Golden Triangle'' of Thailand, Burma
and Laos through Hong Kong and on to the United States. The heroin
was hidden in shipments of innocent-looking vases, ice buckets and
T-shirts.
   Exchanging intelligence and tracking Kon and his syndicate for
four years were a special Thai anti-narcotics unit, the Royal Hong
Kong Police and some of the 80 DEA agents based in Asia.
   ``In this part of the world countries have acknowledged that
they too have an internal drug problem,'' DEA head John C. Lawn
said in an interview during a conference in Kuala Lumpur. ``They
are overt in cooperating so that something can be done not only
about the international problem but their domestic one.''
   Opium-smoking has long been a problem in Asia because of the
proximity of the drug. But Asian nations in recent years have
cracked down hard. Malaysia, for example, has the death penalty for
narcotics offenses.
   While the greater U.S. anti-narcotics focus is currently on
Latin America and the Carribean, the DEA has sharply revised its
estimate of Southeast Asian heroin consumed by American addicts
from 18 percent to 30 percent. An additional 37 percent is said to
originate from the so-called ``Golden Crescent'' _ Iran,
Afghanistan and Pakistan _ and the rest comes largely from Mexico.
   Also requiring shifts of tactics and possibly manpower is DEA's
assertion that Asian syndicates are replacing the Mafia as
wholesalers of heroin to American addicts, estimated to number
about 500,000. According to the DEA, about 70 percent of heroin
reaching New York City originates in Southeast Asia, up from 4
percent five years ago. Latin America is the chief source of
cocaine.
   The war against drugs in Asia works both ways. The United
States, for example, helped set up a network of drug rehabilitation
centers in Thailand that treat some 30,000 addicts a year. The
Thais in turn have forged a dedicated group of anti-drug lawmen who
each year arrest more traffickers and greater quantities of drugs,
much of them bound for the United States.
   ``We couldn't really operate without the Americans,'' said Col.
Viraj Jutimitta, widely regarded as one of Thailand's best
anti-narcotics officers. The United States supplies one of his
elite units, ``The Dirty Dozen,'' with radios, vehicles, travel
allowances and even copying paper.
   The United States also is providing aircraft and herbicides to
spray opium fields in Burma and Pakistan and has helped Thailand's
largely successful effort to get hill tribes people to substitute
coffee, vegetables and other crops for their traditional opium.
   The U.S. State Department spends about a third of its $100
million anti-narcotics budget in Asia, maintaining drug
coordinators in every embassy and 24 officers at special narcotics
units in in Thailand, Burma and Pakistan. Somewhat less than a
third of DEA's current $525 million budget is allocated to Asia.
   Cooperation, however, stops at the frontiers of war-torn
Afghanistan and politically hostile Iran and Syria. Opium and
heroin production in communist Laos is reported soaring with the
connivance of high-level authorities, but U.S. officials say there
is reluctance to impose sanctions for fear the Laotian government
will refuse to cooperate on the accounting of Americans missing in
action from the Indochina war in Laos.
   In contrast, China has moved to forge links with the
international anti-narcotics community which has detected new
trafficking routes across its vast expanses from the Golden
Triangle.
   Most recently, authorities in China, Hong Kong and the United
States got together to nab a ring attempting to smuggle heroin
stuffed inside dead ornamental fish. When the drug-laden gold carp
were discovered in Shanghai, Chinese police contacted American
counterparts. The fish were flown to their San Francisco
destination, along with a senior Shanghai police officer, and
subsequent arrests were made at both ends of the connection.
   Lawn said Thai-U.S. teamwork, which he rated as excellent, was
essential since Thailand was the main funnel for heroin pouring out
the Golden Triangle, which is formed by the rugged borderlands of
Burma, Laos and Thailand.
   American agents regularly tip off the Thais about suspected drug
carriers entering their country while Thai police officers have
followed traffickers to the United States to facilitate
investigations and arrests. Under a treaty now being considered,
the United States would channel a share of assets seized from
traffickers to Thailand's anti-narcotics program in cases where
Thai lawmen provided assistance.
   When U.S. sailors by the hundreds descend on Thailand's
anything-goes beach resort of Pattaya for shore leave, the two
sides activate operation ``Stable Boy.'' A DEA agent mingles with
the Americans while Thai undercover police shadow local drug
pushers.
   The leeway American agents have to operate varies among Asian
countries and there is invariably no power to arrest. But a number
of countries give DEA the green light to track traffickers and
joint operations are mounted. In 1986, a DEA agent on the Malaysian
island of Penang posed as a drug dealer to entrap a local
trafficker. When sufficient evidence was obtained, Malaysian police
moved in to make the arrest.
   In Thailand and the United States authorities are now after
traffickers behind what the Thais say is the world's greatest drug
haul: 1.4 tons of top grade heroin seized in February in Bangkok,
Thailand's capital.
   The drugs, concealed in bales of smoked rubber sheets, were
destined for New York City, where their street value, when cut and
diluted, would have been more than $2 billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs April 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
