<1ST_LINE>a i PM-LuandanNights Adv04   03-28 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Luandan Nights, Adv 04,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs April 4 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>War is Far Off When the Sun Goes Down in Angola's Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the sun goes down and the evening
breeze comes up, Luanda comes alive to an Afro-Latin beat called
batuque, nightclub doors swing open and Angola's 13-year civil war
fades away _ until tomorrow.
   The night, in this capital of 960,000 people south of the
equator, is for restaurants, discos, movie theaters, recreation
centers and pop concerts _ or even just watching ``Love Boat'' at
home on TV.
   But tomorrow always comes and one of the world's longest-running
``regional conflicts'' will be back in view again in the steaming
daylight _ the pro-Soviet, pro-Cuban and Marxist slogans on the
billboards and walls ... the troops back in battle again in the
southern countryside against the U.S. and South African-supported
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) rebels.
   But the night is for none of that in Luanda.
   At the Kizombo Recreation and Cultural Center in the Golf
neighborhood, a ``sparkling'' tropical night show goes on to the
accompaniment of a group called The Kiezos.
   Tables are available only by advance reservation and they are
for couples only.
   At the Mae Negra (Black Mother) recreational center, a private
club in the Cuca neighborhood, four women and a man go through a
gymnastic dance routine to the throbbing beata of the batuque.
   After the performance, elegantly dressed couples fill the floor
of the cavernous pink, purple, red and blue center to dance to
African, Caribbean, British and American tunes.
   Between dances, patrons fill their plates at a buffet, which
comes with the $8.30 admission, of fish stew, salads, baked beans
and tifufuntila, peanut butter mixed with manioc meal and sugar.
   Cold local beer, colas and orange sodas go with it, but
champagne can be had if ordered a week or two in advance, the
locals say.
   At discos like the Caixote (Little Box), Flamingo and Adao,
bouncer-doormen size up prospective patrons, letting in the
subdued, the well-dressed and the well-known for free.
   The T-shirt crowd and the unknown usually end up back on the
street wondering where to go before the midnight-to-6 a.m. curfew.
   A recent pop concert at the Neves Bendinha movie theater sold
out before showtime with a seat going for the same $8.30 it cost
for an evening at Mae Negra.
   On the bill one recent night was an all-star Angolan roster
including Os Anjos (The Angels), singers Minguito, Cananito
Alexandre and Ze do Pau and the closing act of ``Bruxo e A Bruxa''
(the Male and Female Witch).
   The fare at Luanda's 12 movie theaters reflects a diversity that
contrasts with the government's public austerity program and ranges
from the expected Cuban, Czechoslovak, Soviet and Yugoslav films to
Jessica Lange's ``Frances'' and ``Lonewolf McQuade,'' a Chuck
Norris action movie featuring the Texas Rangers.
   For those who stay home, TPA, the state-run television, offers
``Love Boat'' in English with Portuguese subtitles at prime time on
Sunday night.
   Angola was a Portuguese colony for 400 years until 1975 when it
gained independence, and the Portuguese language is still widely
used.
   Even in the southern provinces, close to the war zone, the
atmosphere changes when the sun goes down.
   Across the street from the Hostal America in Kuito, capital of
central Bie province, some of the 40,000 Cuban support troops in
Angola as well as Cuban civilian doctors, teachers and nurses were
seen by visiting foreign reporters whooping it up at the local
recreaction center.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs April 4</NOTE>
