<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Indian-Monuments adv06   03-28 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indian-Monuments, adv06,0850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs April 6 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thousands of India's Ancient Monuments Crumble From Neglect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEEMA SIROHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PURI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of monuments and temples from
India's ancient past are neglected and forlorn, slowly crumbling
under the onslaught of time, weather and vandals.
   Even the Taj Mahal, the 17th-century ``monument to love'' that
perhaps is the best-known symbol of India's past, is in trouble,
its marble yellowing and cracking under the assault of fumes from a
nearby oil refinery.
   Decay and disregard also blight such famed monuments as the
domed, 12th-century temple to the Hindu Lord Krishna here in Puri
and the erotic temple sculptures of Khajuraho.
   Lesser known but historically no less important monuments suffer
even more.
   Hundreds of poor people make their homes or even keep their
cattle in Mogul tombs. Others cart away chunks of monuments to
build makeshift houses. Marble is scratched with uncaring visitors'
names, and peepul or fig trees sprout from cracks in ancient walls.
   Critics attribute the disrepair to a lack of regard for history
by most Indians, a large majority of whom are concerned with
day-to-day survival, and a lack of will on the part of the
government.
   Despite protests from environmentalist, the oil refinery still
operates near the Taj Mahal in Agra, the magnificent tomb built by
the Mogul Emperor Shah Jahan for his favorite queen, Mumtaz Mahal.
   But even at that, the Taj, which attracts 1.4 million visitors a
year, is the best preserved of India's monuments, with pollution
levels at least monitored and treatment applied to stained marble.
   The famous erotic temples at Khajuraho in central India are one
of India's main tourist attractions. But large parts of the temples
are covered with moss and algae, and hundreds of smaller statues,
awaiting transport to museums, lie exposed to the sun and rain.
   Of the 85 temples built in the years 950 to 1050, only 22
survive. Those are protected from vandals and treasure hunters only
by a single barbed wire fence.
   In India, the Archaeological Survey, a 125-year-old government
body, looks after 3,524 monuments of ``national importance,'' and
state governments are responsible for 1,500 other historic
buildings. But that still leaves thousands of sites, either ancient
or notable for artistic beauty, with no protection.
   ``We try to maintain what we have in the best possible
condition,'' said J.P. Joshi, the Archaeological Survey's director
general.
   ``We have helped them survive. Ninety percent of India's ancient
history is our contribution. We have worked hard and quietly.''
   But conservation enthusiasts, such as Abhishek Singhvi, vice
president of the Delhi Conservation Society, contend that the
Archaeological Survey and the states simply do not have the money
or qualified personnel to look after all the majestic remains.
   ``This is not a priority area and funding is a perpetual
problem,'' Singhvi said.
   The survey received about $12 million for monument protection in
1985-86, or an average of $284 a month for the maintenance, repair
and protection of each of the 3,524 monuments on the list.
   The conservationists maintain the nation as a whole has become
complacent about its history.
   At Puri, one of the four major Hindu pilgrimage centers, major
leaks appeared in 1966 in the dome of the temple to Lord Krishna,
but 21 years passed before restoration started.
   The work was blocked by the temple's own priests, who went to
court claiming that repair would anger the gods and cause the
temple to collapse.
   Local kings had covered the temple with thick plaster to save it
from the salty sea breeze about 300 years ago. In time, the plaster
began to absorb water, adding enormous weight to the dome, causing
cracks and making it vulnerable, said Guru Prashad Mohanty, the
temple's chief executive officer.
   The court rejected the priests' claims last year, and hundreds
of Archaelogical Survey workers now are chiseling away the old
plaster, exposing hidden statues and strengthening the temple.
   Not all efforts at restoration have such happy endings.
   In New Delhi, which is a composite of seven cities built by
different rulers dating to the 8th century, some monuments simply
disappear as modern neighborhoods overwhelm smaller tombs and
courtyards.
   Singhvi said a 1913 survey listed about 1,400 monuments in New
Delhi. Of these, 400 have vanished without a trace, most likely
torn down overnight by people putting up houses, he added.
   New Delhi, which is a federal territory and not part of any
state, has no law empowering it to take over monuments, and it must
depend on the Archaeological Survey for conservation.
   Singhvi and other conservation enthusiasts say one way to raise
money to save India's past is to raise admission prices at
monuments, maybe as much as five times current levels. He said
foreign tourists could easily pay 70 cents instead of the present
15 cents to see the Taj Mahal.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weds PMs April 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 0914EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Nigeria-Health Adv7   03-28 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nigeria-Health, Adv 7,0777</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs April 7 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>THIRD WORLD REPORT: Nigeria Tackles Health Care Deficiencies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EVERETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hardly a week goes by without reports in
the newspapers of outbreaks of diseases among Nigeria's 100 million
people _ yellow fever, measles, meningitis, tetanus, cholera,
polio, guinea worm and others.
   Hundreds of thousands die each year as a result of infectious
disease, malnutrition, poor sanitation and the lack of medical care.
   ``The majority of our people do not have access to health
care,'' said Dr. Olikoye Ransome-Kuti, the minister in charge of
health for Africa's most populous nation.
   Her task is to improve the health of Nigeria at a time when the
once-wealthy oil giant has been forced to drastically cut spending.
   Ransome-Kuti's approach to an array of problems is nothing short
of a complete reform of the health care system and his program has
won praise from the World Health Organization in Geneva.
   ``Our priority is to establish a basic primary health care
system,'' he said in an interview. ``If we can put that in place,
at least 50 to 60 percent of our health problems will be solved.''
   Previous administrations spent millions of dollars on large
modern hospitals for the major urban areas, but most never were
completed because of financial mismanagement and the country's
falling oil revenues, Ransome-Kuti said.
   Nigeria has joined a growing number of developing countries that
are switching from large hospitals to a decentralized network of
small health centers in rural and urban areas. The centers focus on
preventative measures to control diseases before they require
expensive hospitalization or reach epidemic proportions.
   The new program stresses mass immunization campaigns, oral
rehydration therapy for diarrhea, Africa's largest child-killer,
and nutrition, hygiene and family planning education. It also seeks
to provide cleaner water and human waste disposal systems.
   Nigeria's predominantly rural population is highly susceptible
to outbreaks of measles, typhoid, cholera, and other diseases
largely caused by a lack of clean drinking water and poor hygiene.
Many villagers are suspicious of modern medicine, preferring to
visit traditional healers whose treatments often aggravate health
problems.
   The World Health Organization in Geneva once assailed Nigeria's
health policies but now applauds them.
   ``Nigeria has a headstart,'' said the organization's
representative here, Samuel Brew-Graves. ``It has the leadership
and the know-how and is applying it.''
   About a third of the nation's local government areas have been
given 500,000 naira ($100,000) each to set up community health
centers. Ultimately all 304 local areas will be included in the
program.
   Both rural and urban areas suffer from a high infant mortality
rate _ 150 per 1,000 live births in rural areas. Three in 10
children die before age 5 in the urban areas, said a 1987 Health
Ministry report.
   As many as 2,000 Nigerian children die daily due to
malnutrition, chronic undernourishment and related health problems.
   Urban hospitals are rundown and underequipped to deal with the
cities' burgeoning populations. Basic drugs are in short supply,
and the country's lack of hard currency has made it difficult to
buy spare parts for medical equipment.
   Another major problem is the low morale of doctors in the civil
service. Many doctors in urban areas moonlight illegally to
supplement their meager salaries. Others remain unemployed rather
than work in the rural areas, most of which lack even rudimentary
health facilities or basic amenities for doctors' families.
   Ransome-Kuti said last year he might be forced to import doctors
from Cuba and still is keeping that idea alive, despite protests
from the Nigerian Medical Association.
   ``My aim is to get health services to the people. If Nigerian
doctors show unwillingness to serve, I'm willing to use health
personnel from any country,'' he said.
   Ransome-Kuti's younger brother, Beko, also a doctor, is vice
president of the medical association. He said there should be no
need to import doctors.
   ``If the amount of money spent on foreign doctors was offered to
Nigerians they wouldn't be short of people applying,'' he said.
   ``The government seems to think patriotism and nationalism are
enough to get people to the rural areas. Incentives need to be
given to attract doctors there.''
   But the health minister said it is in his plans to do that,
explaining that comfortable housing, electricity, running water and
adequate schooling for doctors' children will be provided in rural
posts.
   ``Once these services are delivered, the doctors will find their
place in the rural areas,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs April 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
