<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, April 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, April 4, the 95th day of 1988. There are 271
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   Twenty years ago, on April 4, 1968, civil rights leader Martin
Luther King Jr. was shot to death in Memphis, Tenn., where he had
gone to support a strike by city sanitation workers. A student of
the life of Mahatma Gandhi and a winner of the Nobel Peace Prize,
King advocated non-violent civil disobedience as a way of combating
racism. He was 39 years old.
   On this date:
   In 1818, Congress decided the flag of the United States should
consist of 13 red and white stripes and 20 stars, with a new star
to be added for every new state of the union.
   In 1841, one month after his inaugural, President William Henry
Harrison succumbed to pneumonia, becoming the first U.S. chief
executive to die while in office.
   In 1850, the city of Los Angeles was incorporated.
   In 1887, Susanna Medora Salter became the first woman to be
elected mayor of an American community when she took office in
Argonia, Kan.
   In 1902, British financier Cecil Rhodes left $10 million in his
will to provide scholarships for Americans at Oxford University.
   In 1949, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization was founded.
   In 1969, a surgical team in Houston led by Dr. Denton Cooley
implanted a temporary artificial heart in a 47-year-old patient
while awaiting a human donor heart. The patient, Haskell Karp, died
April 8, one day after receiving a human heart.
   In 1974, Hank Aaron of the Atlanta Braves tied Babe Ruth's
home-run record by hitting his 714th round-tripper in Cincinnati.
   In 1975, more than 130 people, most of them children, were
killed when a U.S. Air Force transport plane evacuating Vietnamese
orphans crashed shortly after takeoff from Saigon.
   In 1977, 72 people were killed when a Southern Airways DC-9
crashed in New Hope, Ga.
   Ten years ago: Some 2,000 people marched through Memphis, Tenn.,
to mark the 10th anniversary of the assassination of civil rights
leader Martin Luther King Jr.
   Five years ago: The space shuttle Challenger roared into orbit
on its maiden voyage. The U.S. government granted political asylum
to Chinese tennis champion Hu Na. Actress Gloria Swanson died in
New York at age 84.
   One year ago: During a visit to Chile, Pope John Paul II
denounced torture and pleaded for reconciliation, telling tens of
thousands of people in the city of Punta Arenas, ``You must find
concrete means of creating a true culture of peace and harmony.''
   Today's Birthdays: Former dance teacher Arthur Murray is 93.
Broadcaster John Cameron Swayze is 82. Composer Elmer Bernstein is
66. Author-poet Maya Angelou is 60. Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., is
56. Baseball's National League president, A. Bartlett Giamatti, is
50. Actress Catherine Spaak is 43. Actress Nancy McKeon is 22.
   Thought for Today: ``Like anybody, I would like to live a long
life. Longevity has its place. But I'm not concerned about that
now, I just want to do God's will. And he's allowed me to go up to
the mountain, and I've looked over and I've seen the Promised
Land.'' _ Martin Luther King Jr. (1929-1968).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
