<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, April 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, April 5, the 96th day of 1988. There are 270
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 5, 1887, teacher Anne Sullivan achieved a major
breakthrough with her blind and deaf pupil, Helen Keller, by
conveying to her the meaning of the word ``water'' in the Manual
Alphabet.
   On this date:
   In 1614, American Indian princess Pocahontas married English
colonist John Rolfe in Virginia.
   In 1621, the Mayflower sailed from Plymouth, Mass., on a return
trip to England.
   In 1649, Elihu Yale, the English philanthropist for whom Yale
University is named, was born.
   In 1792, President George Washington cast his first veto,
rejecting a congressional measure for apportioning representatives
among the states.
   In 1856, black American educator Booker T. Washington was born
in Franklin County, Va.
   In 1951, Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were sentenced to death
after their conviction on charges of being atomic spies for the
Soviet Union.
   In 1964, Army Gen. Douglas MacArthur died in Washington at age
84.
   In 1975, nationalist Chinese leader Chiang Kai-shek died in
Taipei at age 87.
   In 1976, reclusive billionaire Howard Hughes died in Houston at
age 72.
   In 1980, the world's most valuable stamp, an 1856 British Guiana
one-cent magenta, was sold at auction in New York to an anonymous
buyer for $850,000.
   In 1986, an American soldier and a Turkish woman were killed in
the bombing of a West Berlin discotheque, an incident that prompted
a U.S. air raid on Libya more than a week later.
   Ten years ago: Addressing an international group of journalists
and academics in Cairo, Egyptian President Anwar Sadat called on
Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin to be ``more flexible'' in
peace negotiations.
   Five years ago: France expelled about 50 Soviet diplomats and
officials, accusing them of trying to steal military secrets. The
Soviet embassy called the expulsions an unjustified political act.
   One year ago: President Reagan arrived in Canada for a summit
with Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, who prodded the U.S.
administration and Congress to take tougher action on acid rain.
   Today's Birthdays: Actress Bette Davis is 80. Conductor Herbert
Von Karajan is 80. Actor Gregory Peck is 72. Actress Gale Storm is
66. Impressionist-actor Frank Gorshin is 54. Actor Michael Moriarty
is 47. Actor Max Gail is 45.
   Thought for Today: ``It is indeed difficult to define just who
the `modern man' is, and what views he has to hold in order to be
modern.'' _ Josiah Royce, American philosopher (1855-1916).
</TEXT>
