<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, April 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, April 6, the 97th day of 1988. There are 269
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On April 6, 1909, American explorer Robert Edwin Peary became
the first person to lead an expedition to the North Pole.
   On this date:
   In 1830, the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints was
organized by Joseph Smith at Fayette, N.Y.
   In 1862, the Civil War battle of Shiloh began as the
Confederates attacked Union forces in Tennessee.
   In 1892, author and newscaster Lowell Thomas was born in
Woodington, Ohio.
   In 1896, the first modern Olympic games were formally opened in
Athens, Greece.
   In 1917, Congress approved a declaration of war against Germany.
   In 1963, the United States and Britain signed an agreement under
which the Americans would sell Polaris A-3 missiles to the British.
   In 1965, the United States launched the Early Bird
communications satellite.
   In 1971, Russian-born composer Igor Stravinsky died in New York.
   In 1984, the space shuttle Challenger blasted off from Cape
Canaveral, Fla., on a mission to recover and repair a damaged
satellite in orbit.
   In 1985, William J. Schroeder became the first artificial heart
recipient to be discharged from the hospital when he moved into an
apartment in Louisville, Ky., a short distance from Humana Hospital
Audubon.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter signed legislation
extending the mandatory retirement age for most private employees
from 65 to 70 and prohibiting the federal government from requiring
otherwise qualified civilian workers to retire at any age.
   Five years ago: Saying rock bands attracted ``the wrong
element,'' Interior Secretary James Watt declined to invite the
Beach Boys to perform in Washington at a July 4th celebration _ a
decision he later reversed.
   One year ago: The Dow Jones industrial average closed above
2,400 for the first time. New York Congressman Jack Kemp began his
bid for the Republican presidential nomination. Sugar Ray Leonard
upset Marvelous Marvin Hagler to become middleweight champion. Los
Angeles Dodgers executive Al Campanis told ABC's ``Nightline'' that
blacks ``may not have some of the necessities'' to hold managerial
jobs in major-league baseball.
   Today's Birthdays: Composer-conductor Andre Previn is 59. Actor
Ivan Dixon is 57. Country singer Merle Haggard is 51. Actor Billy
Dee Williams is 51. Actor Roy Thinnes is 50. Singer Michelle
Phillips is 44. Actress Marilu Henner is 36. Figure skater Janet
Lynn is 35.
   Thought for Today: ``The brain is a wonderful organ. It starts
working the moment you get up in the morning and does not stop
until you get into the office.'' _ Robert Frost, American poet
(1874-1963).
</TEXT>
