<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1342EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--Oscars Adv10   03-28 0986</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Oscars, Adv 10,1007</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10
^From AP Newsfeatures</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ The Academy Awards ritual returns to an ancient
venue with a wide-open contest among nominated performers. Cher?
Glenn Close? Sally Kirkland? Will Michael Douglas win the Oscar
that has eluded his father? It'll all be settled Monday night on
the stage of the cavernous Shrine Auditorium.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar moves to a new-old location Monday
night for the 60th Academy Awards, which are expected to be
dominated by ``The Last Emperor,'' Bernardo Bertolucci's epic of
modern China.
   The venerable Shrine Auditorium, where the awards were presented
in 1946 and 1947, will again be the site of Hollywood's grandest
affair. ``The Last Emperor'' has been labeled the favored picture
at the ceremonies, especially since Bertolucci won the Directors
Guild award. The directors have proven uncanny in presaging the
Oscars, deviating only three times in 40 years.
   ``Broadcast News'' was an early favorite, but its vogue seems to
have faded. ``Moonstruck'' has proven extremely popular at the box
office and could stage a surprise victory. Less likely are the
other two nominees, ``Fatal Attraction'' and ``Hope and Glory.''
   The nominated performances afford a wide-open contest,
particularly among the actresses. Both Cher (``Moonstruck'') and
Glenn Close (``Fatal Attraction'') have their champions, as does
Sally Kirkland (``Anna''), who collected several critics' awards.
Also nominated are Holly Hunter (``Broadcast News'') and Meryl
Streep (``Ironweed'').
   Michael Douglas delivered two strong performances in 1987 in
``Fatal Attraction'' and ``Wall Street,'' the latter bringing his
nomination. He might well win the Oscar, a feat that has eluded his
father Kirk.
   Marcello Mastroianni (``Dark Eyes'') might be honored for his
long, distinguished career. Then again, Academy voters might
finally recognize comedy and reward Robin Williams for ``Good
Morning, Vietnam.'' Also nominated are previous winners Jack
Nicholson (``Ironweed'') and William Hurt (``Broadcast News'').
   The supporting performance categories are equally impressive.
For supporting actress: Norma Aleandro, ``Gaby''; Anne Archer,
``Fatal Attraction''; Olympia Dukakis, ``Moonstruck''; Anne Ramsey,
``Throw Momma from the Train''; Ann Sothern, ``The Whales of
August.''
   For supporting actor: Albert Brooks, ``Broadcast News''; Sean
Connery, ``The Untouchables''; Morgan Freeman, ``Street Smart'';
Vincent Gardenia, ``Moonstruck''; Denzel Washington, ``Cry
Freedom.''
   Among the directors, Bertolucci appears the solid favorite.
Other probables: Louis Malle's ``Au Revoir Les Enfants'' for
foreign language film and ``(I've Had) The Time of My Life'' from
``Dirty Dancing'' for original song.
   The 60th Academy Awards have proven remarkably free of
controversy, at least in the nomination stages. The one
eyebrow-raiser was the failure to nominate James L. Brooks as best
director for ``Broadcast News.'' Since Brooks wrote, directed and
produced the film that was nominated for best picture and for three
of its actors, how could his direction go unmentioned? Another
Academy mystery.
   Monday night's ceremonies will be televised (ABC-TV, 9 p.m. EDT)
from the stage of the Shrine Auditorium, an ancient cavern a few
blocks from the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum. The move from the
marble and crystal Los Angeles Music Center might seem like a step
backward, but the Academy governors had their reasons.
   For years, producers have smarted over the limited rehearsal
time afforded by the Music Center, which also houses symphonies and
operas. Also, the limited seating capacity of 3,400 didn't allow
the Academy to accommodate members' requests for tickets.
   The Shrine holds 6,308, and at $150 for the best seats and $300
for the Board of Governors Ball in the adjacent exhibition hall,
the event can supply much-needed funds for the Academy.
   Oscar has wandered over a large portion of Los Angeles County
during 60 years. The first event was held on May 16, 1929, in the
Blossom Room of the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel. The 270 film
industry leaders who attended paid $5 a head to dine on squab and
lobster _ no booze in those Prohibition times.
   For the next 14 years, the golden statuettes were presented at
relatively intimate industry dinners in two hotel ballrooms _ the
Ambassador's Coconut Grove and the Biltmore Bowl. Old-timers view
those events with great nostalgia; they were warm, friendly
gatherings during an era when Hollywood had a sense of community.
   The war changed that. In 1944, formal dinners seemed incongruous
with wartime austerity. The dinners were abandoned for the
Grauman's Chinese theater, which could accommodate servicemen
guests with its 2,258 capacity. No black tie or formal gowns,
either. They were considered unpatriotic.
   After three years at the Chinese, the Academy sought a bigger
house, moving to the Shrine Auditorium. Then in 1949 came the nadir
of Oscar's fortunes.
   From the beginning of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences, the major studios supplied financing. Then, in 1949, amid
claims by some critics that the studios were upset by the Academy's
frequent rewarding of European films, the studios withdrew their
support. They claimed they did so to avoid criticism that they
overly influenced voting.
   Totally broke, the Academy was forced to present the 21st awards
in its own 985-seat screening theater, once a neighborhood movie
house. The studios resumed their support, and for the next 11 years
the awards were presented at the art-deco Pantages theater on
Hollywood Boulevard.
   Seeking greater capacity, the Academy Awards moved out of Los
Angeles for the first time in l961, settling into the Santa Monica
Civic Auditorium for the next eight years. The location a couple of
blocks from the Pacific prompted Bob Hope to comment: ``The losers
can walk into the ocean.''
   In 1969, Oscar began a 20-year run in the Dorothy Chandler
Pavilion of the Music Center. Now the awards follow the Grammys to
the Shrine, which also attracted this year's Emmys from their
longtime base at the Pasadena Civic Auditorium.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
