<DOCNO> AP880328-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1344EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--Oscars-Predictions Adv10   03-28 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Oscars-Predictions, Adv 10,0282</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Oscars</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the Academy Awards had been given in
December instead of April, the winner might well have been
``Broadcast News.''
   That's the way it looks to this Oscar-watcher. James L. Brooks'
funny, insightful look at the madness of the television news
business was the talk of Hollywood. But after a few weeks the talk
diminished, and ``Broadcast News'' did not become the box-office
smash that some had predicted.
   Suddenly ``The Last Emperor'' began drawing more respect. As
drama it may have been wanting, but his fellow filmmakers admired
Bernardo Bertolucci's achievement in fulfilling such a difficult
project with style and class. Hence ``The Last Emperor'' appears
the favorite to win as best picture and for Bertolucci's direction.
   Here is an estimate of the acting categories:
   Best actress: Again, Holly Hunter of ``Broadcast News'' was the
early favorite, but she pulled a vanishing act while Cher appeared
on a half-dozen magazine covers. For exposure alone (please, no
puns), Cher looks like the winner for ``Moonstruck.'' Her
performance was widely admired besides.
   Best actor: It looks like the year of Michael Douglas. No more
the nice guy, he was impressive as the Boesky-like inside trader in
``Wall Street.''
   Best supporting actress: Ann Sothern would be the sentimental
choice for ``The Whales of August.'' But the likely winner is
Olympia Dukakis of ``Moonstruck.''
   Best supporting actor: A spirited race, but here sentiment is
likely to prevail _ Sean Connery for ``The Untouchables.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
