<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1400EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv10   03-28 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 10,0858</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gregory Harrison hadn't intended to play in
his remake of the 1948 screen classic ``Red River'' until several
actors turned down the role of the gunfighter.
   ``Two weeks before we started shooting, we still hadn't cast the
role of Cherry Valance,'' says Harrison. ``After several actors
turned it down I said, `I guess that means I should do the part.'
That's how I ended up in it. Everybody else had been cast for a
long time.''
   James Arness stars as Tom Dunson, a tough, embittered ranch
owner who organizes a cattle drive at the end of the Civil War to
save his financially troubled empire. Bruce Boxleitner is Matthew
Garth, his adopted son just back from the war, who clashes
repeatedly with Dunson. The two-hour movie will be telecast Sunday
on CBS.
   The story, in essence, is ``Mutiny on the Bounty'' on a trail
drive, as Matthew is finally driven to rebellion against his
tyrannical adoptive father.
   Harrison, who is co-executive producer with his partner in
Catalina Productions, Franklin R. Levy, says it was ``scary''
taking on the remake of the beloved Western.
   John Wayne starred in the original as Dunson. Montgomery Clift
was Matt. The movie, directed by Howard Hawks, also starred Walter
Brennan, Joanne Dru and John Ireland. Ray Walston plays the Brennan
role, Laura Johnson plays Dru's role and Harrison takes over from
Ireland.
   The closest Harrison's ever come to playing in a Western was the
role as pioneer Levi Zendt in the miniseries ``Centennial.''
   ``I was able to have a lot of freedom with the role of the
gunfighter because I wasn't carrying the movie,'' he says. ``I
could play the bad guy and have fun. I think my work is better
because I did feel free to take chances. I loved putting on the
chaps and the gun belt. I learned to rope.''
   Although it's a memorable movie, Harrison points out that it was
made 40 years ago. ``Most people today haven't seen it except on
the late show.'' he says. ``We've added some new characters and
story lines. My partner and I were also very interested in doing a
Western and there aren't very many opportunities for that.''
   There remain many links between old and new. The remake was
filmed in the same area between Tucson, Ariz., and the Mexican
border. Four members of Hawks' crew worked on the remake, as did
stunt man Bud Stout, who had a small role in the original.
   Arness was Wayne's protege, and it was Wayne who helped him get
the role as Matt Dillon on ``Gunsmoke.'' Boxleitner and Arness had
played together for a number of years in ``How The West Was Won.''
The branding iron used by Wayne was found and used in the new film.
   At the first reading of the script Arness read Boxleitner's
lines by mistake. After 20 years as Matt Dillon on ``Gunsmoke,'' he
read the lines for Matt by force of habit.
   Stan Shaw stars in a new role as a black broncobuster and
Zachary Ansley, a newcomer from Vancouver, Canada, plays the new
role of a teen-ager named Cal.
   ``I think we have a stronger story,'' says Harrison. ``We don't
have the limitations they had when they made the first one. I like
the idea of the black cowboy. It reflects more of today's thinking.
The only question is that you had such memorable performances (in
the original) that nostalgia buffs may not be able to accept (the
remake).''
   Harrison, who recently starred with John Larroquette in the CBS
comedy ``Hot Paint,'' spent 30 days at the Betty Ford Center to
break his dependency on drugs and alcohol. ``It's a very strong
program that teaches you to stay away from drugs and alcohol for
life,'' he says. ``It works for a lot of people. It works for me.''
   He's also producing a stage musical called ``Blame It on the
Movies,'' which features nearly a hundred movie tunes, and a
theatrical comedy called ``My Stepmother Is an Alien.'' Dan Aykroyd
and Kim Basinger star in the sci-fi comedy with Richard Benjamin
directing.
   Away from work, Harrison, whose father was the glass-bottom boat
operator on Catalina Island, is pursuing his goal of surfing around
the world.
   So far, he has surfed at Bali, Fiji, France, England, Denmark,
Israel, Greece, Morocco, South Africa, Australia and in the
Caribbean, as well as Hawaii and elsewhere in the United States.
   Harrison's last series was ``Trapper John, M.D.,'' in which he
played Gonzo for eight years.
   ``I'm ready to get back into a half-hour comedy show,'' he says.
``One that I'm producing and have control over. An hour show takes
too much of your time. I enjoy being around my wife and child too
much to do another hour show.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
