<DOCNO> AP880328-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Israel-Islam Adv03-1stadd   03-28 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Israel-Islam, Adv 03-1st add,0590</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>BEIT AL MAA: Saftawi said.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Growing to more than 50 active members, Jihad Islami in Gaza
drew inspiration from preachers with close ties with Iran, but
Saftwai insisted there was no outside direction or funding.
   The Iran orientation contrasts with the Moslem Brothers, who
support Iraq in the Gulf War and, as Sunni Moslems, oppose the
religious dogmas of Ayatollah Khomeini's Shiite Moslem regime.
   Saftawi, who joined the Moslem Brotherhood as a student in Cairo
in the 1950s and later was jailed in Israel for PLO activism, spoke
with pride about the group.
   The youths, jailed after carrying out knifings that wounded four
Israeli civilians, became local heros when six broke out of the
central Gaza prison on May 18, 1987.
   For five months they stayed underground, until October, when
four were killed in a shootout with Israeli forces. His son and
another man escaped abroad, a feat previously considered impossible.
   ``By their actions and their success, they gave confidence to
the Palestinian people to depend on themselves and be
self-sufficient,'' said Saftawi.
   This can-do attitude contrasts with ``the spirit and mood'' of
the older generation that had relied on outside help for
deliverance, Saftawi said.
   ``We were deceived into believing help would come from outside
and waited for the Arabs or Islamic states or the United Nations to
do something.''
   Two days after the interview in his home in Gaza City, Saftawi
was placed under administrative detention by Israeli military
authorities, who can keep him for six months without trial.
   The PLO, in response to fundamentalist revival, has tried to
channel some of the religious zeal into its own movement and has
formed an alliance with the student groups like Jihad Islami in
Gaza.
   Zohair Saadat Al Didi, 39, a Moslem preacher who served seven
years in jail for belonging to a guerrilla cell of Arafat's Fatah
movement, argues that a political settlement would stop the growth
of radical, fundamentalist groups.
   ``If the situation improves, then there would be no room for
such groups to continue. These groups will become weak and
ineffective,'' said Al Didi, a freelance journalist in Nablus,
known to his friends as Abu Islam.
   ``This occupation is good for the Moslem Brothers and other
radical movements.''
   Al Didi said even though his Fatah cell attacked and wounded an
Israeli soldier he does not believe in violence against civilians.
   ``I believe there should be coexistence between us and the
Israelis,'' he said. ``There is a possibility of reaching an
understanding and sharing the land: two states, a confederation,
cantons, it is not important how.''
   The relative strengths of the PLO and Islamic groups is
difficult to assess.
   Clinton Bailey, an Islamic expert at Tel Aviv University who is
carrying out a study, said fundamentalists claimed the allegiance
of at least 30 percent of the 850,000 residents of the West Bank
while in Gaza it was nearly 80 percent of 650,000.
   ``There is a certain gray area because not all people are one or
the other. Many who identify with the PLO also became religious,''
said Bailey.
   Religious zeal, he added, was one of the factors that brought
about the uprising.
   ``It gave people more daring and more of a willingness to
sacrifice. It is identified with a certain honesty, not tainted
like the PLO by materialism and corruption.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
