<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1435EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideos Adv00   03-28 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Videos, Adv 00,0941</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video Views: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the biggest hits of last summer was Buena
Vista's ``Stakeout,'' a cop buddy movie starring Richard Dreyfuss
and Emilio Estevez.
   Earning $65 million, it had the longest hold in the No. 1
box-office spot and was one of the Top 10 movies of 1987.
   The comedy-thriller directed by John Badham is available this
month for home screens from Touchstone Home Video. It's one of two
recent hit movies in which a policeman assigned to watch a woman
falls in love with her. The other was ``Someone to Watch Over Me,''
starring Tom Berenger, available from RCA-Columbia Pictures Home
Video.
   Elsewhere, HBO Video plans a new music series called ``Super
Sessions.'' Available in May, the series will feature concerts and
performances by such musical talents as B.B. King, Roy Orbison,
Chaka Khan, Phil Collins, Freda Payne, Martha Reeves, Billy Ocean,
Eric Clapton and Etta James.
   ``Roy Orbison & Friends: A Black and White Night'' ($19.99,
VHS@Beta) will be one of the first videos released in the series.
Joining Orbison on stage are Jackson Browne, Elvis Costello, Bonnie
Raitt, T-Bone Burnett, Tom Waits, Jennifer Warnes and Bruce
Springsteen.
   The concert, featuring such Orbison hits as ``Only the Lonely''
and ``Crying,'' was filmed at the Cocoanut Grove in Los Angeles in
September 1987 and was made in black and white.
   Axon Video has released the Italian comedy, ``Spaghetti House''
($69.95, VHS@Beta), starring Nino Manfredi (``Bread and
Chocolate''). In English, the movie romps through the true story
about a group of Italian waiters who are held hostage in a London
restaurant.
   Also new from Axon is ``Vogues of 1938'' ($69.95, VHS@Beta). The
1937 movie, filmed in Technicolor, stars Warner Baxter in a story
about rival fashion houses. It features the Academy Award nominated
song, ``That Old Feeling,'' and a rare filmed performance from the
original Cotton Club Revue.
   Videos reviewed this week are ``Stakeout'' and ``Someone to
Watch Over Me.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Stakeout'' (Touchstone Home Video, $89.95, VHS@Beta, Rated R)
   
   John Badham's action-comedy opens on a richly funny note:
Richard Dreyfuss, a police officer, chases a bad guy and finds
himself squirming about in a vat filled with dead fish in a factory.
   Is this a cop or a guy auditioning for an Abbott and Costello
flick? Yeah, he's a cop all right, but teamed with ex-Brat Packer
Emilio Estevez, the nutty covortings often remind one of a comedy
duo.
   As the detective buddies, Chris and Bill, they are given the
overnight stakeout of Maria (Madeleine Stowe), the girlfriend of an
escaped murderer (Aidan Quinn). They ogle the beauty through a
telescope, and things become dicey when Chris (Dreyfuss) and Maria
meet and fall in love.
   ``I have to face up to my heterosexuality, but don't worry,
you'll be well provided for,'' he tells his partner.
   The chases, the violent teases (there's a cliffhanger or two in
a sawmill and a boat escape) and the nuttiness of Dreyfuss and
Estevez hold up well on the small screen. Badham maintains a
comfortable and easy balance between the banter and thrills. And
the chemistry between Dreyfuss and Estevez makes them believable
and lovable cop buddies and provides a good hoot on a rainy
afternoon or lazy night.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Someone to Watch Over Me'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video,
$89.95, VHS@Beta, Rated R)
   
   ``Someone to Watch Over Me'' was one of two movies last year in
which the plot hinged on a cop falling in love with a woman he was
assigned to watch. ``Stakeout,'' a box-office smash, exploited the
comic, screwball potential of that device; in ``Someone,'' the
romance leads to near-tragic complications.
   Tom Berenger plays a New York City police officer, newly
promoted to detective, who lives happily in Queens with his warm,
no-nonsense wife (Lorraine Bracco) and son. The trouble starts when
he is assigned on the all-night shift to guard Mimi Rogers, a
Manhattan heiress who has witnessed a savage murder and is waiting
to identify the killer in a lineup.
   Long nights alone together in Miss Rogers' mammoth and elegant
East Side apartment lead to an affair, which jeopardizes Berenger's
marriage and career, as well as the lives of all the major
characters.
   What lends distinction to this essentially simple melodrama are
some fine performances _ especially by Berenger and Miss Bracco _
and the stylish direction of Ridley (``Alien'') Scott.
   Berenger, with his sensitive portrayal of a likable character
betrayed by his own weakness, demonstrates again his enormous
range. Hard to believe this is the same actor who played the
earnest but shallow TV star in ``The Big Chill'' and the evil
sergeant in ``Platoon.''
   Andreas Katsulas deserves mention, too, for his chilling
portrayal of a particularly sadistic villain.
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
