<DOCNO> AP880328-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1436EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-28 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0670</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Lefty'' (Columbia) _ Art Garfunkel
   
   When Art Garfunkel released his first solo album in 1973,
ultra-hip Rolling Stone magazine interviewed him and asked him just
who he thought would purchase an album of sweet love songs (like
Jimmy Webb's ``All I Know'') in the waning days of acid rock.
``English lit. majors,'' he suggested.
   It is with the same wit and grace that Garfunkel offers
``Lefty,'' his seventh solo album, a lovely, unrelentingly romantic
record typified by such selections as the evocative ``I Have a
Love,'' a Bernstein-Sondheim selection from ``West Side Story.''
   Garfunkel makes even more use of his unique vocal style on this
album than he has on previous records, from the finger-snapping
``So Much in Love,'' a remake of the Tymes' 1963 hit, to a
interesting, Third World-sounding arrangement of Percy Sledge's
``When a Man Loves a Woman.''
   Background singers Pam Rose and Mary Ann Kennedy, members of the
Nashville group Calamity Jane, are the writers of the beautiful
``Love Is the Only Chain,'' which should be a hit on its own. Leah
Kunkel also sings backup, as does Stephen Bishop, who contributes
three songs. Kenny Rankin is heard on ``I Wonder Why.''
   ``Lefty'' is a soothing album, but by no means homogenized. With
each distinctive cut, Garfunkel proves his subtle range and
establishes once again that his taste in music is superb. Pop music
rarely shows more class.
   _ By Kathryn Baker, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Beethoven, Symphony No. 9 (EMI) _ The London Classical Players,
the Schutz Choir of London, Roger Norrington conducting.
   Beethoven Cello Sonatas (Nonesuch) _ Anner Bylsma, cello;
Malcolm Bilson, fortepiano.
   Beethoven or Bust (Telarc) _ Don Dorsey, synthesizers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   There is a shock in seeing a monument, however familiar, cleaned
of accumulated grit and grime. It's recognizably the same, yet a
constant surprise in its new colors and highlights.
   Roger Norrington has achieved something quite as spectacular
with his recording of Beethoven's choral symphony. Stripped of the
extra parts added as orchestras grew, and shorn of interpretive
conventions of the late 19th and 20th centuries, the symphony
sounds fresh and new.
   Norrington returned not just to the original instrumentation,
but to Beethoven's tempo markings.
   Some of those tempos at first seem agonizingly slow, especially
in the concluding choral movement, but the logic becomes clear. The
chorus is not whipped into a shrieking frenzy as often happens in
the ``Ode to Joy.''
   This Ninth is an outstanding achievement.
   Beethoven is also brilliantly served by another exercise in
original instrumentation, the first and second cello sonatas
recorded by cellist Anner Bylsma and fortepianist Malcolm Bilson.
   By now, the question about any such performance is not whether
the instrumentation is authentic _ are the strings from a breed of
cat which Beethoven would have recognized? _ but whether the music
is compelling.
   On that score, Bylsma and Bilson are outstanding. Their
instruments may speak more quietly than their modern counterparts,
but with no less conviction or fire.
   Turning to completely unoriginal instruments...
   ``Beethoven or Bust'' sounds promising for, oh, about the first
10 seconds of the first cut, ``Rage Over a Lost Penny.'' Then comes
the first tinkle of a synthesized cymbal, followed shortly by an
elephantine boom-chuck boom-chuck boom-chuck, apparently added so
that the musically ignorant will know when to tap their feet.
   This is the sort of sensibility which holds that the Parthenon
by moonlight may be OK, but to really enjoy it you need a seltzer
bottle and a whoopee cushion.
   Don Dorsey, who had a chart-topper with ``Bachbusters'' in 1986,
is a skillful technician but, on this try, a musician of abysmal
taste. Skip it.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Sothern Adv08-10   03-28 0938</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Sothern, Adv 08-10,0960</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08-10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 8-10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Ann Sothern Never Envisioned Oscar Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Look at that air!'' Ann Sothern exclaimed
as she gazed at the smog-laden sky outside the window of her
westside hotel room. ``Now you can see why I no longer live here.''
   For the better part of a half-century, the blond actress had
lived in Los Angeles, where she appeared in 56 movies and 178
television episodes of ``Private Secretary'' and ``The Ann Sothern
Show.'' In recent years a resident of Sun Valley, Idaho, she
returned to her old home town to bask in newfound glory: her
Academy Award nomination as supporting actress for ``The Whales of
August.''
   How did she hear the news?
   ``I was sound asleep, and what woke me was the sound that a
telephone makes when it's off the hook. So I hung it up, and the
phone rang immediately. It was a friend of mine from here, and she
said, `I suppose everybody in the world has been calling you.' I
said no, the phone was off the hook.
   ``She said, `Well, you did it! You got a nomination!' That's how
I learned. Then of course the phone didn't stop all day.''
   She had never thought of herself as an Oscar contender during
her long years in the studios _ ``until this year at least, my type
of work (comedy) was not considered very important for awards. But
of course my performance in `Whales' is not comedic.''
   She was cast as the flighty neighbor of sisters Bette Davis and
Lillian Gish, neither of whom was nominated despite early
predictions.
   ``I'm an old method actress,'' Miss Sothern said. ``Anyone who
has studied (Konstantin) Stanislavski (the Russian actor, director
and teacher) understands you do preparation for the part. What
intrigued me most was that the name of the character was Tisha.
That's my daughter's name. I thought, Lord, there must be some
reason for them to have sent me this part.
   ``I liked the role very much, and I realized it wasn't too much
for me. She was very capricious, very flirtatious. I thought the
red wig I wore was very good for the character. I did the part
about two decibels above my regular speaking voice, and I was
adamant about doing a Yankee accent.''
   About the reports of a feud between legends Davis and Gish:
   ``Lindsay Anderson (the director) is a very strong man, and he
kept things in hand. I think he and Bette had a few tiffs, but I
had no problems. I happen to be a diplomat as well as a tough lady,
and I think Bette respected that. Besides, we've known each other
for a long, long time.
   ``I had never even met Miss Gish, and I was in awe to be in the
presence of this beautiful and talented legend. So we got along
well.''
   Miss Sothern shuns mention of age, but the record books show
that she was born Jan. 22, 1909, in Valley City, N.D., and began
her film career in the 1929 sound musical ``The Show of Shows.''
She is heavier than in her MGM heyday and walks hesitantly, the
result of a long battle with ill health including a broken back.
But her mind remains as lively as ever.
   She marks her film beginnings with the 1933 musical ``Let's Fall
in Love.'' That's when Columbia boss Harry Cohn changed her name
from Harriet Lake to Ann Sothern, reasoning that there were too
many Lakes in movies.
   ``The movie almost killed me,'' she said, recalling the years
when actors could be worked 12 hours a day, six days a week. ``I
decided then that I would never work after 5 o'clock, because there
is just so much you have to give. And I never did.''
   The actress moved on to RKO and in 1938 to MGM, which she still
remembers with great fondness: ``We were the last of the MGM
`babies' _ myself, Ava Gardner, Judy Garland, Mickey Rooney, Van
Johnson, others. I had Greta Garbo's dressing room, next to Greer
Garson's and Joan Crawford's. We were pampered, and we loved it.''
   At MGM she starred in seven ``Maisie'' films, sang the
Oscar-winning ``The Last Time I Saw Paris'' in ``Lady Be Good'' and
played the Ethel Merman role in ``Panama Hattie.'' In the early
1950s she was felled by hepatitis.
   ``I was immobilized for a couple of years,'' she recalled.
``When I recovered, I realized I had to prove that I was still able
to work. So I went back to the theater and did a play with Robert
Cummings for seven months. When I came back, my agent said,
`Something new is happening, and you ought to get into it.'''
   The ``something new'' was television, and the two series created
a whole new audience. Reruns of the shows are broadcast on
Nickelodeon on cable TV.
   Six years ago Miss Sothern moved to Sun Valley, where she had
skied since the early 1940s.
   ``It's a fairyland,'' she rhapsodized. ``Beautiful, clean air _
we're at 5,600 feet _ and it's a healthful atmosphere; everybody
skis. Yes, it can also be boring, but I'm thinking of becoming
involved in a new theater up there.''
   She was married to two actors: Roger Pryor (1936-42) and Robert
Sterling (1943-49).
   ``They were not happy marriages, and I decided not to marry
again,'' she sighed. ``I made a mistake. But then, I always was too
independent.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 8-10</NOTE>
