<DOCNO> AP880328-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1457EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Updike-Rabbit Adv08-10   03-28 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Updike-Rabbit, Adv 08-10,0560</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08-10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 8-10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>RABBIT, RERUN: Updike Promises to Bring Back Harry Angstrom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-WKD--Updike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Are we going to see Harry Angstrom again?
   Author John Updike was recently asked that question while
plugging his new novel, ``S.''
   ``Yes. I hope, if I keep my wits and live a few more years, to
write one more Rabbit novel,'' said Updike, interviewed on his 56th
birthday and perhaps feeling intimations of mortality. ``I look
forward to it, in fact, and it's the next novel on my schedule.''
   Harry ``Rabbit'' Angstrom, Updike fans know, is the protagonist
of the author's Rabbit trilogy.
   When we first met Harry in 1960 in ``Rabbit, Run'' he was a
26-year-old MagiPeel salesman in Brewer, Pa., still coasting on his
glory days as a high school basketball star _ that's how he got his
nickname Rabbit because he was fast on the court. The book's sexual
candor made it a sensation.
   In 1971's ``Rabbit Redux'' Harry, now a typesetter, links up
with a flower child and a black revolutionary. In ``Rabbit Is
Rich,'' which won the author a Pulitzer, Harry has reunited with
his wife, Janice, and becomes prosperous almost by accident when he
takes over his father-in-law's Toyota dealership at the height of
the 1970s gas crunch.
   Harry Angstrom, who has has become as much a part of the
American literary iconography as Holden Caufield, is Updike's ode
to the American male. He is a philanderer and a flirt, sometimes
chauvinistic and a little bit of a jerk. Yet Updike has imbued him
with a magical quality that elevates him. Harry is the embodiment
of grace; he has an innocence and an optimism that is enduring. We
forgive him his weaknesses; we are charmed by his foibles.
   Updike said he had not yet started writing the fourth book.
   ``The reason I haven't started it _ I'm kind of itching to get
going on it, as a matter of fact, and I have a few ideas _ but the
books have all taken place in the ninth year of the decade,
sometimes the 10th. They kind of by accident, then on purpose, wrap
up the decade. So I have to give it another year to see what the
country's going to do,'' he said.
   ``I don't want to overemphasize that side of the books. They're
not just meant to be headline blotters. But on the other hand some
topical constituent has always been there ... and in some sense
Harry is a typical American and the headlines go on as a kind of
background. So there's always been a link between him and the life
of the nation. And I have to see what happens, what will be the
post-Reagan era.
   ``Rabbit is the only novel on my horizon and I think it'll take
a while. I don't want to rush it. I'd like it to be worthy of the
series, and in a way, cap it.''
   Will Rabbit practice safe sex? Did he lose his shirt in the
stock market crash? Have yuppies inflated real estate prices in
Brewer? We'll find out in 1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 8-10</NOTE>
</DOC>
