<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-28 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0552</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. has begun talks concerning the
possible sale of the entire building materials and cement company
to counter a hostile takeover attempt by Beazer PLC, Koppers
Chairman Charles R. Pullin said.
   Pullin said in a written statement Sunday discussions were being
held with ``certain third parties.'' Koppers spokesman Robert J.
O'Gara declined to elaborate.
   Beazer, unable to lure Koppers into a friendly deal, boosted its
hostile tender offer for the building materials and cement company
to $1.7 billion on Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resorts International Inc., the target of
rival takeover bids from entertainer Merv Griffin and developer
Donald Trump, is trying to line up $600 million in high-yield bond
financing, mostly to complete its overdue and over-budget Taj Mahal
hotel-casino.
   The financing negotiations were disclosed Friday by Trump, who
controls 88 percent of Resorts' voting strength, is the company's
chairman and is seeking to buy the rest of its stock and take it
private.
   If Trump's takeover bid fails, the company may seek a smaller
amount of financing, Trump said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real-estate magnate Donald Trump is adding the
landmark Plaza Hotel to his growing empire with plans to spruce up
everything but its name.
   ``It's got the most important name in the world, and it's going
to remain that way,'' Trump said Saturday as he announced he had
purchased the world-renown Plaza for $390 million.
   He vowed the Plaza, already New York City's most famous hotel,
would become ``the most luxurious hotel in the world'' under the
supervision of his wife, Ivana.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a month before the filing deadline,
fewer than half of Americans have finished their tax returns. But
refunds are bigger, the IRS is doing a better job answering
questions, and taxpayers are making fewer mistakes than had been
expected.
   The Internal Revenue Service is almost 3 percent behind last
year's pace in processing returns, but blames that chiefly on
taxpayers' slowness in filing this year. Officials say there is
nothing to signal a repeat of 1985 when faulty computer programs
set off a chain of events that resulted in the worst filing season
in modern times.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes, after declining for
three straight months, posted a modest increase of 3.8 percent in
February, a real estate trade group reported.
   The National Association of Realtors said Friday existing
single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.29 million units in February. It was the first advance since a
1.2 percent rise in October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration launched a final
attempt to overturn a 46-year-old law that prohibits manufacturers
from hiring people to produce apparel in their homes.
   The Labor Department said Friday it will publish proposed
regulations this week that would allow employers to contract work
from people in their homes in five industries: gloves and mittens,
embroideries, buttons and buckles, handkerchiefs and some jewelry.
   However, unlike its two previous attempts to deregulate
so-called industrial homework, officials said this time they will
not try to remove the ban on women's apparel.
</TEXT>
