<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   03-28 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0556</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $2 trillion in Japanese savings accounts
loses its tax-free status this week, and executives from Tokyo
investment firms to foreign manufacturers are dreaming of tapping
into the treasure trove.
   The April 1 change was prompted by complaints from allies that
Japan needs to spur domestic consumption as a way to recycle some
of its $82.7 billion annual trade surplus.
   The hope is the new 20 percent tax on interest will encourage
Japanese to save less and spend more. But many experts do not
foresee that happening.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese monopolies on trade in tobacco and
beef must be eliminated because they are barriers to U.S. exports,
a former Agriculture Department official said during his
confirmation hearing for the post of top U.S. negotiator on farm
trade.
   ``The monopolies must go,'' Daniel G. Amstutz, a former
undersecretary of agriculture, told the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee Friday. ``They are barriers to trade just as sure as
import quotas are.''
   He said the U.S. government is insisting on elimination of
Japanese quotas on beef imports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court denied a request by
Eastern Airlines to block a set of sanctions levied against the
Miami-based carrier for its attempt to sell its East Coast air
shuttle.
   The ruling Friday by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals means
Eastern will at least temporarily have to halt its efforts to sell
the shuttle while it wages a legal battle with its largest labor
union.
   The appeals court also set a May 6 date for arguments on whether
the judges should dismiss a contempt ruling against Eastern that
was issued in the same case.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrival of spring has brought signs of
recovery to the toy industry following 1987's dismal performance.
Stores are selling more toys and manufacturers are getting more
orders.
   But toymakers know the fickle tastes of young customers can take
a promising product and overnight turn it into a dud. So there is
an air of caution in this highly volatile business, although the
early trend is positive.
   ``It's a very good retail environment for the first time in
several years,'' Paul Valentine, an analyst with Standard & Poor's
Corp., said.
</TEXT>
