<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against major foreign currencies
in European trading early today after closing at its lowest level
in three months in Tokyo. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said the Bank of Japan intervened to
prop up the American currency but not enough to halt the dollar's
slide in Europe.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell for the third consecutive trading day, dropping
1.31 yen to a closing 124.43 yen. The dollar now has fallen 2.72
yen in three trading days in Tokyo to its lowest level since Jan. 4.
   In later London trading today the dollar was quoted at 124.38
yen.
   The Bank of Japan intervened shortly after the start of trading
to prop up the dollar at 124.40 yen to 124.45 yen, traders said.
One of the central bank's currency dealers, Taeko Kobayashi, said
the bank bought between $100 million and $200 million.
   Traders in Frankfurt said the amount of the Bank of Japan's
intervention was apparently insufficient to withstand the selling
pressure from market operators testng the dollar's bottom level.
   They said the approaching Easter holiday is slowing activity in
trading rooms where a number of traders already have left on
vacation.
   In London, the dollar dropped almost two cents against the
British pound. One pound cost $1.8530 today, more expensive for
buyers than late Friday's $1.8360.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.6660 West German marks, down from 1.6760; 1.3768
Swiss francs, down from 1.3865; 5.6525 French francs, down from
5.6860; 1.8732 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8820; 1,234,75 Italian
lire, down from 1,241.00; and 1.2425 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2433.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $453.80 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $451.70. Amid quiet trading at
midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $453.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $453.20, up from $451.50 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 59 cents from Saturday's close
to a bid $454.67.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.63 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $6.64.
</TEXT>
