<HEAD>Dollar Falls Again In Japan; Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell today for the third consecutive
trading day in Tokyo, closing at its lowest level in almost three
months, while stock prices recovered from sharp losses over the
weekend.
   The dollar closed at 124.43 yen, down 1.31 yen from Friday's
finish of 125.74 yen, after opening the day's session at 124.60.
The currency ranged between 124.30 yen and 124.63 yen.
   The dollar now has fallen 2.72 yen in three trading days. Its
close today was its lowest since 121.65 on Jan. 4.
   ``Japan is taking the cue from trends overseas like New York,''
said Taeko Kobayashi, a currency dealer with the Bank of Japan.
``Japanese fundamentals are changing and that explains a weaker
dollar here.''
   The Bank of Japan intervened shortly after the start of today's
trading to prop up the dollar at a level of around 124.40-124.45
yen, traders said.
   While the move failed to prevent a further decline, it did help
to steady the dollar. Ms. Kobayashi said the central bank bought
$100 million to $200 dollars.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which shed a hefty 305.99 points in Saturday's
half day of trading, recovered most of its losses, rising 301.99
points, or 1.19 percent, ending the day at 25,622.71.
   Traders said the market was active as investors were preparing
for the new fiscal year.
   Large issues such as steel and shipbuilding, as well as pulp and
paper, were traded actively in the first section, where the overall
volume was estimated at 1.1 million shares.
</TEXT>
