<HEAD>London Stocks Steady After Sharp Drop</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates throughout with shares steadying.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices steadied in light trading on the London
Stock Exchange by midday Monday after dropping sharply during the
morning session.
   Several traders said they were encouraged by the slight recovery
from the market's morning lows. But they also were waiting for the
New York market's next move.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 selected stocks
was down 15.1 points, or 0.9 percent, to 1,752.8 at midday. During
the morning, it was down 19.5 points.
   Volume stood at 212.6 million shares at midday, down from 221.6
million shares at about the same time Friday.
   Traders said activity again appeared to be limited to
market-makers.
   ``Most of the fund managers are busy writing reports'' ahead of
the end of the first quarter, commented one trader.
   ``I can't see anyone wanting to do much before the Easter
holidays.''
   The market ignored the 301.99 point gain made Monday in Tokyo's
Nikkei stock index and instead focused on the possibility of
another bearish run on Wall Street. On Friday, the Dow Jones
Industrial Average fell 44.92 to 1,978.95, its second 40-plus point
loss in two days.
</TEXT>
