<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 0945EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-StockFutures-Limits     03-28 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Futures-Limits,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CFTC Approves Moving Limits On S&P 500 Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange, seeking to
subdue wild price swings on the nation's financial markets, has
adopted an unusual method for limiting daily price moves on its
Standard & Poor's 500 stock-index futures.
   The exchange said the adjustable limits will take effect today,
replacing the 30-point limit the Merc adopted for the contract
after the Oct. 19 stock market collapse.
   The new limits, approved Thursday by the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission, will range from 15 index points to 25 points.
This will depend on the settlement price of the lead-month S&P 500
futures contract on the last business day of the preceding month.
   Investors use stock-index futures to hedge against losses in the
stock market.
   S&P 500 futures account for more than 80 percent of all U.S.
stock-index futures trades.
   Merc officials have said the limits will result in better
coordination of U.S. financial markets, a key recommendation of the
presidential commission that investigated the stock market collapse.
   A one-point move in the S&P 500 index is roughly equivalent to
an eight-point move in the Dow Jones industrial average. Some
analysts had criticized the 30-point limit on S&P 500 futures _
equivalent to about 240 points on the Dow _ as being too high to
curtail all but the most violent price swings.
   A 15-point limit will take effect today because the June
contract settled February 29 at 268.75 points, within the low-end
range of 0 to 275 points.
   The limit would increase to 20 points if the June contract
settled above 275 points on the last trading day of March, or to 25
points if the June contract settled above 325 points.
</TEXT>
