<2ND_LINE>BC-Pennies, Adv 02-03,0888</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 2-3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pennies Make Cents In Greeneville</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEANNE WAXMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry McDowell makes a whole lot of
cents.
   McDowell heads the plant where most of the nation's pennies are
produced, though the U.S. Mint finishes the job by stamping shiny
blanks with their slogans and Abraham Lincoln's profile.
   McDowell knows just about all there is to know about the
nation's 1-cent piece. He's learned most of it since 1981, when the
U.S. Treasury Department gave up penny production and assigned the
task to Ball Corp.'s Zinc Products Division in Greeneville.
   Pennies used to be made almost entirely of copper, but
skyrocketing prices for the metal sent the federal government in
search of cheaper materials and lower operating costs in the
private sector.
   McDowell and other Ball officials convinced the Mint they could
do the job in Greeneville, and the nation's copper-plated penny
over a zinc base was born.
   ``They very quietly introduced this thing and nobody much knew
there was a change,'' McDowell said. ``There was one helluva a lot
of testing before they switched over.''
   The old pennies were 95 percent copper and 5 percent zinc. The
new pennies are 97.5 percent zinc and 2.5 percent copper, he said.
   The Mint first wanted to go to all-aluminum, but aluminum was
very light and trouble was anticipated with vending machines.
Federal officials then thought about an all-zinc penny, but zinc is
silvery like other coins and tarnishes quickly, McDowell said.
   ``Ball came up with the idea to plate zinc with copper,'' he
said.
   The phase-in from old penny to new took a year, he said, with
the 42-acre plant shipping new pennies in 1982 for the first time.
   About 70 percent of the nation's pennies are made in
Greeneville, or about 8.5 billion blanks under the government's
$18.2 million contract with Ball for 1988. A much smaller operation
in La Salle, Ill., also makes penny blanks under a small business
set-aside program with the government.
   Ball Corp. reported net income in 1987 of $66.3 million on sales
of just over $1 billion, said Tom Jenkins, an accountant in Ball's
Muncie, Ind. headquarters. That compared with income of $58.9
million on a similar sales total in 1986.
   The government ships zinc and copper to Greeneville and the zinc
is melted down, cast at a rate of 35,000 pounds an hour and rolled
into thin sheets, coiled 13,000 pounds at a time, then pressed into
penny shapes and rimmed before copper is added during a series of
electroplate and cleansing rinses.
   The process takes about two hours, and the longest time spent is
electroplating, McDowell said. Each blank penny weighs about 2.5
grams, and 181 pennies weigh a pound as opposed to 145 pennies a
pound of the old, mostly copper cents.
   ``Zinc is less dense than copper,'' McDowell said.
   The pennies are turned from a sleek silver to a shiny copper
color during their electroplating baths. After they're dried and an
anti-tarnish material is added, the blanks are checked for quality
before they're shipped to Mints in 3,300-pound wooden crates lined
with plastic.
   ``When they're new, they want them to look new,'' McDowell said.
   A federal law prohibits the government from spending any more on
making a coin than the face value of the coin, which means pennies
must be made with all costs included for less than a cent each.
   When copper prices went as high as $1 a pound in the early
1970s, the government was spending a full cent per penny to
manufacture the coins itself. In the late 1970s, copper cost as
much as $1.45 per pound. Ball is now making pennies, and they're
finished off by the Mint, at a total cost of sixth-tenths of a
cent, McDowell said.
   The Mint coins the pennies in Philadelphia and Denver after
they're shipped from Greeneville by rail and truck.
   Ball cranked out about 12 billion penny blanks in 1982, the
first year of full production, because the government feared there
would be a penny shortage when the word got out copper was no
longer going to be the primary material.
   The government ordered so many pennies that year and in 1983
because officials were jittery after people took silver coins out
of circulation in droves around 1965, when the mint stopped using
silver for dimes, quarters and half-dollars.
   No similar penny shortage occurred, however, and the government
later cut back production in Greeneville so the inventory that had
built up could be depleted, McDowell said. Penny production has
been steady since 1987.
   The Greeneville plant employs about 300 people, with the
facility also manufacturing casings for batteries and other
zinc-based products.
   The Mint still makes all other coins itself and likely will
continue to do so, McDowell said.
   Security is not extraordinary at the Ball plant since the
pennies are shipped as blanks, he said. Besides, vending machines
don't take pennies anyway so criminals aren't much interested,
McDowell said.
   ``How are you gonna peddle them?'' he said. ``They're blank.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 2-3</NOTE>
