<HEAD>Soybean Futures Open Higher; Grains Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures opened slightly higher while
grains opened steady to lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean prices advanced on the government's offer to donate
soybean oil to Pakistan, and also on news that a drought in the Rio
Grande du Sul region of Brazil had prompted the government there to
declare a state of emergency, analysts said.
   Some rain fell over the weekend in Brazil after the declaration
was issued, however, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with G.H. Miller
& Co.
   Farmer sales of corn over the weekend put pressure on corn
futures prices; wheat opened slightly lower on expectations of a
pickup this week in the amounts of surplus wheat sold at government
auctions, Gidel said.
   But wheat futures were trading slightly higher about a half-hour
into the session.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.06\ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to } cent lower with May at $2.09} a bushel; oats were { cent lower
to \ cent higher with May at $1.69 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents
to 3\ cents higher with May at $6.51\ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .28 cent higher with April at 75.20
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .35 cent higher
with March at 82.80 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .57 cent
lower with April at 45.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.27 cent to .72 cent lower with May at 56.65 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Friday.
