<2ND_LINE>PM-American Stores,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Stores Launches Tender Offer For Lucky Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. today launched its
$1.74 billion tender offer for Lucky Stores Inc., a $45-a-share bid
that would create the nation's largest grocery store chain if
successful.
   ``That is correct,'' said American Stores Vice President Michael
Holt, confirming that the offer to Lucky stockholders began this
morning. He refused to comment further.
   Lucky, the country's sixth-largest supermarket chain, boasts
annual sales of about $7 billion, with 480 stores in the West,
Midwest and Southwest, mostly in California and Arizona. American
Stores, with annual sales of $15 billion, has about 1,700 retail
outlets in 40 states, making it the nation's third-largest grocery
retailer.
   Lucky officials at the company's Dublin, Calif., headquarters
referred calls to New York spokeswoman Lissa Perlman. She confirmed
the tender offer had begun, saying Lucky officials have been
reviewing the offer with financial and legal advisers.
   ``Lucky strongly advises its stockholders not to take any action
with respect to the American Stores offer'' until the Lucky board
of directors has a chance to further study the bid and make its
recommendation, Ms. Perlman said.
   No deadline for a recommendation was given.
   Wall Street reacted to news of the bid by sending Lucky Store's
stock up 87{ cents per share to $48.62{ per share at midday on the
New York Stock Exchange. American Stores down $1.87{ per share, at
$54.75 per share.
   American Stores Chairman L.S. Skaggs notified Lucky Stores
Chairman John M. Lillie of the then impending tender offer in a
March 21 letter. Skaggs said if the offer was successful, he
planned to combine American Store's Alpha Beta stores with Lucky's
operation under the Lucky name.
   The letter praised Lucky's management and marketing strategies
and invited Lucky executives to stay on if the deal is completed.
Lucky's headquarters would remain in Dublin, Skaggs said.
   The bid for Lucky comes 16 months after a takeover specialist
Asher Edleman dropped his hostile effort to acquire the company. In
return, Lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal bills.
   Lucky kept Edleman at bay partially by selling off non-grocery
divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures.
   After the text of the letter was released last week, Lucky
officials had no comment on the American Stores' tender offer
except to say company bylaws contain a ``poison pill''
anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any
shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
   American Stores last made financial headlines in 1984 when it
spent $1.1 billion to take over Jewel Companies Inc., a
Chicago-based grocery, drug and convenience store chain.
   That acquisition expanded American Stores' operations from just
over 1,000 retail outlets to its present 1,700. The company has
three divisions _ Skaggs, which operates supermarkets in the
western United States; American Superstores, which runs outlets in
the Midwest and East, and Osco Drug Stores, which has stores
nationwide.
   The company operates stores under the names Acme, Jewel, Star,
Buttrey, Skaggs, Skaggs Alpha Beta, and Osco Drug.
</TEXT>
