<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scotus-Superfund     03-28 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Superfund,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Hear Appeal in New Jersey Hazardous-Waste Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear an
appeal by companies seeking refunds of New Jersey taxes they paid
to help clean up hazardous waste.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that could limit
the amount of the refunds.
   The New Jersey Supreme Court ruled in December that the
businesses are entitled to only a partial refund if the state
Legislature does not appropriate enough money to reimburse them
fully.
   The case stems from a dispute over New Jersey's so-called Spill
Fund and whether it was preempted by the federal Superfund law.
   The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1986, in an earlier review of
the New Jersey case, that the Superfund preempted _ at least
partially _ state efforts to deal with hazardous waste pollution
through taxation.
   The high court said states only may tax the same companies
subject to the Superfund law for purposes not covered by the
federal act.
   Congress then removed the preemption feature from the Superfund
law to eliminate the potential obstacle to state clean-up programs.
   At issue in the case acted on today is the size of the refund
the companies are entitled to recover for the period before the
preemption feature was eliminated.
   The New Jersey Supreme Court interpreted the 1986 U.S. Supreme
Court rulig to allow the state to retain part of the taxes the
companies paid for clean-up costs.
   The state court said that if the New Jersey Legislature failed
by June to reimburse the Spill Fund for the full amount of
preempted expenditures, the businesses are entitled only to a
partial refund.
   The Spill Fund was created in 1977, supported by tax revenues
that average about $10 million a year.
   The $1.6 billion federal Superfund was created in 1980 and
renewed in 1986.
   Seeking the refunds are Exxon Corp., B.F. Goodrich, Union
Carbide, Monsanto and Tenneco.
   They said the New Jersey court ruling would permit the state
illegally to retain millions of dollars in tax revenue.
   The case is In Re Exxon Corp., 87-1296.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2341EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv29   03-28 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 29,0741</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday March 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Advice on Getting and Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are few disputes more vociferous than
those on how Uncle Sam, along with his nieces and nephews in
smaller governmental entities, earn their income and spend their
money.
   Every taxpayer has an opinion. Every business, too. Tax reform
and watchdog groups exist in most municipalities. Presidential
candidates can't steer clear of the subject. Congress tinkers with
it every year.
   Academics write books about taxing and spending. Institutions
exist for the specific purpose of studying every detail of every
proposal. Pressure groups and lobbyists are in a constant uproar
about their favorite projects.
   Here's a sampling:
   The poor are being nickeled and dimed to death by state sales
taxes, says Citizens for Tax Justice. Sales taxes are regressive,
says the public interest organization's director, Robert S.
McIntyre.
   As a share of income, he states, sales and excise taxes take
five times as much from poor families _ and three times more out of
middle-income families _ as they take from the rich.
   ``Taxing the poor heavily is both curel and inefficient,'' he
says. ``It doesn't produce much in the way of revenues, because the
poor don't make very much money.''
   Progressive taxes, based on the ability to pay, are the answer,
he says. He suggests a sales-tax rebate plan to mitigate some of
the regressivity of such taxes, which some states impose even on
food, gasoline and utilities.
   The Center for the Study of Economics in Columbia, Md., pushes
what it calls incentive taxes as a way to generate revenue, while
simultaneously improving the economic base of a municipality.
   It's not a new idea, having been proposed many years ago by
economist Henry George. In fact, some municipalities have accepted
the notion, but not enough of them according to the center, which
proselytizes with missionary zeal.
   One of its tenets is that the value of land was created by
society and government. Nevertheless, taxes on undeveloped land are
almost always far below land on which an investor has placed a
building.
   In short, downtown parking lots pay low taxes and contribue
minimally to the area's economy in terms of jobs, payrolls and
products. But lots with structures on them and job-producing
businesses in them are taxed more heavily.
   They ask if the opposite policy wouldn't be more productive?
Shouldn't that parking lot be forced to develop itself into a more
economically productive role? How better to do it than by taxing it
into compliance?
   No discussion of spending and taxing could be so boisterous as
to drown out J. Peter Grace, who headed the President's Private
Sector Survey on Cost Control, said by the White House to have
saved $40.5 billion in fiscal 1988.
   Now head of Citizens Against Government Waste, Grace is
currently circulating his notions of how Uncle Sam can reduce the
budget deficit by $60 billion a year.
   He claims, for instance, that $6 billion could be saved in three
years by establishing a bipartisan commission to recommend an
extensive program of military base closings.
   An additional $1 billion could be saved over three years, he
says, by imposing user fees for non-emergency Coast Guard Services,
such as getting a tow if your outboard runs out of fuel.
   Earlier this month, the President's Management Report said
recommendations by the Private Sector Survey led to savings of
$30.6 billion in fiscal 1986 and $38.9 billion in fiscal '87, for a
three-year total of $110 billion.
   ``They still haven't gone far enough,'' said Grace in handing
Congress his new proposals.
   Never at a loss for money-saving ideas is the Heritage
Foundation. This year, as in years before, it is suggesting that
big savings are possible by ``privatization'' _ turning various
functions over to the private sector.
   This can be accomplished, it says, by selling off assets such as
the federal loan portfolio and the Naval Petroleum Reserve; by
contracting out services that it now tries to handle by itself; and
by further deregulation.
   If Heritage had its way, public housing would be privatized, a
private air traffic control system would be developed, and Amtrak,
the passenger rail service, would be sold to private operators.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues March 29</NOTE>
