<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ForbesBiggest     03-28 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forbes Biggest,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Leads Forbes List Of Most Valuable Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. leads
Forbes magazine's list of the nation's most valuable companies for
a fourth consecutive year, the magazine said Monday.
   IBM's stock market value at the end of 1987 was $69.0 billion, a
decline of 5.2 percent from a year earlier. That was still enough
to surpass Exxon Corp., whose stock market value rose 4.5 percent
to $52.6 billion.
   IBM, the world's largest computer company, has led the Forbes
list since 1984, when American Telephone & Telegraph Co. fell off
the top of the heap because of the breakup of the Bell System.
   Among the big movers in the top 10, Merck & Co. Inc., the
Rahway, N.J.-based pharmaceutical company, climbed to sixth from
ninth. Ford Motor Co. ascended to ninth from 15th, while General
Motors Corp. fell to eighth from fifth.
   Stock market value is determined by multiplying the price of a
company's stock by the number of its shares.
   Here are the top 10 companies in Forbes' market value list,
which will appear in the ``Forbes 500s'' issue of April 25.
   1. International Business Machines Corp., $69.0 billion, down
5.2 percent.
   2. Exxon Corp., $52.6 billion, up 4.5 percent.
   3. General Electric Co., $39.8 billion, up 1.6 percent.
   4. American Telephone & Telegraph Co., $29.0 billion, up 8.2
percent.
   5. Du Pont Co., $20.9 billion, up 3.5 percent.
   6. Merck & Co. Inc., $20.8 billion, up 23.2 percent.
   7. Philip Morris Cos. Inc., $20.2 billion, up 18.2 percent.
   8. General Motors Corp., $19.1 billion, down 9.0 percent.
   9. Ford Motor Co., $18.6 billion, up 26.6 percent.
   10. Amoco Corp., $17.8 billion, up 6.5 percent.
</TEXT>
