<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TravelAgents     03-28 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Travel Agents,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Required Bonding For Travel Agents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COCONUT CREEK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flood of travel scams has pushed
two Florida legislators to propose a law that would require bonding
for travel agents, a plan that gained the support Monday of state
Attorney General Bob Butterworth.
   Travel agents would be required to register with the state and
post bond ranging from $10,000 to $25,000, unless they already are
bonded by Airline Recording Corp., under the proposed measure.
   Butterworth endorsed the bill at a news conference at the
Coconut Creek Government Center.
   ``When bogus holidays are offered by deceptive telephone
promotions, the reputation of Florida as an ideal vacation destiny
is damaged,'' he said.
   His office launched a major investigation of travel scams last
June with raids on eight offices. Complaints naming more than 200
other travel companies are under investigation.
   ``Fraudulent travel providers who fast talk customers in
telephone promotions are being brought to justice,'' Butterworth
said.
   Although the bill would add regulation, it has picked up
industry support.
   ``The professional is concerned to make sure the traveling
public does not get bilked, and I think the professional also is
concerned he doesn't want the reputation of the industry impugned
by scam operators,'' Harold Berns, a member of the board of
directors of the American Society of Travel Agents, said Monday.
   ``The professional travel agent is more than happy to see this
happen,'' said Berns, owner of Air and Sea Travel in Fort
Lauderdale. ``We've heard too many horror stories. Not only here,
but all over the country.''
   Tobin and Weinstein charged tour operators who take money from
unsuspecting consumers for trips they will never deliver are a
growing problem.
   A 1985 state law made the fraudulent sale of travel a
misdemeanor. But victims have no way of recovering their money
without bonding, Weinstein said.
   Opposing the bill would ``be like being against apple pie,''
said Berns.
   Most of Florida's 2,200 legitimate travel agents already meet
the bill's requirements by registering with Airline Recording
Corp., which requires bonds of up to $50,000 bond.
   Virtually all travel agents who sell airline tickets must
register with the corporation, Berns said.
   Agents already associated with such a recording association
would not be required to register under the bill, Weinstein said.
But agents already bonded may voluntarily register with the state.
   Failure to obtaing a bond would be a misdemeanor, and the state
Division of Consumer Services would have the power to shut down
unbonded agencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1510EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FishFigures     03-28 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish Figures,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Region's Fish Harvest Down But Value Soars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New England fishermen returned to port last year
with 12 million fewer pounds of fish and shellfish than in 1986 but
the value of the catch soared 14 percent to $512.6 million,
according to figures compiled by a federal agency.
   Massachusetts led the five states in the region with fishing
industries both in total harvest and value, followed by Maine and
Rhode Island. New Hampshire led Connecticut in terms of harvest
weight, but Connecticut's catch was worth more.
   Gloucester fishermen caught the most fish and shellfish but the
value of the catch was substantially below that of New Bedford
fishermen, whose lucrative harvest of pricey sea scallops made that
port first in the nation in terms of catch value for the second
consecutive year.
   The region's 1987 lobster harvest was virtually identical to the
previous year, 19.8 million pounds compared to 19.7 million pounds
in 1986, but the value of that harvest jumped from $46.2 million to
$54.6 million.
   The preliminary harvest figures were compiled by the Northeast
Fisheries Center, a division of the Commerce Department's National
Marine Fisheries Service. The center compiles the data for an
annual report on the fishing industry nationwide that the Commerce
Department is expected to release in April.
   Commercial fishermen throughout the region caught 543.7 million
pounds of fish and shellfish in 1987, down from the 1986 total of
555.7 million pounds. But because of increased overall fish prices,
the catch value increased from $448.9 million to $512.6 million.
   Massachusetts fisherman harvested 256.8 pounds of fish and
shellfish in 1987, down from 271.3 million pounds a year earlier.
But the value of the Bay State catch jumped 14.4 percent from
$243.6 million in 1986 to $278.9 million last year.
   The Maine catch of 169 million pounds was up slightly from 168.2
million pounds in 1986, but the value of the harvest increased 22
percent from $108.4 million to $132.4 million.
   Rhode Island's catch also remained relatively stable, 100
million pounds in 1987 compared to 101.6 million pounds in 1986,
with the value of that state's catch increasing 3 percent from
$75.1 million to $77.5 million.
   New Hampshire fishermen caught 9.3 million pounds of fish and
shellfish last year, up from 7.9 million pounds in 1986. The value
of the harvest increased nearly 26 percent, from $6.2 million to
$7.8 million.
   Connecticut had the smallest regional harvest in terms of
weight, 8.6 million pounds, but it was worth $16 million, an
increase of 2.5 percent from $15.6 million in 1986, when that
state's total catch was 6.7 million pounds.
   In terms of weight, Gloucester led the region's major fishing
ports with a catch of 92.6 million pounds, followed by New Bedford,
Point Judith in Narragansett, R.I., Portland, Me., Rockland, Me.,
Boston and Newport, R.I.
   New Bedford fishermen harvested about half of the 18.2 million
pounds of sea scallops caught in New England in 1987, according to
fisheries center spokesman Ron L. Schultz.
   The average price of $4.42 a pound paid to fishermen for sea
scallops was by far the highest of the 14 major species of fish and
shellfish harvested in New England waters. The average price paid
to fishermen for lobster was $2.91 a pound.
   The price paid to Gloucester fishermen falls far below that paid
to their New Bedford counterparts because two of the major species
harvested by Gloucester fishermen, pollock and Atlantic herring,
net per-pound prices among the lowest of the 14 species.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
