<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Close Sharply Higher; Grains Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade while most grain futures
retreated.
   Soybeans were supported by news that a drought in the Brazilian
soybean-growing region of Rio Grande du Sul had prompted the
government there to declare a state of emergency on Friday,
analysts said.
   But traders were divided over the extent of damage to the nearly
ripe soybean crop, especially after weekend rains were reported in
the area.
   Nevertheless, most soybean contracts closed at new lifetime high
prices on a combination of fundamental and technical factors with
most players feeling bullish ahead of Thursday's Agriculture
Department reports on spring planting intentions and grain stocks,
analysts said.
   ``Right now, everything seems to be go in this market,'' said
Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New
York.
   Wheat posted substantial losses due to rainy weather in the
Midwest, which was seen as helping out the new crop, said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst in Chicago with G.H. Miller & Co.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 5{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $2.99{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
lower to } cent higher with May at $2.10{ a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 2\ cents lower with May at $1.66{ a bushel; soybeans were 4
cents to 10\ cents higher with May at $6.55{ a bushel.
