<2ND_LINE>AM-Furrs-Safeway,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Approves Furr's Purchase of 59 Stores in Safeway's El Paso
Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission on Monday
approved Furr's Inc.'s purchase of Safeway's 59-store El Paso
division.
   However, Furr's must hold the stores separately pending the
final sale of 12 Safeways in New Mexico and Texas to Jaynes Group
Inc., according to the FTC.
   The Jaynes Group is a newly formed corporation organized by
former Safeway employees. Both it and Lubbock-based Furr's are
privately held and did not disclose the amount of the transactions.
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. of New York acquired Safeway in
1986 in a $4.3 billion leveraged buyout to fend off a hostile
takeover by the Dart Group of Maryland. It has been selling off
whole divisions to pay off its debt.
   During the four-month FTC review period, Furr's operated the 59
stores as an autonomous division.
   Furr's now operates 154 retail grocery stores in Texas and New
Mexico. It also operates two distribution centers and several
support offices.
   The FTC's only objection to Furr's purchase of Safeway's El Paso
division was that it would have a monopoly in 12 New Mexico and
Texas cities.
   Furr's reached an agreement with the Jayne's Group to buy the
stores, which are in the Texas cities of Pecos and Fort Stockton
and the New Mexico cities of Alamogordo, Artesia, Clovis, Espanola,
Hobbs, Las Vegas, Lovington, Portales, Roswell and Silver City.
</TEXT>
