<1ST_LINE>r f AM-IrvingBid     03-28 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irving Bid,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Adopts New Anti-Takeover Provision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp., which is resisting a $1.08
billion takeover offer from another banking company, said Monday it
took additional steps to discourage hostile bidders from acquiring
its stock.
   Irving said its board of directors approved an amendment to its
share purchase rights plan that would deal with the possibility of
a ``street sweep'' under which a bidder who terminates a tender
offer then begins buying the target company's begins on the open
market or in privately negotiated deals.
   Irving said the provision was adopted to assure that a street
sweep would not jeopardize Irving's efforts to explore alternatives
that would maximize values for its shareholders.
   Bank of New York Co. launched a $60-a-share offer of cash and
securities last week for each of Irving's 18.1 million common
shares outstanding.
   Irving has called the offer inadequate, and indicated last week
that it was seeking a friendly bidder and exploring other
alternatives to thwart the hostile offer.
   The scrap has attracted an unusual level of attention because
hostile takeover efforts are rare in the banking business.
   A spokesman for Bank of New York, Owen Brady, said his company
thought the latest provision adopted by the Irving board was
illegal and said it was investigating what to do about it.
   Separately, Bank of New York disclosed that its chairman, J.
Carter Bacot, asked Joseph Rice, Irving's chairman, in a letter to
make sure that Bank of New York gets a chance to look at any of the
confidential financial information that Irving has been sharing
with other potential friendly bidders.
   Under the new move by Irving, the company's previously adopted
share purchase rights plan would be activated if a party who made a
tender or exchange offer subsequently bought enough non-tendered
Irving stock to push its total Irving stake to 5 percent or more.
   If that occurred, each right would entitle its holder to
purchase Irving stock with a market value double the right's
exercise price.
   Bank of New York's tender offer currently is scheduled to expire
April 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1804EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     03-28 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 0.3 Percent in Week Ended March 26</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 1.996 million tons in
the week ended March 26, an increase of 0.3 percent from the
previous week's 1.991 million tons, the American Iron and Steel
Institute reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 93.0 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 92.7 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
23.725 million net tons, an increase of 33.2 percent from the
17.805 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations
of USX Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down
by a strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 89.9 percent of capacity,
compared with 68.0 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended March 26: Northeast
Coast, 291,000; Pittsburgh, 204,000; Youngstown, 124,000; Lake
Erie, 163,000; Detroit, 174,000; Chicago, 535,000; Midwest,
177,000; Southern, 225,000; and Western, 103,000.
</TEXT>
