<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1901EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pennsylvania-Koppers 1stLd-Writethru   03-28 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pennsylvania-Koppers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Takeover Legislation Promised</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 4th graf with Sen. Specter's announcement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. John Heinz Monday said he will
introduce legislation to thwart a hostile takeover of Koppers Co.
by British business magnate Brian Beazer and the Wall Street
investment bank Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The Pennsylvania Republican charged again at a news conference
that if a $1.7 billion tender offer from BNS Inc. succeeded, Beazer
will gain a monopoly in the various local markets for aggregates,
road building materials that include the sand and pebbles added to
concrete to make cement.
   ``One of the reasons it's attractive to have a stranglehold on
the existing aggregates business is that environmental laws are
such at the state and local level that you cannot easily open ... a
new source of aggregate,'' he said. ``So in effect it is a sellers'
market for a very very long time.''
   U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said Monday he asked Attorney
General Edwin Meese to personally review the Koppers case and to
respond to the request by Thursday.
   Heinz withheld details of the proposed legislation.
   ``To reveal our stragegy might very well be to jeopardize its
success,'' he said.
   The proposal will be offered this week or after the Easter break
in Congress as an amendment to pending legislation, Heinz said. The
proposed law is unlike an amendment sponsored by U.S. Rep. John
Bryant, D-Texas, to require foreign investors to disclose details
of takeover attempts.
   ``I'm not in the business of making hollow promises, and I do
not make idle threats,'' Heinz said. ``I have drafted and am
prepared to introduce and press legislation to make the takeover of
Koppers extremely unpalatable to Beazer-Shearson and similar
consortiums in the future.
   ``The corporate raiders will be and should be as surprised by
this legislation as Koppers was by this raid.''
   ``We are not corporate raiders,'' Beazer declared in a full-page
advertisement Monday in Pittsburgh's newspapers. ``Our goal is not
to make a quick buck. Rather, we are in the process of creating a
vital, dynamic worldwide organization.''
   Beazer's ad appealed to Koppers' worried employees and to the
city to investigate the fate of the Atlanta homebuilder Cohn
Communities and the Dallas construction materials company
Gifford-Hill after he acquired them in 1985 and 1986 respectively.
   ``Each of those companies has grown and prospered under our
ownership,'' he said.
   Koppers has rejected each of the offers, $45, $56 and $60 per
share, that BNS has made since launching its cash tender offer
March 3. The latest expires April 7, although a federal court in
California has blocked the acquisition over anti-trust concerns.
   Koppers management says it may sell all or part of the company
or pay cash to shareholders to keep the company out of Beazer's
hands.
   Heinz said taxpayers would spend more for public roads if the
takeover succeeds. The combination would heighten Beazer's
concentration in markets where his holdings and Koppers compete.
   ``The two of them combined in what are essentially local market
areas would, if the sale went through, amount to a de facto local
monopoly on very costly road building materials,'' he said.
   The senator, Allegheny County Commission Chairman Thomas
Foerster and others at the news conference warned that the takeover
jeopardizes the approximately 1,100 Pittsburgh-area jobs in
Koppers' chemicals businesses.
   Beazer has said he would sell chemicals and related businesses,
although it is not clear that all those jobs would be eliminated.
   Opponents also worry about the $232 million that Koppers
contributes to the area economy.
   Heinz joined city, county and state officials who have lambasted
Shearson for going a step beyond traditional takeover financing and
becoming an equity partner in the takeover company, BNS.
   ``I am appalled by the involvement of Shearson,'' he said.
``Shearson stands to gain tens of millions of dollars in fees
simply for shuffling some paper around.''
   Shearson officials have said their ownership in BNS is merely a
temporary method of helping finance the takeover.
</TEXT>
