<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Hit New Contract Highs On South American Crop
Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The possibility of severe drought damage to Brazilian soybean
crops helped propel U.S. soybean futures prices above $6.50 a
bushel Monday to their highest levels since mid-1984.
   Grain futures retreated in other trading on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   On other exchanges, copper futures fell sharply while precious
metals were mixed; energy futures advanced; livestock and meat
futures were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   News that a month-long dry spell in the Brazilian
soybean-growing region of Rio Grande du Sul had prompted the
government there to declare a state of emergency on Friday gave
U.S. soybean futures a healthy boost, analysts said.
   But traders were divided over the extent of damage to the nearly
ripe Brazilian crop, especially after light weekend rains were
reported in the Rio Grande du Sul area.
   Nevertheless, most soybean contracts closed at new lifetime high
prices on a combination of fundamental and technical factors with
most players feeling bullish ahead of Thursday's Agriculture
Department reports on spring planting intentions and grain stocks,
analysts said.
   ``Right now, everything seems to be go in this market,'' said
Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New
York.
   Wheat posted significant losses due to rainy weather in the
Midwest, which was seen as helping out the new crop, said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst in Chicago with G.H. Miller & Co.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 5{ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $2.99{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to } cent
higher with May at $2.10{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2\ cents
lower with May at $1.66} a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 9}
cents higher with May at $6.55} a bushel.
   Copper futures plummeted on New York's Commodity Exchange in
reaction to a rise in inventories of the metal at the warehouses of
the world's two largest copper exchanges.
   The Comex reported an increase in warehouse copper stocks of
1,425 short tons to 11,170 short tons. The London Metal Exchange
reported an increase of 425 metric tons to 56,725 metric tons.
   The closely watched March contract was the big loser, tumbling
6.15 cents to $1.076 a pound. Some of that activity was also due to
traders selling out of the March contract before it goes off the
board on Tuesday, said Bette Raptopoulos, metals analyst in New
York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Also on the Comex, gold futures advanced slightly and silver was
nearly unchanged in quiet trading.
   Gold settled $2.60 to $2.80 lower with April at $455.90 a troy
ounce; silver was unchanged to 0.5 cent lower with March at $6.665
a troy ounce.
   Energy futures advanced in slow, featureless trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 7 cents
higher with May at $17.10 a barrel; heating oil was .27 cent to .47
cent higher with April at 48.17 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .08 cent to .10 cent higher with April at 48.02 cents a gallon.
   The contracts for April and June delivery of live cattle posted
new highs on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Feeder cattle also
advanced while pork futures retreated.
   Higher cash markets underpinned the rise in cattle futures, said
Tom Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington
Heights, Ill.
   Pork-complex prices fell on expectations that the USDA's
quarterly hogs and pigs report will show an increase in the
nation's hog herd of 4 percent to 8 percent from a year ago, Morgan
said.
   Live cattle settled .30 cent to .55 cent higher with April at
75.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .73 cent higher
with March at 82.95 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .33 cent
lower with April at 46.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.20 cent to .92 cent lower with May at 56.45 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures advanced on the Chicago Merc, where the
contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500 index
settled 2.15 points higher at 259.90. The underlying spot index
finished .45 point lower at 258.06.
</TEXT>
