<1ST_LINE>r f AM-IPITalks     03-28 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IPI Talks,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IPI, Unions Meet Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of International Paper
Co. and its striking unions met Monday in an attempt to defuse the
hostility that has permeated negotiations during a yearlong
contract dispute and hindered chances of a settlement.
   Both sides declined to release information on what was discussed
or how long they met.
   ``We've agreed that any releases would be joint statements and
only where there's something to report,'' said William Meserve,
president of Local 14 of the United Paperworkers International
Union in Jay, Maine.
   He did say the two sides would meet again Tuesday, and the talks
are expected to last for weeks. IP has paper mills throughout the
country.
   Company spokesman William Greener echoed Meserve's statement,
saying from the company's Purchase, N.Y., headquarters that neither
side intended to release details of the meetings.
   IP and its unions, the UPIU and the International Brotherhood of
Firemen and Oilers, have been at odds for more than a year over
contracts that have come up for renewal. The disagreements focus on
whether local contracts should restore premium pay for Sunday and
holidays.
   Premium pay had been eliminated with labor's approval from past
contracts, but since the industry's fortunes have improved in the
last year, the unions have campaigned to revive the benefit.
   About 3,500 workers in four locations are embroiled in contract
fights. In Mobile, Ala., 1,200 workers have been locked out of
their jobs by the company. An additional 2,300 have struck plants
in Jay, Lock Haven, Pa., and DePere, Wis.
   Contracts are also open in Pine Bluff and Camden, Ark., and
Natchez, Miss.
   IP has continued to operate its mills with replacement workers.
The company claims the strike-breakers are now permanent employees
and has offered assistance to strikers who want to re-enter the job
market, including positions at other IP mills. The unions have
rejected such offers.
   International Paper Co. claimed earnings of $305 million in 1986
and said it expected to post earnings of $407 million when final
figures are released. However, the company said its profitablity
was below the industry average in both 1986 and 1987, when measured
in terms of its net worth.
</TEXT>
