<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-28 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0566</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fresh decline in the dollar and lingering
anxiety about Wall Street's own strength pushed stock prices mostly
lower Monday, but the market avoided the sharp falls of the
preceding two sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed a scant 0.82
higher at 1,979.77, after posting moderate declines through much of
the trading session.
   But the broader market moved downward. Declining issues outpaced
advances by more than 2-to-1 on the New York Stock Exchange, with
1,059 issues falling, 468 gaining and 420 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 142.82 million shares, down from
163.17 million in Friday's session.
   Many investors had their new-found confidence shaken late last
week when stocks fell sharply on Thursday and Friday. The closely
watched Dow Jones average tumbled around 45 points on Friday after
falling nearly 44 points in the previous session _ sparking
widespread fears that Monday's session could turn into another
``Black Monday'' akin to the collapse on Oct. 19.
   ``We've been almost rudely reminded that the market is still on
very, very thin ice,'' said Hugh Johnson, a senior vice president
of First Albany Corp. in Albany, N.Y. ``It's still volatile and
vulnerable.''
   But Monday's decline was tempered by some ``bargain-hunting''
buying at the lower price levels, traders said. They noted, though,
that many foreign investors and financial institutions remained on
the sidelines.
   Although the latest losses were more moderate, analysts said
they reflected a bearish sentiment that continued to pervade the
market. And the anxiety was deepened by fresh declines in the
battered dollar on world currency markets.
   ``We're again hooked to the dollar,'' said Monte Gordon,
director of research for Dreyfus Corp. ``The market continues to
wallow in confusion and uncertainty.''
   The U.S. currency was quoted at below 124 Japanese yen in late
trading in New York, down sharply from more than 125 yen late
Friday. The dollar also retreated to around 1.66 West German marks
from 1.68 marks.
   Earlier in the day, the dollar's slump brought the Federal
Reserve into the market to buy dollars in a bid to support the
currency after it fell to around 124 yen, traders reported.
   The financial markets have been ``reminded that stabilizing the
dollar is not going to be easy,'' First Albany's Johnson said.
   Among the most actively traded issues on the NYSE, Bankers Trust
was down \ at 31}, AT&T fell ] to 26}, Gillette dropped 1| to 45[,
Navistar lost \ at 6] and American Express was unchanged at 24{.
   Shares of Lucky Stores, the object of a $1.74 billion,
$45-a-share tender offer from American Stores, rose ~ to 48|. IBM
advanced 1[ to 108[, while General Electric gained { at 41.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 168.89 million shares.
   The NYSE's composite index was down 0.47 at 146.11.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials slipped 0.45 point to
299.08, and S&P's 500-stock composite index was also down 0.45, at
258.06.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 2.64
to 292.00. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 370.42, down 2.12.
</TEXT>
