<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LordGeller     03-28 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lord Geller,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Reserves Decision on Injunction in Advertising Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state court judge reserved a decision Monday
on a request that he prohibit six former top executives of Lord,
Geller, Federico, Einstein Inc. from soliciting business or
employees from Lord Geller for their new ad agency.
   Justice Herman Cahn asked attorneys for Lord Geller, which had
made the request for a preliminary injunction, and for the
defecting Lord Geller executives to work out a plan for introducing
evidence in the case.
   The six executives, led by Lord Geller founding partners Richard
Lord and Arthur Einstein Jr., walked off the job March 18, saying
they felt unduly constrained under the ownership of the British
firm, WPP Group PLC.
   WPP Group, which is headed by Martin Sorrell, had aquired Lord
Geller last summer when he bought its parent, JWT Group Inc., for
$566 million in the biggest ad agency acquisition ever. In addition
to Lord Geller, JWT Group owned the much larger advertising agency,
J. Walter Thompson Co.
   Since the six top partners left Lord Geller to form a new agency
called Lord, Einstein, O'Neill & Partners, about 30 other Lord
Geller employees have quit, some of them signing on with the new
agency.
   Two Lord Geller clients, WNBC-TV and New Yorker magazine, have
indicated they plan to take their business to the new agency.
   But most of the ad world's attention is focused International
Business Machines Corp., the computer giant which reportedly
accounts for about half of Lord Geller's $245 million in annual
billings.
</TEXT>
