<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WorldBank     03-28 0116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank,0120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Bank Appoints 17 New Agents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank, which borrows on world markets
for re-lending to poor countries, announced on Monday that it is
asking 14 U.S. companies outside New York and three in Toronto to
be agents for the sale of its longer-term bonds.
   Its object is to get a bigger variety of investors, the
announcement said.
   The 17 companies will be in addition to the five in the United
States which are now primary agents for what the bank calls its
Continuously Offered Longer-Term Securities (COLTS). These are
bonds with maturities of three to more than 30 years.
   It has $1.4 billion in such bonds outstanding.
</TEXT>
