<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LuckyStores 1stLd-Writethru   03-28 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lucky Stores, 1st Ld-Writethru,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Stores Launches Tender Offer For Lucky Stores</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 12 new grafs on American latest offer of $50 per
share and CLARIFIES references to size of companies. Picks up 11th
graf pvs ``The letter praised...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. said Monday it was
prepared to up its bid for Lucky Stores Inc. to more than $1.9
billion in an effort to create the nation's largest grocery store
chain.
   In a letter to the board of the Dublin, Calif.-based company,
American Stores chairman L.S. Skaggs said his company was ready to
offer $50 per share if a ``mutually acceptable agreement'' could be
worked out with Lucky Stores.
   Earlier Monday, American launched a cash tender offer for Lucky
at $45 per share, or a total of $1.74 billion. That offer expires
at midnight April 22.
   ``We made clear our willingness to negotiate concerning all
aspects of our offer, including the price,'' said Skaggs in his
letter to Lucky.
   Skaggs noted that Lucky Stores' representatives had so far
declined the invitation to negotiate.
   The combination of American, the nation's third largest grocery
retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion, and
Lucky, the sixth largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion,
could produce the biggest grocery retailer in the country, analysts
say.
   Lucky Stores officials were not immediately available for
comment on the latest developments, which were announced by press
release after the close of stock trading.
   Lucky shares advanced 87{ cents to close at $48.62{, while
American shares lost $1.75 to finish at $54.87{ on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Before American revealed the contents of its letter to the Lucky
Stores board, Lucky spokeswoman Lissa Perlman said company
officials had been reviewing the offer with financial and legal
advisers since last week.
   ``Lucky strongly advises its stockholders not to take any action
with respect to the American Stores offer'' until the Lucky board
of directors has a chance to further study the bid and make its
recommendation, Perlman said.
   No deadline for a recommendation was given.
   In a March 21 letter, Skaggs notified Lucky Stores Chairman John
M. Lillie of the then impending tender offer. Skaggs said if the
offer was successful, he planned to combine American Store's Alpha
Beta stores with Lucky's operation under the Lucky name.
   The letter praised Lucky's management and marketing strategies
and invited Lucky executives to stay on if the deal is completed.
Lucky's headquarters would remain in Dublin, Skaggs said.
   The bid for Lucky came 16 months after takeover specialist Asher
Edelman dropped his hostile effort to acquire the company. In
return, Lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal bills.
   Lucky kept Edelman at bay partially by selling off its
non-grocery divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures.
   After the text of the letter was released last week, Lucky
officials had no comment on the American Stores' tender offer
except to say company bylaws contain a ``poison pill''
anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any
shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
   American Stores last made financial headlines in 1984 when it
spent $1.1 billion to take over Jewel Companies Inc., a
Chicago-based grocery, drug and convenience store chain.
   That acquisition expanded American Stores' operations from just
over 1,000 retail outlets to its present 1,700. The company has
three divisions _ Skaggs, which operates supermarkets in the
western United States; American Superstores, which runs outlets in
the Midwest and East, and Osco Drug Stores, which has stores
nationwide.
   The company operates stores under the names Acme, Jewel, Star,
Buttrey, Skaggs, Skaggs Alpha Beta, and Osco Drug.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
