<FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Farmers-Batus 1stLd-Writethru   03-28 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus, 1st Ld-Writethru,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Batus Proxy Fight for Farmers May Violate Law, Regulator Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 4th graf pvs, ``The proposal ... $4.5
billion,'' with Reno court developments, PICKS UP 5th graf
original, ``The Kansas ... regulatory approval.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proxy solicitation by Batus Inc., which is
making a hostile bid for insurer Farmers Group Inc., may be illegal
and may have to be halted, the Kansas Insurance Department has said.
   The ruling was disclosed Monday by Los Angeles-based Farmers,
which has been resisting takeover overtures by Batus since January.
It was later confirmed by Batus, the American subsidiary of
London-based BAT Industries Inc. PLC.
   At issue is whether a proposal by Batus for which proxies are
being sought would, if successful, constitute a change in control
of the company.
   The proposal seeks to make Farmers' directors reconsider their
previous refusal to negotiate on Batus' takeover offer of $63 per
share, or $4.5 billion.
   Meanwhile, Farmers filed suit Monday in Nevada, where the
company is incorporated, challenging Batus's proxy solicitation.
Farmers claims Batus did not disclose enough information in the
solicitation. An April 13 hearing on the dispute was scheduled in
U.S. District Court in Reno.
   Judge Howard McKibben also said he would decide by Wednesday
whether to declare unconstitutional the Nevada Takeover Act, which
prevents stockholders from taking advantage of tender offers after
the deal is 60 days old.
   The Nevada attorney general's office contends the law is meant
to protect investors from being strung along for months during a
takeover bid.
   But Batus' attorneys argue the Nevada law conflicts with the
federal Williams Act, which gives shareholders the right to
participate in tender offers at will.
   The Kansas Insurance Company Holding Act says no one can take
control of an insurer without first obtaining regulatory approval.
   ``Control shall be presumed to exist if any person ... holds
proxies representing 10 percent or more of the voting securities,''
the law says.
   If the issue isn't resolved or the proxy solicitation isn't
``stopped immediately,'' the regulators said, the department will
be ``required to initiate the applicable administrative or legal
action.''
   The Kansas Insurance Department outlined its concerns in a
letter to Batus dated last Thursday.
   Batus said Monday that it is responding and ``strongly believes
that it will be able to satisfy the concerns raised.''
   Batus is basing its argument on the contention that its
proposal, even if successful, couldn't directly constitute a change
in control of Farmers.
   ``In fact, a change in control cannot result from a vote on our
proxy,'' Batus spokesman Wilson Wyatt said.
   Kansas is one of nine states in which Farmers owns insurers.
Regulatory approval must be obtained in each of those.
   Besides Kansas, where Farmers Group operates Farmers Insurance
Co., and California, where Farmers Group is based, the other states
are Arizona, Idaho, Illinois, Ohio, Oregon, Texas and Washington.
   Farmers, in its release Monday, noted that insurance regulators
in Texas, Illinois and Idaho have rejected or found deficient
certain required filings by Batus on grounds that they contained
inadequate information.
   BAT is a tobacco, retailing and paper-goods conglomerate that
for some time has been seeking a foothold in the U.S. financial
services market. Its American subsidiary, Batus, is based in
Louisville, Ky.
   Farmers, with about $11 billion in assets, is the nation's third
largest home and auto insurer, and the seventh largest property and
casualty insurer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880328-0277 </DOCNO>
